<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, October 16, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FURNITURE-TRENDS _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ In the '80s, Americans
``cocooned,'' as trends guru Faith Popcorn called the Yuppy
obsession with bettering their homes instead of hanging out at
bars. Now, as a new century looms, will that lifestyle change?
Popcorn, chairman of BrainReserve, a marketing consultancy to
Fortune 500 companies, had a captive audience Thursday as
retailers, designers and media from around the world flocked to
High Point for the International Home Furnishings Market. Here,
where next spring's furniture lines get their first showing, all
eyes and ears as fixed on trend watchers such as Popcorn for
predicting, as best anyone can, how home furnishings will sell. 15
inches with file photo of popcorn and new products pix. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-PARIS _ Fashion coverage from Paris. Show names:
Confirmed shows Sonia Rykiel and Martine Margiela. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-DRUG _ AUSTIN, Texas _ More than once, doctors had warned
Lizette Coleman that her chances offor a long life were not good.
In the seven years since her first treatment for breast cancer, the
disease had returned time and again until finally she told her
doctor that she wouldn't take chemotherapy for the rest of her
life; she would find a better way. In June, on the verge of signing
up for an all-natural treatment in the Bahamas, Coleman learned
about Herceptin, the first genetically engineered drug for breast
cancer, and quickly began traveling once a week to Houston to
participate in the small clinical trial of the drug. Last week, the
drug hit pharmacy shelves for the first time, an answered plea for
many more women desperate to stanch their spreading disease. (Park,
Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-CONNECTICUT _ We bid farewell to our hundreds of Pratt &AMP;
Whitney neighbors who, by virtue of the vagaries of corporate
America, find themselves moving to Hartford, Conn., and vicinity.
Good luck, Godspeed. Moving can be an unsettling business, so we
offer a few tips about life up north: Hartford's nickname is ``The
Insurance City.'' Does that tell you anything? (Reid, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITCH _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Peggy Butera, a practicing witch,
doesn't consider any question too dumb. Here she explains spells at
her Port St. Lucie spinning and weaving studio, called Dream
Weavers. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WITCH-SIDE _ It's hard to imagine the Wicked Witch of the West
casting the Stuffed Animal Sweet Dream Spell. Or the Come to Me
Love Spell. Or the Little Bo Peep Spell to Find Lost Objects. These
are the creations of Silver RavenWolf, the author of Teen Witch:
Wicca for a New Generation (Llewellyn, $12.95, 1998). (Anna, Palm
Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIVE _ ATLANTA _ In these waning days of the American Century,
it's pretty clear the country isn't perfect. For one thing,
democracy didn't come with an owner's manual. So Sacramento,
Calif., lawyer Steven Strauss has come writing to the rescue. His
book, due in stores by the end of the month, is titled: ``The
Complete Idiot's Guide to Impeaching the President.'' It figures. A
nation built on self-sufficiency, independent spirit and
enterprising pioneer grit has come to the point where we can't even
throw the bum out without a how-to book. (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ NBC's airs a decent new drama
``Trinity'' and then debuts its Saturday lineup: ``Wind on Water''
(with Bo Derek), ``The Pretender'' and ``Profiler.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FRAMPTON _ If there were a test to determine whether you're a
rock has-been, Peter Frampton would pass with flying colors.
Appeared on an album of children's songs? Check. Moved to
Nashville? Check. Started going bald? Check. Things have changed so
much for the 48-year-old rock legend, whose classic Frampton Comes
Alive remains the best-selling live album of all time, that when he
plays Friday at the Coral Sky Amphitheatre, he'll be opening for
Lynyrd Skynyrd, a band that lost much of its original membership in
a 1977 plane crash. (Passy, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MIGHTY _ Be wary of the ads for The Mighty that feature the
faces of Sharon Stone, The X-Files' Gillian Anderson, Harry Dean
Stanton and Gena Rowlands. They are merely supporting players in
this lesson-laden teen movie about growing up a misfit. (Erstein,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MIGHTY _ Review of ``The Mighty.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EVIL _ There are artists who are of their time, and there are
artists who are ahead of their time. Then there are those complete
originals who exist in a time of their own. The most tragic of them
all, if only because he was probably the most naturally gifted man
ever to walk on a sound stage, was Orson Welles. And he is
inimitable. ``Touch of Evil'' is 40 years old, but it could be
made, not yesterday or today, but tomorrow _ not that there's
anybody around with the necessary audacity and insolence. With the
exception of some leather-jacketed toughs who seem to have stepped
out of West Side Story, this movie isn't dated at all. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-MAGIC _ Practical Magic is a lumpy witches' brew of
romance, comedy, horror and twaddle. With so many batty females
flitting about _ albeit attractive ones _ sitting through the movie
is a bit like spending two hours at a pajama party. The giggles.
The hugs. The squeals. The gossip. The nicknames: ``I love you,
Jellybean.'' The horror, indeed! (Schwan, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MAGIC _ Movie review. ``Practical Magic.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-APTPUPIL _ ``Movie review. ``Apt Pupil,'' from director
of ``The Usual Suspects.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CHUCKIE _ Movie review. ``Bride of Chuckie.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-BELOVED _ Critical Mass for ``Beloved.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
