<SLUG> BC-LIVE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even `Dummies' can learn how to impeach the president
 &HT;    WITH ILLUSTRATION
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In these waning days of the American Century, it's
pretty clear the country isn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, democracy didn't come with an owner's manual.
</P>
<P>
   So Sacramento, Calif., lawyer Steven Strauss has come writing to
the rescue. His book, due in stores by the end of the month, is
titled: ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Impeaching the President.''
</P>
<P>
   It figures.
</P>
<P>
   A nation built on self-sufficiency, independent spirit and
enterprising pioneer grit has come to the point where we can't even
throw the bum out without a how-to book.
</P>
<P>
   We are overrun with advice and self-help books from a publishing
industry so certain of our ineptitude that the two hottest how-to
series are marketed by flip-flopping the old adage that the
customer is always right.
</P>
<P>
   The customer, as it turns out, is always either a dummy or a
complete idiot.
</P>
<P>
   But, please, don't take that the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `dummy' is our way of giving advice but taking the
snobbery out of it,'' says Mimi Sells, spokeswoman for IDG, the
publisher that since 1991 has sold 50 million ``Dummies'' books on
373 topics ranging from computers to sex to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, says Sells, some pretty famous Americans have been
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton read `E-Mail for Dummies' so she could
communicate with her daughter,'' says Sells. ``And this is no dumb
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of other niche publishers mint a mind-numbing number of
how-to titles each year, sending their authors off on the talk-show
circuit packing advice from tomes with titles that read like flat
jokes from a Letterman Top Ten list:
</P>
<P>
   ``Left Brain Finance 4 Right Brained People''
</P>
<P>
   ``The One-Minute Father''
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Creative Divorce''
</P>
<P>
   ``Be Your Own Dating Service''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop Screaming At The Microwave''
</P>
<P>
   How-to books for parents is an industry in itself, where each
cloying, guilt-ridden title (``How To Really Love Your Child'')
invites a rebuttal from the publisher down the street (``Loving
Your Child Is Not Enough'').
</P>
<P>
   Even the pedestrian business of putting one foot in front of the
other has spawned at least 10 how-to books, including ``Walk
Yourself Thin,'' and ``Walk Yourself Well''. Here's a sage piece of
advice from ``The 90-Day Fitness Walking Program'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk out of your door and walk for five minutes in any
direction at any speed. Then turn around and come home. That's it.
You're done.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of how-tos goes back a bit. The Bible contained this
parenting tip: ``Hear, my son, your father's instruction, and
reject not your mother's teaching.'' And Ben Franklin may have
written the first how-to book on American soil: ``Every Man His Own
Doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Carnegie _ whose 1936 ``How To Win Friends and
Influence People'' still sells steadily _ is considered the daddy
of the modern how-to.
</P>
<P>
   ``His was the first book that gave people nuts and bolts advice
on how to transform and reinvent themselves,'' says Richmond-based
writer Robert A. Carter, who has studied the how-to genre and
taught publishing at Pace University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the 1970s _ when shrinks began wrapping their
advice in best selling how-to tomes such as ``What You Always
Wanted to Know About Sex But Were Afraid to Ask'' _ that the
self-help industry became imbedded in the popular psyche,
eventually spilling over from books to talk radio and other media.
</P>
<P>
   Today, how-to books do an estimated $500 million in sales. Their
appeal, say publishers, is that they're fast studies on difficult
subjects for readers increasingly crunched for time. And they fill
a knowledge gap for Boomers who threw out many of their parents'
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   A critic of the how-to industry agrees, but she sees a downside
to getting life information from professional advisers. ``Our
parents were luckier,'' says Anne Cassidy, author of ``Parents Who
Think Too Much,'' who advocates we go back to trusting our
instincts. ``They didn't have all this research and pop psychology
to sort through. It bedevils us. It really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem: In the how-to genre, the only real checks and
balances are in the authors' bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the business and wonder if it's any more credible
today than it was at the turn of the century, when there were
self-help books that said masturbation would make you crazy,'' says
Gerald Rosen, a Seattle psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen has written pieces in professional journals citing
research that showed even when the advice in how-to books is from
professionals, and backed by research, it doesn't necessarily work
when tried at home.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers put the 1974 parents guidebook ``Toilet
Training in Less Than A Day'' to scrutiny, for instance, they found
that the program worked four out of five times when parents were
assisted by therapists.
</P>
<P>
   When parents applied the advice on their own, it failed four out
of five times.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this, too: Americans have been desperately gobbling up
hundreds of diet books for decades but, as of 1997, according to
the National Center for Health Statistics, we're fatter than ever.
</P>
<P>
   If dieters are at their width's end, imagine the befuddlement of
mom and pop trying to wrest sanity from the some 2,000 parenting
books in print.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Montgomery, a 41-year-old Decatur mother of two young
children recently paid $25 to attend a seminar by John Covey, who
helped research his brother Stephen Covey's best-selling book,
``The 7 Habits of Highly Effective Parents.''
</P>
<P>
   She was impressed, but not exactly a Covey convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read a lot of these advice books on parenting,'' she
says. ```Infants And Mothers,' `Parent Effectiveness Training,'
`When Your Child Drives You Crazy.' But I try to limit them to ones
recommended by psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's still confusing. There are too many of them. The best
are the one's that confirm what you already know, what's
instinctual.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some how-to authors concede the rash of advice books makes
them uncomfortably hot and bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen McGrath, a clinical psychologist, said she did some real
soul-searching before agreeing to write the latest in the
``Complete Idiot's'' series: ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to
Beating the Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath was afraid she'd get lumped in writers like Judith Rich
Harris, whose ``The Nurture Assumption'' has made headlines with
the startling assertion that parents don't have much effect on
their kids' development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ... books out there that may based on
research, like 'The Nurture Assumption,' but they're not written by
someone with clinical experience,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they tend to take an extreme view just to get media
attention. But they're not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, says McGrath, she was ``turned off'' by the
``Idiot's'' title, but she agreed to do the book because she
figured it would give her broader appeal than her previous, more
academic how-to: ``When Feeling Bad Is Good.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the book is broken up into chapters _ ``Coping With
Cancer Blues'' _ that are a shade glib. And she goes by ``Dr.
Ellen,'' instead of ``Dr. McGrath'': ``It's less intimidating,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   The high tide of how-tos shows few signs of ebbing _ and why
should it?
</P>
<P>
   Two advice books _ ``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution,'' and
``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff...And It's All Small Stuff'' _ seem
permanently camped on best seller lists. And last year, combined,
the ``Dummies'' and ``Complete Idiots'' series did more than $130
million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The next ``Dummies'' title is ``Herbal Remedies for Dummies.''
Says ``Dummies'' spokeswoman Sells: ``We're publishing new titles
as fast as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as fast, in fact, as the Idiot's savants at Macmillan
Publishing, where _ when editors get through with Clinton and
impeachment _ they plan to dumb down another pretty ripe subject:
God.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in bookstores next year: ``The Complete Idiot's Guide
to the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
