</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revised `Evil' restores some of Welles' genius
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are artists who are of their time, and there are artists
who are ahead of their time. Then there are those complete
originals who exist in a time of their own. The most tragic of them
all, if only because he was probably the most naturally gifted man
ever to walk on a sound stage, was Orson Welles.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences couldn't get a grip on him any more than movie
executives. The fact that he never had a hit movie, and that he
perversely needed to insult and madden the people who provided the
money to make movies, sealed his professional doom.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's safely dead, Welles' films have rolled out in
restored versions every few years _ ``Citizen Kane,'' ``Othello,''
``It's All True'' and now a new, slightly revised print of the 1958
``Touch of Evil,'' in which all of his jagged, impressionistic
brilliance is on display.
</P>
<P>
   Some great directors are easy to imitate _ look at Alfred
Hitchcock and the nihilistic hash made by people who copy his shots
and chilly misanthropy but can't come near his underlying feeling
for fear.
</P>
<P>
   But Welles is inimitable. ``Touch of Evil'' is 40 years old, but
it could be made, not yesterday or today, but tomorrow _ not that
there's anybody around with the necessary audacity and insolence.
With the exception of some leather-jacketed toughs who seem to have
stepped out of West Side Story, this movie isn't dated at all.
</P>
<P>
   Some background: Welles shot ``Touch of Evil'' in the winter of
1957 quickly, authoritatively, on schedule and on budget in
memorably tawdry Venice, Calif. Universal didn't like the picture
and took it away from Welles after the first preview. In spite of
the fact that it had good performances by two big stars and was in
a commercial genre, Universal treated the movie as if it was
something to be scraped off its corporate shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Welles never made another movie in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The version in circulation for the past 15 years has been the
preview print that Welles didn't have a chance to fine-tune. The
difference in running times between the old print and the new one
is precisely three minutes, and that's because the credits were
taken from the legendary three-minute tracking shot that opens the
film and put at the end.
</P>
<P>
   There is no new footage. What the great editor and sound
designer Walter Murch (``Apocalypse Now,'' ``The Conversation'')
has done is follow a 58-page memo that Welles fired off to
Universal after he was taken off the picture and do some internal
reediting.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Leigh always seemed to disappear in the old version, and
this cut makes a much stronger, symbiotic connection between her
and her newlywed husband, played by Charlton Heston, a Mexican cop
struggling to find a killer in a nightmare border town ruled by
Welles' Sheriff Hank Quinlan.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh and Heston do what they're asked to do very well in their
stock parts. The attention is naturally diverted by the billed and
unbilled cameo parts _ Marlene Dietrich, Joseph Cotton and other
old Welles cronies from the Mercury Theater days.
</P>
<P>
   Welles gave himself the best part. With his rheumy eyes, vast
bulk and unshaven jowls, Hank Quinlan is a grotesque, fascinating
beached whale of a man, a great detective and a bad cop who seems
to have been marinated in corruption. With the exception of his
Falstaff in Chimes at Midnight, it's Welles' best performance.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, the new print is an improvement. Janet Leigh doesn't
disappear for half the movie, the plot makes more sense, and the
suspense of the last sequence is ratcheted up a little more. On the
other hand, Henry Mancini's sleazy, evocative score has been
severely cut back, which is a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touch of Evil'' remains what it's always been: The best
B-movie ever, by the greatest director of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
