<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-CONNECTICUT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Button up, Pratt folks. `Insurance City' is ice cold
 &HT;    By By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ We bid farewell to our hundreds of Pratt
&AMP; Whitney neighbors who, by virtue of the vagaries of corporate
America, find themselves moving to Hartford, Conn., and vicinity.
Good luck, Godspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Moving can be an unsettling business, so we offer a few tips
about life up north:
</P>
<P>
   Hartford's nickname is ``The Insurance City.'' Does that tell
you anything?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a city known for nightlife,'' says Pat Seremet,
columnist at the Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   How about cost of living?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of Hartford as having New York costs without New York
amenities,'' says Seremet. ``A nice three-bedroom house will cost
around $200,000.''
</P>
<P>
   At least you'll get the change of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Keep those Florida clothes because you'll need them for 8 or 10
weeks during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But you can toss your bathing suit because the nearest beaches
are 40 miles away. Avoid swimming in the Connecticut River. It's
like the Lake Worth Lagoon: long, dirty and full of fish with
lesions.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other relevant considerations:
</P>
<P>
   Waterfront vibrancy _ Neither Hartford nor West Palm Beach has a
functioning waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Pro baseball _ No pro ball club in Hartford, none to speak of in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   State song _ Connecticut: Yankee Doodle. Florida: Old Folks at
Home. (Now there's truth in advertising.)
</P>
<P>
   Average January temperature _ 42 degrees. This can be deceiving.
Wind-chill factors below zero are common from December to March.
Spend these months looking at old photos of South Florida, where 73
degrees is a cool day in February.
</P>
<P>
   Driving _ Connecticut drivers are mostly polite and unarmed.
Speeders will be caught by state troopers, and speeding fines are
humongous.
</P>
<P>
   Museums _ Mark Twain's house. Hey, it's not New York.
</P>
<P>
   Theater _ Good off-Broadway productions and serious theater at
the Hartford Stage and Bushnell Theater. You'll never miss the
BRITT.
</P>
<P>
   Civic pride _ The annual Hooker Day parade commemorates the
city's founder, Thomas Hooker. Residents throw off inhibitions,
dress as bikers, parade their lawn mowers. Great fun.
</P>
<P>
   Things to do in Hartford on Saturday _ Go to New York or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Student-teacher ratio _ 14.4 to 1. Now there's some good news.
Florida's student-teacher ratio is 19.1 to 1. And Connecticut
teacher salaries average a tad over $50,000 versus $33,000 in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Chief crops _ Christmas trees and mushrooms. Martha Stewart
lives downstate so you'll have plenty of ideas about what to do
with all those old Christmas trees and mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   State tax _ Here, none. There, 4.5 percent top income tax
bracket and property taxes are pretty high.
</P>
<P>
   But forget the high taxes, here's the best thing about Hartford.
No drawbridges.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
