</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Muddled `Practical Magic' tosses too much into the pot
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Practical Magic is a lumpy witches' brew of romance, comedy,
horror and twaddle.
</P>
<P>
   With so many batty females flitting about _ albeit attractive
ones _ sitting through the movie is a bit like spending two hours
at a pajama party. The giggles. The hugs. The squeals. The gossip.
The nicknames: ``I love you, Jellybean.''
</P>
<P>
   The horror, indeed!
</P>
<P>
   This is a story of witches in search of love. It's risky
business, since when one of them finds true love, their man croaks,
and not like a frog. It's a curse dating back to the Puritans.
</P>
<P>
   These are basically nice witches, however, and an underlying
theme of the movie is female empowerment _ without the male
bashing. Still, most men in the audience will wish they'd stayed
home to watch that John Wayne flick on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Owens clan has numbered witches for centuries. That's not
easy. Sally and Gillian Owens grew up, well, different. Orphans,
they lived with their spinster aunts in a rambling Victorian house
in a New England fishing village. The aunts taught the girls
``practical magic'' to help them with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sally (Sandra Bullock) wants none of the witchcraft business
when she grows up. She marries happily and has two kids. Alas, the
curse kicks in, and her husband gets run over by a truck.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Gillian (Nicole Kidman) enjoys casting
``spells'' over men, although she does so in the traditional way _
by wiggling her hips. She escapes home and lives fast with the
wrong crowd, turning into a bit of a slut along the way.
</P>
<P>
   When she's threatened by one of her seedy beaus (Goran Visnjic),
Sally rides her ``broomstick'' to the rescue. The girls dig into
their bag of witch's tricks to take care of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem, namely the beau, isn't done for yet. Talk about
toil and trouble. A chain of spooky events leads to a cop (Aiden
Quinn) showing up on the island to sort things out. This, of
course, gives Sally a chance to brave the curse and find true love
once again.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Alice Hoffman, the movie version takes its
cues from Arsenic and Old Lace, The Exorcist, Bewitched and your
average soap opera. The two eccentric aunts, played by the always
amusing Diane Wiest and Stockard Channing, provide the touch of Old
Lace.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, there's a possession. And an exorcism, during which
the townswomen who once scorned the Owens clan come together in
sisterly solidarity. Bewitched shows up in the form of practical
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the movie is lighthearted without being funny. The
tale takes a bit too long to set up, and too many ingredients are
tossed into the pot to make for a coherent or compelling story
line.
</P>
<P>
   In both a visual and narrative sense, the film has the feeling
of clutter. Director Griffin Dunne rarely shoots a frame that isn't
jumbled or simply busy with people and objects. That's not
necessarily a bad thing, and he does evoke a nostalgic, storybook
feeling to a movie about witches.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bullock and Kidman add more than beauty to their roles. We
know Kidman can get down and dirty from her work in Malice and To
Die For. And Bullock is more mature and determined, less passive or
frazzled _ less cute _ than in past performances
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, a movie with so many different elements
lacks the one ingredient that would make it whole. Practical Magic
lacks magic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
