<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITCH-SIDE16-COX     10-15 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCH-SIDE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do you believe in `magick'? this Wiccan lives it
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine the Wicked Witch of the West casting the
Stuffed Animal Sweet Dream Spell.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Come to Me Love Spell. Or the Little Bo Peep Spell to
Find Lost Objects.
</P>
<P>
   These are the creations of Silver RavenWolf, the author of Teen
Witch: Wicca for a New Generation (Llewellyn, $12.95, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   The book is a witchcraft primer, something of a Wicca 101 for
kids, with the first two pages devoted to calming down parents who
discover the book in their child's room. (``Okay _ you've picked up
this book, and you're going through minor coronary arrest.'')
</P>
<P>
   RavenWolf, who lives in Mechanicsburg, Pa., has four children,
ages 12 to 19. They helped make up the spells.
</P>
<P>
   Witchcraft, commonly known as ``Wicca'' from the Old English
word for ``witch,'' is similar to Native American nature-based
religions, practioners say. Central to the religion is the Wiccan
Rede: ``Do what you like, so long as you harm none.'' And a rule
most Wiccans follow _ the three-fold law of return _ says that all
deeds, good and evil, return to the doer magnified three times.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes a chapter called ``The craft: What it is and
what it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   What it isn't, RavenWolf says, is flying on brooms, worshipping
the devil (Wiccans do not believe in Satan), attacking people and
animals or eating babies (``Yuckie!'').
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the book consists of spells _ or ``focused prayer''
_ as RavenWolf puts it.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Call Me Spell, and the Don't Call Me Spell (which
involves a piece of paper with the person's name crossed out, a
handful of pepper and several chants). And the Elf Locker Spell, to
keep people from breaking in.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a spell to keep people from bothering you on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it wasn't needed here. RavenWolf answered the
following questions by e-mail. Q. Were you a teen witch? A. Yes. I
began at age 13, finding my own way. My mother died when I was 17,
which pushed me further into alternative studies. Q. With this
book, are you recruiting? A. No. What I'm trying to do is stop the
misinformation on several levels. I tried to write the kind of book
that I would have been looking for when I was 13. Q. Why does
witchcraft suit you better than any other faith? A. I like the
freedom of Wicca, the connection to nature, the ability to work to
enhance my life no matter what the difficulty or goal, and the
balanced masculine-feminine spirituality. Q. How are kids hearing
about witchcraft in the first place? A. In many cases, kids seem to
know that magick (she spells it with a `k' so it's not confused
with a magic act) is inherently real even though they've been told
it is not, and therefore start looking for it. That's what happened
to me. In some cases, the Christian propaganda on how negative the
Craft, actually makes kids curious. You know, don't tell a kid what
not to do because they will therefore do it. So, some come that
way, and then are surprised that the Craft isn't what they'd heard
it was. Then, there have been some major pushes (interestingly
enough) from television and the film media. Book sales on real
magick skyrocketed immediately after the movie The Craft, and then
with Sabrina, the Teenage Witch. With Practical Magic coming up and
the Charmed show, sales will most likely show an improvement. Some
buy just to ``see,'' where others buy to practice. Q. A new TV
show, a new movie about witches _ what makes witches ``cool''? A. I
wish I had an intelligent answer for this one, but I have no idea
why the general community is suddenly focused on WitchCraft. The
religion is very positive, nonthreatening, and we have been working
for the last 20 years to educate the public as to what WitchCraft
is, and is not. Q. What do teens find the hardest to understand
about witchcraft? A. Due to the overabundance of Hollywood trash
material, the hardest thing teens find to understand is the
difference between real magick and Hollywood magick. I've
especially noticed this with the newer generation that has seen
special effects in movies and can't discern that those special
effects are orchestrated. This is scary on many levels _ not just
when dealing with the Craft. Q. How are real witches different from
the ones we see on TV? (Tabatha, Samantha, etc.) A. I wish I could
wiggle my nose and get my housecleaning done. Q. How do your kids
explain witchcraft to people they meet? A. My children have
experienced discrimination about their faith. My oldest daughter
had her arm slammed in a locker by a kid. In the past, some have
taunted my children. One group of children waited after school and
physically accosted my other daughter. Q. What would you say to a
teen who gets into witchcraft because they think it is dark and
wicked? Or who thinks they can use it to jump into Satanism or
something? A. Don't bother. We don't go there. Q. Any statistics,
demographics on how many Americans are into witchcraft and who they
are? Is it becoming more popular, and why? A. The statistics of the
Wiccan/Pagan Press Alliance indicate that approximately one in 10
Americans are involved in some type of alternative spirituality.
(Note: Teen Witch says one in five in the U.S. have dabbled in it.)
The popularity of Sabrina, Charmed, and Practical Magic indicate
that the American public is hungry for a positive way of life that
does not require you to expend money and can fulfill the
spirituality in each individual. Q. In your book, you say that when
people ask what Wicca is, you think of a thousand wonderful things.
What are, say, five of them? A. 1. Wicca provides a way of
self-empowerment and empowerment through the divine. 2. In Wicca,
there is always something to do, regardless of your situation. You
are never left thinking, ``Why me?'' 3. Wicca provides the road to
feminine spirituality. 4. Wicca does not need a middleman to tell
you what is or is not the right thing to do. 5. Wicca is a
life-affirming, nature belief system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
