</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCHES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida witch takes mystery out of magic
 &HT;    (Editors: See WITCH-SIDE16-COX)
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Peggy Butera, a practicing witch, doesn't
consider any question too dumb.
</P>
<P>
   She's explaining spells at her Port St. Lucie spinning and
weaving studio, called Dream Weavers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good magic would be spells to get a new job, improve your
financial situation,'' she says. ``Some use spells to make
themselves more lovable.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use a spell to make someone love you, that would be gray
magic,'' she says, sitting at a small table, knotting the fringe on
a shawl.
</P>
<P>
   And a spell to get someone to sleep with you just once?
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be gray magic, not good,'' says Butera, 44.
``Witchcraft is a tool,'' she explains, her voice soft and patient.
``People can put curses on other people, but what goes around comes
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witches, more than most people, think of the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention a witch and most people think of actress Margaret
Hamilton in The Wizard of Oz. Butera's face is not green, her nose
has no warts. She says she's been a witch all her life, but eight
years ago she aligned herself with a mentor, a woman named Tzipora,
who introduced her to the world of spells and ceremonies, harmony
and happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Joe, is schooled in witchcraft. Her daughter,
Nicole, 21, has a mentor, and son, Joey, 23, has studied.
</P>
<P>
   Witchcraft is a lifestyle, she explains, involving the study of
traditions and learning how to live in harmony in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a movie about witches comes out, such as the upcoming
Practical Magic, Butera will see it. Soon to follow, she says, is a
new wave of interest in witchcraft. When The Crat came out a few
years ago, she was running a metaphysical store and was flooded
with people asking questions, looking for books.
</P>
<P>
   Butera's 16-member witch ``family'' meets in Port St. Lucie
during full moons and new moons, plus high holidays such as
Samhain, which is commonly linked to Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a celebration of the final harvest marked by the first
killing frost,'' she explains. ``And it's a new year, the start of
a new season.''
</P>
<P>
   Witchcraft's beliefs are similar to North American Indian
traditions and include the use of herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about worshiping the old gods of nature, the Earth,
the moon,'' she explains. ``It has survived for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you do has layers of meaning. The media has
convinced people that spells and magic are the alluring part of
witchcraft.''
</P>
<P>
   A witchcraft ceremony is meant to draw energy from a god and
direct it toward a purpose, such as healing. This ritual can last
two hours and involves chanting and holding hands. A witch's tools
include incense, candles, a ceremonial knife, a bell and statues of
gods and goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   A spell is created, she says, ``if you put enough energy into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She offers an example of a spell she used. Her son Joey wanted
to try skydiving four years ago. She had a typical mother's worries
about the adventure and created a spell to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   When Joey got to the airfield, the money to pay for the lessons
was missing from his glove compartment. He had no choice but to
abandon the plan. But on his way home, the money reappeared in the
glove box.
</P>
<P>
   ``People fear what they don't understand,'' she's saying,
methodically tying knots in the shawl. If being a witch is right
for you, she says, you'll know quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the people who actively start studying witchcraft
and say, `I feel like I'm coming home.'
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
