<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIGHTY16-COX     10-15 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGHTY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Film has mighty fine lessons for kids, adults
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be wary of the ads for The Mighty that feature the faces of
Sharon Stone, The X-Files' Gillian Anderson, Harry Dean Stanton and
Gena Rowlands. They are merely supporting players in this
lesson-laden teen movie about growing up a misfit.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Rodman Philbrick's Freak the Mighty, a popular novel
for young adults, it has been brought to the screen with some
success by director Peter Chelsom (Hear My Song), despite its
heavy-handed assaults on our tear ducts and its tangential dips
into melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it is an improvement over the mawkish Simon Birch,
which it superficially resembles. It, too, has a young, disabled
main character, Kevin Dillon (Kieran Culkin), with a degenerative
disease that causes his internal organs to grow faster than his
bones. But Kevin has learned to cope by emphasizing his mental
facilities, devouring books and wielding a heady vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after moving into a low-rent Cincinnati home with his
doting single mother (Stone), Kevin meets Maxwell Kane (Elden
Henson), a lumpish, slow-witted, brawny but gentle classmate. ``You
need brains, and I need legs,'' reasons Kevin, and so they bond, as
Max hoists Kevin on his shoulders. Together, they roam the streets
as Freak the Mighty, gaining a new respect from their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin becomes Max's reading tutor, turning him on to literature
through the stories of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round
Table. Together, they do good deeds and vanquish bullies, but Max
remains under the dark cloud of his violent felon father.
</P>
<P>
   About midway, the movie loses a lot of its gentle urban fable
quality, trading it in for unlikely melodrama, when the father
escapes from prison and abducts his son. It is the weakest part of
The Mighty, an overwrought segment that almost negates the goodwill
the movie had been building.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the movie hangs on the credibility of the two young
actors, and they deliver impressively. Henson projects a palpable
vulnerability as Max, haunted by dark memories, wounded by cruel
classmates and desperate for friendship. He is well-complemented by
Culkin _ Macauley's younger brother _ as Kevin, who uses his
intelligence and sarcasm as defensive shields, masking an
emotional, as well as physical, fragility underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is sheer earnestness as Kevin's put-upon mother, an
un-glam-orous and rather thankless role that she manages to handle
well enough. Anderson also seems intent on image-changing, playing
an alcoholic housewife with a few scenery-chewing moments. That's
more than you can say for Rowlands and Stanton, who are all but
irrelevant as Max's doting, and often puzzled, grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to admire the way The Mighty doesn't fit into any of
the usual Hollywood formulas, though that was undoubtedly a factor
in its sitting on the studio's shelf for almost a year. Surely, it
is intended to reach a wider audience than young teens, but the
heavy-handedness of Charles Leavitt's screenplay argues against
that.
</P>
<P>
   For youngsters, there are messages galore about the importance
of friendship, the trap of assumptions about the disabled and the
value of reading and using one's imagination. Come to think of it,
those aren't bad notions for adults to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
