<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-DRUG16-COX     10-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUG16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors say drug not for everyone
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than once, doctors had warned Lizette
Coleman that her chances offor a long life were not good. In the
seven years since her first treatment for breast cancer, the
disease had returned time and again, sneaking into organs and bones
from her liver to her lungs until finally she told her doctor that
she wouldn't take chemotherapy for the rest of her life; she would
find a better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we were going nowhere with chemo,'' says Coleman,
38, of WestlakeWest Lake Hills. ``It froze the disease but it
didn't go away. I told him, 'I'm looking for the cure.'''
</P>
<P>
   In June, on the verge of signing up for an all-natural treatment
in the Bahamas, Coleman learned about Herceptin, the first
genetically engineered drug for breast cancer, and quickly began
traveling once a week to Houston to participate in the small
clinical trial of the drug at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. Last
week, the drug hit pharmacy shelves for the first time, an answered
plea for many more women desperate to stanch their spreading
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken 10 percent of the cancer which is in my liver . . .
and on my spine also,'' Coleman says, unable to mask her
hyperactivity, an exuberance she attributes to the Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was drawn in a lottery of women wanting to be among the
first to try Herceptin. ``I always ask the doctor to assure me that
this drug is working and he says 'It's working.'''
</P>
<P>
   Herceptin is not the cure for breast cancer, it only works for
about one-fourth of women with the disease and it offers only a
small boost over other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only women whose cancer has come back after multiple
rounds of chemotherapy can get Herceptin. But its release marks a
milestone in the history of cancer drugs, raising the bar for
future research and development. From now on, it's genes they're
targeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of therapy of cancer is going to be in the genetic
management of the disease, in terms of prevention and treatment,''
says William Thames, director of pharmacy at Southwest Regional
Cancer Center in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've been waiting for for a long time,'' says
Austin oncologist Robert Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's precedent-setting and . . . based on the molecular
knowledge of a cancer, and I think that makes it different _ as
opposed to a lot of therapies in the past that have been quite
honestly hit-or-miss,'' says Richard Elledge, assistant professor
of medical oncology at the UT Health Science Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Herceptin is not the first gene-based drug for cancer, but it is
the most anticipated. An impressive coalition of activists,
bureaucrats and some of the world's top breast oncologists worked
with Genentech Inc., the San Francisco biotechnology firm behind
the drug, to get it in patients' hands quickly. As Herceptin was on
the verge of FDA U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval last
month, a journalist hawked a book on the drug's story on national
television and Genentech employees prepared to work around the
clock to get Herceptin shipped to doctors way ahead of its
anticipated release.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough with Herceptin goes back to discoveries madein
the early 1980s, when scientists identified a gene called HER-2. In
the breast tissue of some women, HER-2 produces too much of a
protein who's job it is to tell the cells to multiply. With too
much of the protein, those cells multiply faster than they should
and cause cancer tumors to grow to dangerous levels. Women with
this genetic defect _ called overexpression _ are more likely to
have an aggressive, life-threatening form of breast cancer that
attacks them early and resists chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering the protein that HER-2 overproduces,
scientists created an antibody that attaches itself to the protein
and blocks the signal to the cell to multiply. By interrupting the
growth of the cells, the antibody can slow or stop the progression
of breast cancer and make the disease more receptive to
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   But with the hype about Herceptin growing, many doctors are
urging women to temper their hope.
</P>
<P>
   HER-2 is just one of scores of genes that are factors in the
spread of breast cancer, and it causes overexpression in only 25 to
30 percent of women with breast cancer. The antibody, dubbed
Herceptin by Genentech, will only help women who test positive for
overexpression of the protein, and it is only available to women
whose cancer outlasts multiple rounds of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people who have been involved in this have been
guilty of overdramatizing this event,'' says Elledge, who has
worked with the drug's clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors describe the clinical impact of Herceptin as modest. It
didn't keep many of the women who participated in the clinical
trials from eventually dying, prolonging their lives by an average
of several months. But for those who have had the chance to take
Herceptin, there is no denying its near-mythical impact.
</P>
<P>
   Two months shy of Marsha Geib's fifth year free of cancer _ when
doctors begin to think of the disease as cured _ it reappeared in
her breast and chest wall. The Midland teacher resumed round after
round of chemotherapy, treatments that caused her to lose dangerous
amounts of weight, suffer around-the-clock nausea and lose feeling
in her hands and feet. Eventually, she took to a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Geib took her first Herceptin treatment at the
Allison Cancer Center in Midland, hopeful it would be a drug she
could live with. By most accounts, the side effects are relatively
minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got three kids and I need to be here,'' said Geib, who is
48. ``I really feel this is going to be the drug and going to help
a lot of us get through these tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Paz Polanco's breast cancer progressed much faster. In three
years, she's had three kinds of chemotherapy, a mastectomy and a
bone marrow transplant, but none could stop invasions of her spine,
brain and liver. When clinical trials were expanded, Polanco drove
to San Antonio to take Herceptin. Friday, she took her treatment at
the Southwest Regional Cancer Center for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Propped back in a red leather recliner in a row of chairs
reserved for chemotherapy patients, Polanco said she already feels
better than she did during her three bone-aching cycles of
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hope and there is something out there for everyone,''
says Polanco, 50, of Austin. ``If I can be a witness to some of
them, I want to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
