<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN16-COX     10-15 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Mentor's belief in us forces us to believe in ourselves
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hear they're doing a remake of All About Eve, the 1950 classic
about the fawning starlet who ingratiates herself to the reigning
diva, Bette Davis, only to dethrone her. It's a great movie, even
if it bears no resemblance to the real working relationships of
women. But who needs reality? Who would flock to a flick called
Mentors?
</P>
<P>
   In Eve's universe, I should be hot-pink with chagrin right now,
because my former boss, one Laura Archer Pulfer, has beaten me to
the punch in publishing her first book.
</P>
<P>
   During the eight years I worked for her at Cincinnati Magazine,
Laura wasn't even a full-time writer. Her official title was editor
and publisher. Her unofficial titles were myriad: Friend.
Cheerleader. Wordsmith. Giver of good counsel. Keeper of the
talking toilet seat. (Trust me, it was hilarious.)
</P>
<P>
   Yep, I should be steaming mad. Not only has my former editor
written a book, she has written a wonderful book, funny and wise
and pointed and passionate (especially when the subject is kids).
You can catch her Saturday at 2 p.m. at Books &AMP; Co. in Kettering,
sharing selections from I Beg to Differ: Politically Incorrect,
Proudly Midwestern, Potentially Funny, a collection of her columns
from National Public Radio and the Cincinnati Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Why am I thrilled for Laura instead of properly jealous? It must
be her fault. She was my editor during my formative years in this
business, and she should have taught me how to get ahead by
stepping all over people and taking credit for their work. Instead
she went around town telling everybody that her job consisted of
taking ``prolonged lunches and raising Chia pets and collecting
congratulations'' for the accomplishments of her staff. Whenever
something went right, it was to our credit; when something went
wrong, it was her responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, when she called the staff together to tell us
about her breast cancer diagnosis, she was the one who ended up
reassuring us. Today, as a vocal and eloquent survivor, she is
still the one doing the reassuring, although now in very public
forums _ in her columns, before packed auditoriums and even once on
Fountain Square. ``When I first got breast cancer, I never thought,
'Why me?' '' she said. ``I understood 'Why me?' It was to be as
open as possible and to show up looking as healthy as possible any
time I'm asked.''
</P>
<P>
   The message around Cincinnati Magazine was clear: Be a good
person first, lead a full life outside the office, and it will
follow, as the night the day, you will be a good employee. Maybe
all of us alumni should file a class-action suit against Laura, or
at least act real snotty next time we see her, for giving such bum
advice for women of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, maybe nobody ever set her the right example.
Consider the book's dedication: ``To the memory of my first editor
and mentor, Hope Strong, who taught me what I needed to know to
make my living as a writer. And to my mother, Betty Rose Archer,
who taught me everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong hired Laura straight out of high school to work at the
Lima News during her college summers. That first day, the editor
``leaned across the desk and said, 'Listen, Toots, I just want you
to know this ain't no tea and cookies outfit,' '' Laura recalls.
Strong sported New York fashions and wrote about issues such as
battered women long before it was stylish to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Strong must have seen some raw talent in the teen, ``but believe
you me it was raw ,'' Laura said. ``It made all the difference . .
. having an editor who was kind but always made me do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. For a writer, it makes all the difference, having
an editor whose belief in you forces you to believe in yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, there was a woman like that in my life
once, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
