<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER:  
 BRITRAIL SENIOR PARTY PASS CUTS FARES 25 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're traveling solo or in a group, there are
discounts, deals and special offers just for the mature traveler.
Here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITRAIL SENIOR PARTY PASS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BritRail hasn't forgotten a thing for mature travelers _
including a Senior Party Pass for those ages 60 and older that's
priced as much as 25 percent lower than the regular BritRail Senior
Pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Party Pass permits each senior in a party of three to travel
any four days in a month first class for $224, or $202 for each of
four people in a party. These rates compare to $269 for a single
senior BritRail pass.
</P>
<P>
   To travel any eight days in one month the three-party price is
$325, or $293 for four people (compared to $390 for an individual).
</P>
<P>
   The price per senior in a three-person party for one month?
$608; the four-person Party Pass price is $548.
</P>
<P>
   It's all detailed in ``Britain's Heritage Cities,'' a brochure
that helps the independent traveler plan routes and stops for major
events in the cities and to decide which treasure houses and
gardens are available.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at the end of October in Stratford-on-Avon is the
English Music Festival, and from November through the end of
September 1999 the Royal Shakespeare Company will be performing.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of November, unique Christmas shopping is promised in
York's City Centre.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the brochure, call (888) 424-3731, or visit their
Web site at www.raileurope.com.
</P>
<P>
   To book, call your travel agent or BritRail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DELTA FLIES SKYWISE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delta is flying high with its updated program for mature
travelers. Now called The Delta SkyWise program (formerly ``Senior
Select Savings Plus''), those ages 62 and older can enroll for $40
to get discounted zone airfares to nearly 300 U.S. destinations.
</P>
<P>
   If you're accustomed to flying with friends or relatives, you
can also enroll up to three companions of any age for $25 a person.
</P>
<P>
   While the pricing is good, there are restrictions, including
capacity control, non-refundable fares, blackout dates and such.
Key provisions call for reservations made 14 days in advance with
tickets purchased at the time, round-trip purchase and a required
Saturday-night stay.
</P>
<P>
   Travel must be booked by June 12, 1999, started by June 26,
1999, and completed by June 30, 1999. If you had enrolled in Senior
Select Savings Plus, that program is cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   There are also deal sweeteners: discounts at Radisson and
Swissotel hotels, Alamo, Avis, Hertz and National rental cars, and
Delta Queen, Norwegian and Royal Caribbean cruise lines as well as
select Delta Vacation packages.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new SkyWise program, Delta still offers 10
percent discounts for those ages 62 and older on most posted fares
and has the ``Young at Heart'' senior coupon books that cost $596
for four coupons.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Delta or visit their Web site at
www.delta-air.com/SkyWise. To enroll, call (800) 325-3750 and be
prepared to give your date of birth, SkyMiles number, Social
Security number and credit-card information.
</P>
<P>
   If you are enrolling companions, you'll need their SkyMiles
numbers and dates of birth, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COAST TO COAST FOR $254 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak offers many ways to travel America, but its Fall Explore
America Fares provide a leisurely way to travel coast to coast and
back for about $254, which includes the 15 percent senior discount
for travelers ages 62 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket structure starts with the regular fare for traveling
one region at $179, two adjacent regions at $239 or the entire
country at $299. If you want to explore just Florida, the price is
$69.
</P>
<P>
   Mature travelers take 15 percent off these rates, as they can on
all full-fare Amtrak tickets, or special one-way fares.
</P>
<P>
   The Fall Explore America rates are on sale through Nov. 14 for
travel through Dec. 17. Tickets are non-refundable and require
14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Work with your travel agent or call (800) 872-7245. You can also
visit their Web site at www.amtrak.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALASKA SIGHTSEEING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gray Line of Alaska makes seeing the Great State easier _ and
cheaper _ for those traveling on their own or adding extra
sightseeing days before or after cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Two popular tours eligible for the senior discounts are the
Portage Glacier Cruise aboard the mv Ptarmigan, south of Anchorage,
and a visit to Gold Dredge No. 8 at Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   The three Portage Glacier tours are a 10-hour tour that combines
the highlights of Anchorage with the cruise for $77; a seven-hour
cruise tour that includes a stop at Alyeska Ski Resort for an
optional tram ride to the top of the mountain for $60; and a
one-hour tour for those with their own transportation to the cruise
dock for $25.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Dredge No. 8, the only dredge open to the public and a
National Historic Site, has two tours eligible for the senior
discount.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour Discover the Gold Tour for $57 includes a miner's
lunch and a chance to try your hand at panning gold. An eight-hour
tour that combines a tour of the Dredge site and a four-hour
Sternwheeler Cruise on the Chena and Tanana rivers costs $57.
</P>
<P>
   A senior discount of 10 percent is applied to all sightseeing
tours offered by Gray Line of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   All these tours are available from mid-May to the end of
September. For reservations, call (800) 544-2206. For brochures,
call (800) 628-2449.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRY BEFORE YOU BUY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For seniors looking to try an active adult community lifestyle,
Del Webb's Vacation Getaway packages have been extended to their
Spruce Creek Communities in Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   For $99, a mature traveler age 55 or older can stay three days
in a furnished villa, get one free round of golf and make use of
the recreational amenities like the fitness center, bocce,
billiards, tennis courts and swimming pool. Travel companions must
be 18 or older. For reservation information, call (888) 932-2639.
</P>
<P>
   Many Del Webb communities in tourist markets such as Phoenix,
Ariz.; Las Vegas, Nev.; Hilton Head, S.C.; Georgetown, Texas; and
Palm Desert, Calif., offer similar Vacation Getaway programs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL'S HOTEL DEAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Dan Hotel chain offers its Silver Star promotion at Dan
Panorama in Tel Aviv, Dan Panorama in Haifa or the new Dan Pearl in
Jerusalem for guests ages 65 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Show your passport, driver's license or any document with your
date of birth and claim a 15 percent discount off room rates and
food bills through April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This offer is valid Sunday-Thursday in Haifa and Jerusalem and
weekends in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Contact your travel agent or call (800) 223-7773.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For mature travelers it's the best time of life to get up and
go! The aim of this column is to help make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the bargains and special trips that will be
reported on are for 49ers-plus, the information can help younger
travelers spot values too.
</P>
<P>
   Mature travelers should remember that wherever they go, whatever
they do, they should always ask for the senior-citizen discount,
even if one isn't posted. That's one of the main privileges of
being among the ``chronologically gifted'' who are 50 or over. &QL; 
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
</P>
<P>
   The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &UR; ----- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
