<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8439 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-15 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Oct. 15, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-MITCHELL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Friday already has meaning for
former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine. It's the
first birthday of his son. It also is the day Mitchell, 65, will
learn whether he is the recipient of the Nobel prize for his role
in brokering the Northern Ireland peace agreement. By PAUL
GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco Examiner-KTVU poll
shows Republican Dan Lungren trailing Democrat Gray Davis for the
governorship of California. Davis remains favored by 48 percent of
those surveyed _ the same percentage of voters backing him in three
polls since July. Lungren is backed by just 42 percent of those
surveyed with two weeks left in the campaign. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS-COMPUTERS (San Antonio) _ The ``boys only'' sign has moved
from math and science classrooms to technology, a key to the
information age, a national study has found. Girls still trail boys
in math and science achievement, and an emerging gender gap exists
in the number and difficulty of computer classes they take, the
report said. By JEANNE RUSSELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Part of me wishes that all the
workers on Earth would call in sick tomorrow and keep calling in
sick every day until they use up all the sick days that their
employers offer. It would wake up all those companies that have
antiquated sick leave policies _ policies that essentially
discriminate against dedicated workers. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BELOVED (San Francisco) _ An unrelenting story of
what slavery did to one woman and the people caught up in her life,
``Beloved'' left those in the cast _ Oprah Winfrey, Danny Glover
and Thandie Newton _ to deal with memories from their past. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-MUSIC-PROFILE (Undated) _ Many musicians point to a
defining moment when they knew absolutely what they wanted to do
with their lives. Butch Vig, drummer/producer with the group
Garbage, remembers his: It happened in the late 60s when he saw the
Who perform on television. The band's drummer wreaked havoc on the
set and a little kid in Wisconsin got hooked on the spirit of rock
'n' roll. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY-GARCIA (San Francisco) _ The bitter monetary dispute
between the widow of Grateful Dead leader Jerry Garcia and his
former wife is coming to a rapid close after both sides reached an
agreement that would pay Carolyn ``Mountain Girl'' Adams Garcia
about $1 million. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   COKIE-ROBERTS (San Francisco) _ After 10 months of reporting and
analyzing the White House sex scandal, Cokie Roberts says she feels
``imprisoned by the story, both literally and figuratively.''
Despite being pinned down inside the Beltway, Roberts' reach has
extended nationwide with the publication of ``We Are Our Mothers'
Daughters,'' her reflection on and celebration of women. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROWAVE-FOOD (Undated) _ Making frittate _ Italy's answer to
omelets _ takes mere minutes in the microwave without sacrificing
the superior taste of a dish that takes longer to cook
conventionally. And the results are lush. Creamy eggs hold enticing
chunks of whatever one chooses to add. As with omelets, one usual
addition is cheese, which can be the cook's choice. By ANN STEINER
and CICI WILLIAMSON.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-WINE (Undated) _ They don't call it the Grape State of
Texas for nothing. While some small Texas wineries continue to
produce amateurish efforts, others have made noticeable strides in
upgrading the quality of their wines. By MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   LI-WINE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Long Island is known for many things,
not all of them positive, but perhaps the least likely is that the
extreme east end supports one of the state's four wine regions, and
the one with by far the longest growing season. By FRED LEBRUN.
(For release Sunday, Oct. 18)
</P>
</TEXT>
