 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2490 - October 15, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2490 -- Oct. 15, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. TODAY'S KOSOVO CRISIS IS HARDLY A SURPRISE The Dayton Accord
that ended Bosnia's war has been oversold. Had Washington
intervened in 1993, as Bill Clinton promised to, 100,000 lives
could have been saved, writes Warren Bass. Dayton has strengthened
the two nastiest dictators in the region, Serbia's Slobodan
Milosevic and Croatia's Franjo Tudjman, and edged towards accepting
the de facto partition of Bosnia. The violence in Kosovo today is a
reminder of the costs of appeasing aggressors. From Foreign Affairs
magazine. 2,000 words. 2. FOR AMERICA'S SAKE, IT'S TIME FOR CLINTON
TO RESIGN As the evidence has mounted against him, Ross Perot
writes that he believed President Clinton would resign in shame and
in the best interests of the country. But it is now obvious that
Clinton will not voluntarily resign. (Ross Perot is a businessman,
philanthropist, former Reform Party candidate for U.S. president
and the author of books including ``United We Stand,'' and ``Not
for Sale at Any Price.'') 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
A LOVE STORY BEYOND MONICA AND BILL This time it's not the tiresome
adventure that has forever joined Bill Clinton with Monica
Lewinsky, but a real love story, without disgraceful power
struggles or treacherous friends. The central character in this
story is Simone de Beauvoir. The other one isn't Jean Paul Sartre,
but rather the American novelist Nelson Algren. By Tomas Eloy
Martinez. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
BEWARE, YELTSIN. DO NOT MEDDLE IN NEW GOVERNMENT'S WORK Russia is
at a dangerous threshold. The clock shows five minutes to midnight,
writes Mikhail Gorbachev in this article. 1,000 words. 5. TACKLING
INTERNATIONAL CORRUPTION After years of being tolerated with a
mixture of apathy, cynicism and denial, corruption is becoming a
target of serious international action. By John Brademas and Fritz
Heimann. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,500 words. 6. SEEKING
BETTER TREATMENTS FOR STROKE Stroke (when a blood clot in an artery
blocks blood flow to the brain) is the third most common cause of
death worldwide, and leaves many more victims seriously disabled.
Researchers report the results of a large, international study that
sought to determine if the clot-dissolving drug alteplase can help
patients if it is given as late as 6 hours after the onset of
symptoms of a stroke By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service.
1,000 words. 7. From MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE :
</P>
<P>
   A. BRAIN IMPLANT EASES SOME PARKINSON'S SYMPTOMS : Dual implants
that electrically stimulate the brain offer hope as a treatment for
Parkinson's disease, French researchers report. 500 words. B. MORE
MEN SNORE, BUT THE HABIT FADES WITH AGE : After men hit 50, their
snoring seems to calm down - but young men are louder than ever,
according to a Swedish study. 300 words. C. EARLY-BIRD, NIGHT-OWL
TENDENCIES MAY BE GENETIC : A ``clock'' gene may determine who's a
morning person or a night owl. 250 words. D. DRUG RESTRICTION CUTS
HOSPITAL INFECTIONS, BUT AT A PRICE : By limiting the use of
certain antibiotics, hospitals can combat drug-resistant bacteria
and the infections they cause, but at the price of increasing the
bacteria's resistance to other antibiotics.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
TRICK OR TREAT SMARTS Simple ways to keep your kids safe at
Halloween without taking any of the fun out of the occasion. By
Liza N. Burby. From Child magazine. 700 words. 9. HANDLING THE FEAR
FACTOR ``Parents have to determine how much of Halloween is for
them - because they want to see their child dressed as a pumpkin -
and how much of it kids really enjoy,'' says one child
psychologist. ``Halloween is not just about a photo-opportunity.
It's a children's holiday, so if they are not having fun, don't
celebrate it.'' By Candy Schulman. From Child magazine. 700 words.
10. A RUN ON THE WILD SIDE The New York City Marathon will take
place this year on November 1. Ten thousand of the runners will be
from outside the U.S. (last year 95 other countries were
represented, led by France, Germany and Great Britain.) Here is a
brisk tour of the most tiring race in the city that never walks,
with advice on how to make it across the finish line. By Andrew
Blum. 500 words + photo. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in story no. ______ from summary
2490 Name : ____________________________ Publication :
_________________________ Country : ___________________ Fax :
___________________ Tel : ______________ email
________________________________________________________________
</P>
