<TEXT>
<P>
   ACTOR STANLEY TUCCI IS AN IMPOSTOR!
</P>
<P>
   EYE SCOOPS: CHRIS ISAAK GETS HOUNDED, SOPHIA LOREN NAMED NEW
FACE OF FASHION
</P>
<P>
   TREND WATCH: PEARL PARTY and NEUTRAL LIPS
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS FROM THE MILAN FASHION SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   E-TAILING GETS FASHIONABLE
</P>
<P>
   These are the stories that clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's ``High Style and More'' package received this week.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ``High Style and More'' is a weekly fashion and entertainment
service that reports on style and the people who create it and live
it.
</P>
<P>
   The latest from W magazine, Women's Wear Daily and other
Fairchild periodicals is available in short, ready-to-use features
-- PLUS EYE-CATCHING ART. They're prepared to be plugged right into
your lifestyle, entertainment or fashion section.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Sign up for a trial of ``High Style and More'' _ NO STRINGS
ATTACHED! Call (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796), and you'll
automatically be connected to a salesperson in your territory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLLYWOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ACTOR STANLEY TUCCI IS AN IMPOSTOR!'' From W magazine. One
color slide. ``As soon as somebody says, `Don't do it the way you
want to,' I say, `See you later,''' actor Stanley Tucci explains in
his mellifluous voice that helped make him so creepily convincing
as suspected murderer Richard Cross on television's ``Murder One.''
Cross isn't the only villain on Tucci's resume. The 38-year-old
actor's parts have ranged from various Italian heavies to the
dogcatcher in ``Beethoven,'' Demi More's husband in
``Deconstructing Harry'' and an assassin in ``The Pelican Brief.''
In this interview from W magazine, Tucci talks about his latest two
starring roles _ in the film ``The Impostors,'' a shipboard farce,
and in HBO's ``Winchell,'' in which he portrays the legendary
gossip columnist Walter Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOSSIP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``EYE SCOOPS!'' From DNR. One color slide and one B&AMP;W photo
available. Elizabeth Taylor and Magic Johnson kick off the
festivities at a fashion spectacle and AIDS fund-raiser produced by
Macy's West ... singer Chris Isaak gets hounded after the taping of
his upcoming concert on VH1's ``Hard Rock Live'' ... Rome's mayor,
Francesco Rutelli, names Sophia Loren the new face of fashion ...
and more.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION TRENDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``TREND WATCH: PEARL PARTY.'' From WWD. Three color slides. When
it comes to classics, nothing beats pearls. And this season,
jewelry designers are making them current again. A pictorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``BEAUTY TREND: NEUTRAL TERRITORY.'' From W magazine. One color
slide. We always suspected Catherine Deneuve was on to something.
What started as a mere trendlet at the fall ready-to-wear
collections _ the ultra-sexy, Belle de Jour-era nude mouth _
emerged as a fullblown trend at the fall couture. A report.
</P>
<P>
   ``MILAN IN MOTION.'' A guide to the top fashion shows of Milan.
On the catwalk: Emporio Armani, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Fendi, Ferragamo,
Gianfranco Ferre, Gucci, Prada, Narciso Rodriguez, Jil Sander and
Versus, among others.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``E-TAILING GETS FASHIONABLE.'' From WWD. Apparel marketers are
starting to spin a fashion web on the Internet. The concept that
cyberspace is a viable sales ground only for basic styles and
commodity items rather than trendy designs was solidly debunked by
a range of manufacturers and retailers at a roundtable discussion
in New York last week. A report.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NEXT WEEK: An in-depth look at why Isaac Mizrahi closed his
doors.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   CALL NOW ... (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
