<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8510 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-$ADV17     10-15 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICA AWAITS BRAZIL'S NEXT MOVE AS CONCERNS OVER ECONOMY GROW
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With BRAZIL-PRIMER-$ADV17.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Oct. 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Picture the country of Brazil as just one free-wheeling,
spend-happy consumer.
</P>
<P>
   He gulps Coca-Cola, vacations in Florida, and feels lost without
his cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine that he's broke.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it's easy to see why economic troubles in
Brazil -- home to 164 million potential consumers -- could deal a
devastating blow to U.S. businesses as wide-ranging as Coca-Cola
Co., Motorola Inc., and Walt Disney Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Boasting the world's ninth-largest economy, the South American
country has become a major concern for analysts and investors who
fear that Brazil could plunge into recession by 1999, or be forced
to avert recession with a currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Brazil hopes to receive a bailout of up to $30
billion assembled by the International Monetary Fund, or IMF, to
help stabilize the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy could still crumble if President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso fails to implement an austerity package he is
expected to announce by Oct. 20, and somehow push through Brazil's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso faces the daunting challenge of needing to cut the
government's 8 percent budget deficit, overhaul a shaky social
security system, and adjust a 15 to 20 percent over-valuation in
Brazil's currency.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high because economic woes in Brazil portend
economic woes throughout the rest of Latin America, which would
place the global financial crisis smack on the doorstep of the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget how important Brazil is to the U.S. economy, but
the export market in Brazil is 25 percent bigger than China's,''
said David Hirschmann, executive vice president of the Brazil-U.S.
Business Council in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Brazil's importance is best explained in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's $800 billion-a-year economy is twice the size of
Russia's and nearly twice the size of Mexico's. More than 400 of
the top 500 U.S. companies have subsidiaries in Brazil. The country
accounts for 45 percent of Latin America's output.
</P>
<P>
   And here are just a few ways in which Brazil and the U.S.
economy are inextricably linked:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  American banks had made $34 billion in outstanding loans to
Brazil by September.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More than one million Brazilian tourists vacation in the
United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. corporations have more than $25 billion invested in
Brazilian factories.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors wonder whether Brazil's precarious economic
situation might take some of the steam out of the future earnings
of companies that have made big investments there.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is Coca-Cola's third-largest market, behind the United
States and Mexico. The Atlanta-based company and its bottlers,
which employ 42,000 people in Brazil, invested $1.4 billion in
infrastructure and marketing in Brazil from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of potential in Brazil,'' said Bill Hensel, a
spokesman for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Motorola Inc., just won a five-year, $220
million contract from Brazil's Global Telecom to supply a cellular
phone network system in southern Brazil. Motorola completed a
50,000-square-foot manufacturing facility in Brazil only last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brazil's future certainly will have repercussions
on Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Trade between Brazil and Florida totaled more than $8 billion
last year, meaning Brazil has become Florida's most-important
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 Brazilians live in Florida, and most of the
one million Brazilians who visit the United States each year travel
to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the U.S. exports that go to Brazil go through Florida
or are produced in Florida,'' Hirschmann said. ``You could argue a
compelling case that, in fact, the way Brazil goes, so will go
Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for the future of Brazil's economy have been running high
since Oct. 4, when Cardoso, credited with stabilizing his country's
currency in recent years, became the first president in 109 years
of the Brazilian republic to be re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Even the World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank have
promised to help Brazil make economic reforms, although neither has
specified how much financing will be offered.
</P>
<P>
   But now all eyes are on how well Cardoso's allies fare during
the second round of Brazil's national elections scheduled for Oct.
25.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old sociologist will have a tough time cutting back
on public spending without the key support of Brazil's governors.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes also are focused on Congress, which has proved to be a
stumbling block to Cardoso's plans for reform in the past.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   During Cardoso's first term he repeatedly failed to push
money-saving reforms to the public sector through Congress,
preferring the line of least resistance and raising taxes that did
not require congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time Cardoso did move on other important fronts:
he privatized several bloated state monopolies, including the
country's phone company; and he helped Brazil draw massive amounts
of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   And, earlier this year, Cardoso's government managed to avoid a
collapse of the currency and stem at least some capital flight by
hiking interest rates to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's why some economists are reluctant to predict whether
Cardoso can be successful this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The uncertainty in Brazil is whether the Congress has been
shaken from its complacency and whether reforms can actually be
passed,'' said Don Bowler, regional director for Latin America for
the Economist Intelligence Unit in London, an economic research
firm. ``I'm not sure they can because there's not a lot of party
unity in Brazil and there is a wide range of views within the
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso supporters say the mounting urgency of the world's
financial crisis will give the president the muscle he needs to
deal with Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardoso and his team are smart and they know what needs to be
done,'' said James Ferrer, head of the Institute of Brazilian
Issues at George Washington University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said he expects Cardoso's package to include sharp
spending cuts, some small tax increases, and reforms to the social
security system.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends.)
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agree that the government wants to do all it can
to avoid a devaluation of the real, which would send shock waves
through a population that fears a return to the days of
hyperinflation that ended just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso was a popular finance minister whose 1994 currency plan
brought price increases to zero from 3,000 percent in less than
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, foreign currency reserves, the best defense
against a speculative attack on the real, have plummeted from $67
billion at the end of August to $47 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's devaluation of the ruble in August scared U.S.
investors away from emerging markets such as Brazil, causing
dollars to disappear faster than candy before hungry children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone expects a devaluation except, perhaps,
Cardoso and his associates,'' said Jerry Haar, director of the
Inter-American Business and Labor Program at the University of
Miami's North-South Center.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Cardoso may be forced to devalue if the country
keeps hemorrhaging money in the public sector due to the lack of
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, you can work for the government for 10 years and
still retire at 110 percent of your salary,'' Haar said.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agree that Cardoso's plan must shave at least $25
billion off a whopping public deficit of $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a devaluation would almost surely throw the economy
into a recession, as well as reintroduce high inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And it most certainly would erode the spending power of
Brazilian consumers and businesses, hurting U.S. exporters.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-$ADV17     10-15 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
