<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Bob
McCarthy at the Daily News, (818) 713-3665. 
. 
OPRAH-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ When Oprah Winfrey read ``Beloved,''
Toni Morrison's Pulitzer Prize winning novel, she immediately
wanted to turn it into a movie. Now the film nobody _ including
Morrison _ ever thought could be made is here and it's generating
strong buzz for its unflinching portrayal of an African American
family coming to grips with the legacy of slavery. Winfrey, in just
her second film role, is being talked up for an Oscar (``Oprah ...
Oscar ... Oscar ... Oprah''), too, but she says she's not going to
give up her daytime job any time soon. ``What I need to do in TV is
just beginning,'' Winfrey says. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
HAPPINESS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ There's irony in the movie
``Happiness'' from writer-director Todd Solondz, whose comedy about
extreme sexuality and dysfunction seems more disapproving than
empathetic. (3 stars). By Bob Strauss. 
. 
BELOVED-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Faithful to a fault to Toni
Morrison's 1987 Pulitzer Prize-winning novel, Jonathan Demme's
shockingly vivid ``Beloved'' is a movie _ whether you like it or
not _ that will stay with you long after the house lights go up. (3
stars). By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
MAGIC-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Practical Magic'' blends romance,
rah-rah sisterhood, family drama and outlandish supernatural
effects into a bland, watered-down concoction that rarely bubbles
into anything appetizing. (2 stars). By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
NUDITY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Odette Springer's ``Some Nudity
Required'' hits the expected feminist notes, reveals repressed
memories of child abuse and confirms that Roger Corman and his ilk
who make movies like ``Hollywood Chainsaw Hookers'' can be kind of
crude. (2 stars). By Bob Strauss. 
. 
CELEBRATION-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Funny, fiercely well-acted but
hardly as revolutionary as it wants to be, ``The Celebration'' is a
dysfunctional family drama that won a special jury prize at the
Cannes Film Festival, presumably for its character honesty. (3
stars). Bob Strauss. 
. 
EVEREST-IMAX (Los Angeles) _ On May 23, 1996, filmmaker David
Breashears and an IMAX film crew stood on top of the world, only
days after the worst climbing tragedy in the history of Mount
Everest. Their quest for the summit is told in ``Everest,'' which
opens today in Los Angeles. By Bob McCarthy. 
 
 
MORRISSETTE-CONCERT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Review of Alanis
Morrissette's concert Wednesday night at the Hollywood Palladium..
By Fred Shuster. 
. 
SHARPS-FLATS (Los Angeles) _ Kokomo. It was one of the greatest
'70s soul revues you've never heard of. From 1974 to 1982, this
supremely talented band cut three excellent yet hard-to-find
platters for Columbia and toured the States opening for Average
White Band. Much of the band's best material is collected on the
anthology ``Kokomo: The Collection'' (Castle), which can be ordered
through the online mail-order shop at NME.com. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ By Fred Shuster and James Hames. 
. 
XFILES-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ For all you fans who didn't make it to
the theaters, now you can watch ``The X-Files'' movie in your
living rooms. And, as a bonus, the video has a couple of prolonged
scenes _ one that explains the fate of one of the characters, and
another that elaborates on the ongoing conspiracy. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

