<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-SONS-TEX     10-15 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDER BUSH SAYS SON'S SUCCESS HIS OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush has not asked his powerful
father for ``one darn thing'' during a long career that has ranged
from oil and gas ventures to the state's top political job, former
President Bush told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush's comments came amid increasing speculation, and
scrutiny, over the possibility of his son's run for president in
2000. Among the questions being raised by political opponents are
whether the younger Bush relied on his father's help in business,
politics and military service.
</P>
<P>
   Such accusations, the former president said, are ``groundless,
untrue and unfair to my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The 41st president, who has largely kept a low profile at his
Houston home since leaving office in 1993, has begun to speak out
more often as two of his sons conduct gubernatorial campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about his eldest son undergoing media scrutiny
at a time when politicians' private lives are increasingly becoming
public, the 74-year-old father said he is thankful that sons George
W., 52, and Jeb, 45, a gubernatorial candidate in Florida, haven't
been discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current `gotcha' atmosphere discourages a lot of good
young people from getting into public service,'' the former
president said, responding in writing to questions from the
Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank heavens my two sons have not been discouraged. I feel
many in the media are too often intrusive and unaccountable. Some
unnamed source makes a groundless charge and it is repeated and
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened to me, and I expect it will continue to happen to
my two decent sons in the political arena, who deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   President Bush also called the Texas governor a ``true leader
who brought dignity and respect to his office,'' saying that he and
Barbara Bush ``have been proud of him at every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The former chief executive agreed to accept two questions in
writing. A spokesman in the elder Bush's office said that, because
of the number of inquiries being received, Bush's time is limited.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about whether the governor had ever
used connections to help him advance in business, politics or
military service, Bush wrote: ``I am offended by the suggestion.
George never asked me for one darn thing in business, politics, and
certainly not the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``In business, he built his own company and never tried to drop
my name. And I can guarantee you that the head of George's National
Guard unit told the truth when he said anyone who intimated
influence was used was a `damned liar.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to recent comments by retired Lt. Col. Walter
B. ``Buck'' Staudt, the younger Bush's commanding officer, in the
Washington Post. George W. Bush, who entered the Air National Guard
in 1968, flew F-102 fighter jets. He was not drafted and did not
serve in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable father/son comparisons also provoked comment from
the former president. He told GQ magazine recently that he is
``immune to these things now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts George and it hurts Jeb to have it look like they're
riding a wave their incompetent father couldn't,'' he told GQ.
``And I've tried to assure them that it's inevitable, and, in some
schools of journalism, mandatory, so don't you boys worry about it;
it's not going to hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, George W. Bush's gubernatorial
opponent, Democratic land commissioner Garry Mauro, called the
governor a ``decent man from a decent family.'' He said Bush
benefits from having George and Barbara Bush as parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is look at his contributor list,'' Mauro
said, referring George W. Bush. ``There's a lot of people on his
list that are former contributors to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president has become involved in the Texas lieutenant
governor's race. He has helped Republican Rick Perry raise money,
and also appears in a recent TV ad, saying that the former first
family supports Perry.
</P>
<P>
   The election is Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Fero, a spokesman for Perry's Democratic opponent, state
Comptroller John Sharp, said Sharp has a ``great deal of respect''
for the former president. But Fero said the candidates' records and
their platforms will decide the race, not ``partisan
endorsements.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, George W. Bush said his famous name has both
helped and hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a great name,'' the governor said. ``When your name is
George Bush and you've had a father who has brought class and
dignity to the process, it's helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, some people assume that he ``can't possibly do
any good as governor _ `He's just this spoiled kid who's got famous
parents.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
