r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONG-ISLAND-WINE-$ADV     10-15 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-ISLAND-WINE-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND WINERIES OFFER A TASTE OF THE GOOD LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LEBRUN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long Island is known for many things, not all of them positive,
but perhaps the least likely given the din and congestion of the
townships closest to New York City is that the extreme east end
supports one of the state's four wine regions, and the one with by
far the longest growing season.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest is only coming to its conclusion now at Paumanok, as
it is at the 16 other wineries along a concentrated length of Long
Island's North Fork.
</P>
<P>
   The North Fork's season is at least a month longer than the
Finger Lakes, or Hudson Valley, or Niagara frontier, and even
several weeks longer than the nearby South Fork, because of
prevailing air and water currents.
</P>
<P>
   So not surprisingly there are 17 wineries on the North Fork, and
only two on the South Fork. A little of that has to do with the
availability and cost of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamptons are on the South Fork, where property is valued
practically by the cubic inch. But then, the entire Long Island
winery industry is a rich man's game, just as this used to be
strictly a rich man's playground. Even real estate along the North
Fork, formerly rich potato and vegetable farms, runs $18,000 to
$25,000 an acre, which is a major reason there are few big
vineyards _ only two are over 100 acres, Pindar and Macari. As a
result there are rarely bargains to be had in Long Island wines.
It's pricey stuff because it's made for the most part in limited
quantity on very pricey land.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, some of the best wines made in New York, or anywhere
in the United States for that matter, are created here. That
remains a moderately well-kept secret because so much of the
produce, particularly from the smaller wineries, doesn't travel far
from the vineyard, and seldom past a few restaurants in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The east end of Long Island is a terrific spot for wine lovers
for a weekend or even better, mid-week getaway. All 17 North Fork
wineries are located on two roads along 18 miles, from Riverhead to
Greenport.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration and variety are such that one home base at one
of the dozens of stately old bed-and-breakfasts in the area is
perfect for forays at two and three wineries at a time. There are
plenty of good restaurants in the neighborhood since the North Fork
and South Fork have been touristy areas for centuries. This year,
Hargrave Vineyard, the first winery on Long Island, is celebrating
its 25th anniversary, indicative of just how new this business is
on the North Fork. The winery is also up for sale, also indicative
of the ``shaking-out'' that is ongoing in these essentially
formative years.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa and Alex Hargrave, in their early 20s, fresh out of
Harvard and from affluent families, wandered the West Coast and
Finger Lakes for a place to open a winery in order to produce big
red wines like the ones they admired in Bordeaux. They were
attracted to the potato fields of the East End, and created what
had only been dreamed about before. And they did indeed create some
wonderful, big reds, award-winners still talked about years later.
The cabernet sauvignon grape has the needed time to ripen here as
it does nowhere else in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The big red of a perfect cabernet sauvignon, perhaps softened a
little in the Bordeaux manner with either cabernet franc or merlot,
remains the preferred quest of almost all the other winery owners
drawn in by the Hargrave experiment. The most notable successes in
my view, however, have been with chardonnay, riesling and the
medium reds, particularly merlot, but also cabernet franc.
</P>
<P>
   If a single grape is best suited for the area, it's chardonnay,
as riesling is for the Finger Lakes. Virtually every Long Island
winery puts its own signature on this grape, from the most austere
finish in stainless steel and without a mellowing secondary
fermentation, to the biggest, oakiest, fruitiest California finish
imaginable. The years 1988 and 1995 are the benchmarks, although
characterizing benchmarks for a region that's only been making wine
for a quarter of a century is about as presumptuous as slapping
``vintage'' on a gallon jug of California bulk wine.
</P>
<P>
   This year also could be world-class for all of Long Island's
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are two-thirds the way through a potentially remarkable
year,'' acknowledged Charles Massoud, winemaker and co-owner with
his wife, Ursula, of Paumanok in Aquebogue. ``A mild winter and hot
August, and even the 11 days of uninterrupted rain early came just
at the right time for when the vines need to push and grow. We are
about a week ahead of a normal year,'' he added, due to the mild
winter and spring.
</P>
<P>
   Massoud is also president of the Long Island Wine Council, and
is a reasonably representative North Fork winery owner. He was born
in Lebanon of a well-to-do international hotel and restaurant
family. His wife is German, from a family with a long history in
wine production. Of the 19 winemaking vineyards, two are owned by
physicians, others by retired advertising executives and venture
capitalists. A few are owned by the less rarefied, but not many.
</P>
<P>
   The upside for the visitor is that nearly all the vineyards have
excellent tasting rooms, open year-round. Most of the wines are
free for the tasting, with a few of the rarer bottles of the better
wines requiring a small tasting fee. Touring the wineries is
inexpensive and enormously rewarding because of the wide range of
attempts with European vinifera grapes and also with native grapes
like Niagara and catawba, and hybrids like Suffolk red and baco
noir.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As to which ones of the wineries to visit, that is a personal
choice. But a suggestion is to start with Pindar, which is
somewhere in the middle geographically, but will establish the
standard. Herodotus ``Dan'' Damianos has the most acreage in grapes
_ 300 _ and offers the most choice and range in wines, sparklers
and stills. He is also the owner of the excellent Duck Walk
Vineyard, one of the two on the South Fork. Duck Walk merlots may
be the best on the island, but there is plenty of stiff competition
for that designation.
</P>
<P>
   After Pindar, must-visits include Hargrave, because of its
distinction as the first winery on Long Island; Palmer and Lenz
because they win the most awards (although I personally feel Lenz
tends to be overrated and overpriced); Paumanok for the chardonnay;
and Pugliese for sparkling wines.
</P>
<P>
   A word about pricing. There seems to be no rhyme nor reason to
it, which was confirmed by discussing the matter with winery
owners. One bottle of merlot will be $18, and another from an
adjoining vineyard, same year, same style, will be $10 more. Price
relates more often to the whim of the owner. So shop around. There
is a wide range in pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind this is a tony tourist area, and plan accordingly.
A bed-and-breakfast in high season before Labor Day, and for
weekends through September, may well have run $125 a night and up.
But prices drop like a pebble in the wishing well in October, which
would be my first choice. Any time before Jan. 1, actually, would
be ideal. The moody Sound and Peconic Bay, bobbing with boats at
anchor, are as romantic a backdrop as Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Long Island Convention and Visitors Bureau
(800-441-4601) for lists of bed-and-breakfasts and other
accommodations. Especially ask for the Long Island Wine Council's
seasonal publication, The Wine Press, which does an excellent job
of profiling all the vineyards, the players, and all available
wines. A helpful booklet is ``Newsday Guide to the Wines of Long
Island,'' by Peter M. Gianotti, and the more in-depth ``The Wines
of Long Island,'' by Philip F. Palmedo and Edward Beltrami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
