<HEADER>
A8666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDDIE-COX     10-15 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDDIE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Will `Fast Eddie' face the music?
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Rochell
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The buzz around Louisiana these days sounds a lot
like the buzz in Washington. People are saying, ``This time, maybe
they've finally got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, who earned his nickname ``Fast
Eddie'' the same way President Clinton earned the nickname ``Slick
Willie'' _ by escaping scandals that would have destroyed lesser
politicians _ could see his good luck run dry this week.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year federal investigation that involved wiretapping,
searches and seizures of large amounts of cash from Edwards' home
and office, as well as hundreds of hours of secret grand jury
testimony, is coming to a close. And the noose could be tightening
around the neck of the once-invincible, always colorful four-time
governor. He could be indicted this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two former Edwards associates accepted plea bargains
and agreed to testify against the former governor and his son,
Stephen Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Edward DeBartolo Jr., owner of the San Francisco 49ers,
testified that Edwin and Stephen Edwards pressured him to pay them
$400,000 and monthly fees to influence the state's gaming board to
grant DeBartolo a license for a riverboat casino in Shreveport. He
pleaded guilty to concealing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Ricky Shetler, a gambling consultant and a
childhood friend of Stephen Edwards, pleaded guilty to giving the
Edwardses $550,000 in payoffs, some allegedly during Edwards' final
term as governor. According to prosecutors, the money was part of a
scheme to extort from the Players Casino in Lake Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, Dempsey White, who served as chief highway
engineer in Edwards' administration, was charged with conspiring
with the Edwardses to wiretap the homes of two FBI agents involved
in the case. His lawyer said Wednesday that White has agreed to
testify against Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Edwards told reporters that he was entrapped by a
friend of White's who was a wiretapping expert and FBI informant.
Edwards said he did pay the man $4,000, but he said the money was
not to spy on the FBI but rather to obtain FBI tapes the man said
he had of Edwards. Edwards claims he only wanted to know if the FBI
was taping him illegally, without a court order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the government is building its case a lot
stronger than they have in the last trials,'' said John Maginnis,
publisher of the Louisiana Political Fax Weekly. Edwards was
indicted twice in the 1980s _ and he walked away both times.
``We've never heard Edwards wiretapped before. This will be
something new for the public and for a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 71, has denied all charges.
</P>
<P>
   After DeBartolo's appearance in a Baton Rouge court last week,
Edwards stood on the courthouse steps, cracking jokes and poking
fun. He called DeBartolo the ``new Linda Tripp,'' referring to the
former friend of Monica Lewinsky who turned over tapes of
conversations with her to federal prosecutors in the Clinton
scandal
</P>
<P>
   ``That performance at the courthouse is just a preview of what
will be the show of a lifetime should he get indicted and go to
trial,'' Maginnis said
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' attorney, Mike Fawer, said DeBartolo's plea is
meaningless because he has changed his story since he received a
letter last year saying he was a target in the investigation of the
Edwardses. Those discrepencies will be obvious if Edwards is
indicted and DeBartolo has to testify in court, Fawer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that before last week, he never suggested he
was victimized by Edwards,'' he said. ``He negotiated an agreement
with Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   What's so unusual about an agreement between a client and an
attorney?''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr, U.S. Attorney Eddie
Jordan and his team of more than 100 FBI agents have been
criticized for spending time and money on what until last week
seemed like a wild goose chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man has been through hell twice now, and they couldn't
convict him,'' said Jim Monaghan, owner of Molly's on the Market, a
hangout for journalists and politicians, including Edwards. ``This
investigation is cruel and unfair punishment, just like Starr's is
for the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Monaghan said talk at the bar included speculation that Edwards
himself might cop a plea to get the whole thing over with. But all
indications from Edwards and his attorney point to him going to
trial if he is indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the possibility of Edwards having to go to trial again
makes for good theater, the more troubling issue is the black eye
the scandal gives to the state's Gaming Control Board. The board
was created by Gov. Mike Foster to imbue Louisiana's casino
industry with a level of integrity it seemed to be lacking under
Edwards. But it was the board, under Foster, that awarded DeBartolo
the state's 15th and final gaming license. The U.S. Attorney's
Office, it is now clear, is accusing Edwards of influencing the
board to grant that license.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a shadow cast on the Gaming Control Board,''
Maginnis said. ``Even on the day they awarded that contract, they
made a speech about how there would be no outside influences on
them. Now, the idea that the politicians may have been influencing
even one board member _ maybe two, maybe more _ it makes you wonder
about some of their other decisions.'' To many here, it is hard to
believe Edwards could be convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards always thumbed his nose at propriety and the law and was
applauded for it. He rode in a horse and buggy to his 1985
racketeering trial to illustrate the slow wheels of justice. He
celebrated his fourth election victory _ won in large part because
people were voting against his opponent, former Ku Klux Klansman
David Duke _ in a Las Vegas casino, where his earnings reportedly
exceeded $40,000. A popular bumper sticker at the time was ``Vote
for the crook: It's important.''
</P>
<P>
   He boasted of his sexual prowess and flagrantly cheated on his
wife of 40 years. After divorcing her in 1989, he met Candy Picou,
a student more than 30 years his junior. They are now married.
</P>
<P>
   To give the public a hint of just how strong a case there is
against Edwards, the U.S. Attorney's Office has made public
tantalizing tidbits of the thousands of hours of tapes they
secretly made of Edwards on the phone and of him talking to his son
in the law office they share in Baton Rouge. The excerpts are
peppered with coarse language and contain what sounds like damning
evidence of schemes to extort money and influence government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's developments, a lot of Louisianans are
beginning to think that Edwards won't be able to escape punishment
this time. A cartoon in the New Orleans Times-Picayune last week
pictured Edwards in bed with his wife and her saying, ``Why didn't
you just have an affair with an intern?''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is guilty or not, the idea of Edwards not skating out
of his latest troubles makes some people a little wistful for the
good old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is convicted, it will feel like the end of an era,''
Monaghan said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell is a writer for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
