<SLUG> BC-HAPPINESS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HAPPINESS' GOES HEAVY ON THE SEX, IRONY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the title of his movie ``Happiness'' on
through every frame of the film, writer-director Todd Solondz
strives so hard to create an atmosphere of irony it's almost
endearing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the last thing Solondz wants is to be endearing.
``Happiness'' is the celebrated/infamous comedy that won the
International Critics Prize at the Cannes Film Festival and was
abandoned by October Films, its initial American distributor, when
the supposedly independent releasing company was pressured by
corporate parents Seagram and Universal to drop the hot potato.
</P>
<P>
   If such cowardice isn't exactly laudible, it is understandable.
Solondz, who made the edgy, observant coming-of-age comedy
``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' has made a comedy of extreme
sexuality this time around. ``Happiness'' presents obscene phone
callers, elderly adulterers and even a pederast with some degree of
compassion, punctuated by enough bad sex and masturbation scenes to
make ``There's Something About Mary'' seem as innocent as
``Bambi.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though he's obviously out to shock, Solondz also wants
to appear sensitive, to make the pain of his dysfunctional
characters' missed connections and unsatisfying perversities
palpable. But more often than not, Solondz's irony overcomes his
empathy. Even when someone in the movie is at his or her most
vulnerable, the director's attitude toward them is at least as
snide as it is sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of this long film, one sister tells another, ``I
wasn't laughing at you, I was laughing with you,'' to which her
sibling replies, ``But I wasn't laughing.'' Whatever else you want
to say about ``Happiness,'' at least its maker is aware of his own
misanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the movie is at its best when it makes us
laugh and feel queasy about laughing at the same time. Things start
off on a hilariously overwrought note (a more deadpan approach
takes hold later), at a fancy New Jersey restaurant, where Jon
Lovitz's self-pitying loser cries, wheedles and upbraids his date,
a mousy woman named Joy Jordan (Jane Adams), for not feeling what
he wants her to.
</P>
<P>
   He is, we soon learn, the latest in a long line of Mr.
Not-Quite-Rights the 30-year-old bachelorette has let get away.
She's chirpfully, mercilessly reminded of this by her
self-satisfied sister Trish Maplewood (Cynthia Stevenson), snug and
smug in her two-story suburban home, with three kids and a
successful therapist husband, Bill (Dylan Baker).
</P>
<P>
   But Bill, we soon learn, has no amorous feelings for Trish
because he's more interested in the playmates of his pubescent,
sexually neurotic son Billy (Rufus Read). Father and son bond over
oddly explicit, birds-and-bees conversations. Thankfully, Dad's
escapades with Billy's sleep-over friends occur discreetly, but
nonetheless alarmingly, off screen.
</P>
<P>
   A third Jordan sister, Helen (Lara Flynn Boyle), is a snooty,
successful pop poetry writer who gets her kicks with glamour boys
and lives next door to the compulsive, introverted Allen (``Boogie
Nights' '' Phillip Seymour Hoffman), a phone freak who confesses
his violent fantasies about Helen to his analyst _ who is none
other than her child-molesting brother-in-law. A third high-rise
resident, Kristina (``The Practice's'' Emmy-winning Camryn
Manheim), is after the otherwise-engaged Allen; we eventually learn
she has quite an intimate secret, too.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a retirement village in Boca Raton, the Jordan
girls' parents (Louise Lasser and Ben Gazzara) are finally doing
something, sort of, about their long, loveless marriage. The
message, of course, is that age and experience don't yield any more
clues to where that elusive happiness lies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bleak and not entirely convincing landscape Solondz
creates. Unlike the sex-addled but fully emotional fools in
``Boogie Nights,'' the generally more intelligent ``Happiness''
crowd comes off, for the most part, as abstract, walking obsessions
more than real people with problems.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there's deft comic delivery on every actor's part,
and Adams, Baker and Stevenson succeed best at suggesting their
characters' extra dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, for all of his bad-boy effort to push the taboo
limit, Solondz reveals himself to be a puritan at heart. No urge
that's slaked in ``Happiness'' leads to, well, happiness; it just
triggers recrimination or self-loathing or a bitter lesson that
makes someone a better, more celibate person.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is as repulsed by sex in all of its permutations as
Solondz presumably expects people to be shocked by it. That might
not be precisely the tone he was going for with ``Happiness.'' But
you've got to admit, it's exquisitely ironic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
