<HEADER>
A8702 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUDITY-REVIEW-LADN     10-15 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDITY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTION ON CORMAN'S B-MOVIES MISSES THE FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 Stars 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Working for Roger Corman's exploitation movie
operation made Odette Springer feel bad, so she decided to make a
documentary about it. The dreary result, ``Some Nudity Required,''
hits the expected feminist notes, reveals the almost-to-be-expected
repressed memories of child abuse and confirms that the guys who
make movies like ``Hollywood Chainsaw Hookers'' can be kind of
crude.
</P>
<P>
   Sleazy and degrading as the B-movie business often is, however,
Springer _ a classically trained composer who co-directed
``Nudity'' with documentary and episodic television director
Johanna Demetrakas _ makes the whole scene seem more demoralizing
than you suspect it actually is. Yes, these often straight-to-video
productions trade on cheap violence and sexuality, but they're
hardly worse than some better-made, soul-deadening Hollywood A
product.
</P>
<P>
   But while composing scores for the cheap, essentially worthless
productions, Springer realized that the guy who gave Francis
Coppola, Martin Scorsese and James Cameron their starts was really
only interested in making a quick buck. Springer's artistic
aspirations, along with her gender politics, were constantly
challenged by the parade of bimbos she encountered at the studio.
The actress' often enhanced physiques made her question her own
attractiveness, too.
</P>
<P>
   So why does she eventually find these awful movies strangely
fascinating?
</P>
<P>
   Springer is so involved with how all of this impacts her, we
never feel we're getting much real insight into these films' wider
cultural meaning. A couple of actresses, the optimistic Julie
Strain and the depressed Maria Ford, make their own, highly
subjective points, while directors like Jim Wynorski are
alternately accommodating and annoyed when badgered to defend
their, um, art.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who directs this stuff, Catherine Cyran, has the most
persuasive take on why, psychologically and socially, these films
have their audience. Corman, who reportedly hates the movie, barely
appears in it.
</P>
<P>
   The thing Springer misses here, of course, is that the real
selling point of exploitation films is their absurdity. There's no
fun allowed in ``Some Nudity Required''; considering the subject
matter, that's a creative miscalculation on a level with anything
you'll see in ``Sorority House Massacre II.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8705 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGIC-REVIEW-LADN     10-15 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRACTICAL MAGIC' HAS CHARMS, BUT IT ISN'T SPELLBINDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Practical Magic'' tells us that it's important
to accept who you are _ even if you're a witch.
</P>
<P>
   That's basically the goofball moral of this uneven mishmash of a
movie, a film that blends romance, rah-rah sisterhood, family drama
and outlandish supernatural effects into a bland, watered-down
concoction that rarely bubbles into anything appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical Magic'' isn't totally without its charms. Nicole
Kidman and Sandra Bullock make for appealing witches and the film
has fun with some of its abracadabra. But bewitching it isn't;
bothering and bewildering it often is.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman and Bullock play sisters who are continuing their
family's hocus-pocus heritage. For more than 300 years, Owens women
have been casting spells in their quaint New England village, much
to the dismay of the local townsfolk. Only now, their neighbors
just shun them instead of taking them to the gallows. Still it
isn't much of an existence, and you wonder why they just don't move
to a place where they would blend in _ say, New Orleans maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem comes from a curse. Any man who loves an Owens
woman winds up six feet underground. Sally (Bullock) deals with
this by running from love. Gillian (Kidman) copes by using her
witchcraft to seduce an assortment of grungy losers who wouldn't
know true love unless it came from a syringe.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian eventually ends up in a rather abusive relationship and
the sisters have to dust off their dormant powers to cope with the
mess. This leads to more trouble (see what happens when you deny
who you are?) and takes the movie to its ridiculous final act,
which alternates between silly supernatural effects and soppy
romance. It's tough to decide which is more grating.
</P>
<P>
   Director Griffin Dunne and writers Robin Swicord, Akiva Goldsman
and Adam Brooks have some pretty good source material in Alice
Hoffman's novel, but they have blunted the book's edginess into a
feel-good froth. Dunne never settles on a tone, and the unsteady
mix of genres seem to come more from a demographic study taken at
Lilith Fair than any desire to make a good movie.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Wiest and Stockard Channing are largely wasted as the
elder witches, as is Aidan Quinn as a law enforcement love
interest. And as engaging as Bullock is, it seems like we just saw
her give the same performance in ``Hope Floats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical Magic'' isn't an awful movie. It has a few good
laughs, but largely wastes its resources. We're still waiting for a
good witch movie to cast its spell on us. This isn't it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
