<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8714 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRAH-MOVIE-LADN     10-15 1651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH'S OBSESSION  _  HOW HER `BELOVED' GOT TO THE SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You'd think that people would have learned by now
that if you tell Oprah Winfrey she can't do something, she's just
going to try all the harder to make it happen. One of her most
telling character flaws, she says, is the way she relishes the
I-told-you-so moment. ``I can't resist,'' Winfrey says. ``I kind of
live for the times when I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those times, most famously, include: I told you I could get a
part in a Steven Spielberg movie (``The Color Purple''), I told you
a cookbook could sell millions of copies (``In the Kitchen With
Rosie''), I told you people will respond to television that's
sincere and dignified, and (this one is a recurring favorite) I
told you I could lose those 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey's biggest I-told-you-so might just be her current
passion, ``Beloved,'' the film adaptation of Toni Morrison's
Pulitzer Prize-winning novel that Winfrey calls her ``greatest
achievement.'' Nobody, including Morrison herself, thought this
dense, surreal novel about the horrific emotional effects of
slavery ever could be translated from the page to the screen.
Nobody except Winfrey. And in the end, of course, hers was the only
opinion that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey read the book in fits and starts 11 years ago when it
was published. (She did not finish it in one sitting, as widely
reported. ``You try doing that and get back to me,'' she says,
laughing.) When Winfrey completed the novel, she called Morrison,
not to talk about making it into a movie, but so she could better
articulate her own feelings about the book when talking to viewers
on her then-fledgling talk show.
</P>
<P>
   But as she and Morrison talked and Winfrey confessed how she
identified with Sethe, the book's iron-willed former slave, the
idea to film ``Beloved'' began to take hold. Eventually, Winfrey
bought the rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said _ and this is kind of charming _ `I'm going in my
pocketbook and write a check,''' Morrison remembers. ``I wasn't
talking to a lawyer, but to another human being. It reminded me of
myself. A single black woman who said, `Well, I'm doing this. It's
going to be hard for me, but that's beside the point.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was a decade ago. And Winfrey was right. It was hard _ both
getting the movie made and playing a stoic character who represses
her emotions, a woman the film's director, Jonathan Demme, calls
the ``anti-Oprah,'' alluding to Winfrey's well-known capacity for
empathy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, winning the opportunity to portray Sethe was a victory
in and of itself for Winfrey. Many directors, including Peter Weir,
were interested in the film, but not necessarily with Winfrey in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could understand that, especially because a lot of the years
I was shopping this around, I weighed 200 or more pounds,'' Winfrey
says. ``They couldn't see me playing the role. And I said, `I'll
lose the weight.' And they'd say, `Well, we can't make any
guarantees.' At one time, I really thought about giving it up
because so many people were telling me I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I thought that would be stupid because I had the
rights to the movie and had fought for so long to get it made. I
should at least be given the opportunity to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Demme, though skeptical, was willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had such admiration for Oprah for a long time,'' says the
director of ``The Silence of the Lambs'' and ``Philadelphia.'' ``I
had dinner at her house, and within half an hour of listening to
her express herself about her connection to the character of Sethe
and the immeasurable importance to her of the themes of the story,
I went from being a little skeptical that we would be able to
separate Oprah Winfrey from Sethe to thinking there's no one else
who can play this part.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that didn't mean there weren't problems. The period
setting _ post-Civil War, rural Ohio _ helped erase the image of
the modern-day talk-show icon. But Morrison, still protective of
her book, cautioned Demme that ``Oprah is emotional; Sethe is
not.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Winfrey a long time to be able to make that distinction.
Demme often had to admonish her during takes to stop sympathizing
with her character and maintain the appropriate impassiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do cry a lot,'' Winfrey admits. ``So, that was a difficulty
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Before shooting a scene and often between takes, Winfrey would
go off in a corner and weep into a towel and empty herself of all
her sadness and then morph into Sethe, a former slave and mother
living in denial and haunted by her brutal past. Demme often would
put her through take after take after take, Winfrey crying after
each one and Demme diplomatically telling her, ``Very good,'' and
then, ``Let's try it again.'' Winfrey soon caught on to her
director's code language.
</P>
<P>
   ```Very good' really means `You suck,''' she says, laughing.
``It means, `You're going to be here for a while.' Now, if you get
an `amazing' or a `fantastic' from him, then you know you did OK.
Otherwise, I'd know I was feeling sympathy for Sethe when I
shouldn't have been.''
</P>
<P>
   And more than anything, Winfrey was committed to helping Demme
put Morrison's book on the screen without an inappropriate trace of
sentimentality or sloppy emotionalism. ``Beloved'' was always
intended to be a difficult movie to watch. The goal, Morrison says,
was not to simply show what slavery looked like, but what it felt
like as well.
</P>
<P>
   Says the author: ``They did something I thought they never
could: to make the film represent not the abstraction of slavery
but the individuals, the domestic qualities and consequences of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Record producer Quincy Jones put it a little more colorfully in
an interview with Vogue. ``People are expecting some PG (stuff),''
he said. ``Oprah went for the art, man.''
</P>
<P>
   And the process inspired her. In fact, as filming was winding
down last summer, Winfrey considered ending her talk show after her
contract expired in 2000 and concentrating instead on movies.
Looking back now, she says, she sees that she simply didn't want
the experience to end. She wanted it to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was almost a postpartum feeling for Winfrey, who
has no children with her long-time companion Stedman Graham, but
certainly honed her motherly instincts while making ``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think mothers feel, `It's here; everybody's going to see it.
Feel happy, happy, happy,''' Winfrey says. ``And that's how I feel
for the movie. I can't wait for it to open, but there's a part of
me that feels, `It's over; it's ended.' But like my friends tell
me: You created the movie. You still have the movie. I have to
remind myself, `Oh yeah, that's right.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Winfrey still has her day job as well. She recently extended
her contract through the year 2002, saying that the more she
thought about her experience with ``Beloved,'' the more she felt it
had inspired her to continue the talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're blessed to get one movie like this in a lifetime,''
Winfrey says. ``And I absolutely feel that what I have to do in
television is just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like a revelation, coming out of this movie,''
Winfrey continues. ``I've decided I'm going to use television and
not have television use me. Because who am I kidding? It's not just
a show; it's like a whole big force field in people's homes every
day. And I'm aware of that and intend to use it with a greater
sense of meaning and intention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know I'll get asked, `Who do you think you are, trying
to change people's lives?' I hear that all the time. But television
teaches people, whether or not it comes right out and says so. All
you have to do is watch all the shows where people beat each other
up. If a child watches a show where somebody picks up a chair and
throws it because they don't like what was said, that teaches that
there's no such thing as conflict resolution. It teaches: If
someone says something you don't like, slap 'em silly. That's
really what they're saying and what our children are learning.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Winfrey plans to continue popular segments like the Book
Club and the recently added ``Remembering Your Spirit,'' which aims
to soothe viewers' souls. Last year, she launched the Angel
Network, an attempt to encourage her audience to donate time to
community programs.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the talk show, Winfrey continues to take the high
road as well. Winfrey's production company, Harpo films, is in the
middle of a six-picture deal with ABC to produce TV movies, all of
which are based on books that inspired her. The first, ``Before
Women Had Wings,'' told the story of a young girl who was
physically abused by her alcoholic mother. It was one of last
year's highest-rated television movies. Winfrey herself was raped
at age 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself as a vehicle to provide information for people to
pick and choose and allow themselves to make decisions to improve
their lives,'' Winfrey says. ``Because I think _ and this is just
what I think; if you don't think it, you don't have to watch,
really _ that given the choice, people choose to be better. They
will choose happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her future in the movies, Winfrey isn't ruling anything
out. She's more secure about her abilities than before making
``Beloved'' but says, ``If I wait another 10 years, I'll be
insecure again.'' Demme, for one, would love to work with her
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said to her several times that I want her to do an
incredibly up-to-the-minute, tough, tough comedy,'' he says. ``I
want to see Oprah being just funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Oprah ... just being funny? Winfrey says she would love to try
it. Now all she needs is somebody to tell her she can't. After the
triumph of ``Beloved,'' she might be hard-pressed to find any
takers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
