<HEADLINE>
MORISSETTE PUTS PALLADIUM AUDIENCE IN HER POCKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We shoulda known.
</P>
<P>
   The anxious crowd let out a roar when the lights came down and
Morissette's newly expanded band opened with an Eastern-style
rhythm, the perfect foil for the headliner's wide, distinctive
vocal range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be home,'' Morissette said after the second song,
later adding she was having ``flashbacks to that Dragonfly show I
did a few years ago,'' referring to the local rock dive.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most memorable new songs, mostly co-written with
Morissette's co-producer, Glen Ballard, were set-opener ``Baba''; a
powerful ``Are You Still Mad,'' which kept the audience rapt; and
``Uninvited,'' from the ``City of Angels'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The crafty new single ``Thank U,'' already a radio staple, left
the crowd cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Morissette's band, expanded with the addition of keyboardist
Deron Johnson, also boasted a new second guitarist. But the
always-reliable Nick Lashley anchored the proceedings with lashings
of sturdy rhythm and lead guitar work.
</P>
<P>
   The drummer, too, was worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   Morissette has retooled some of her best-known material,
including the petulant breakup breakthrough hit ``You Oughta Know''
and the title track of her multimillion-selling Maverick debut.
</P>
<P>
   The new disc, ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie,'' is due
Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the spindly Morissette still seems somewhat awkward,
saying little between songs and making strange, jerky movements.
But it's clear that performance and composing act as some type of
therapy for her, with her primary goal being emotional honesty.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the freewheeling singer has such a vast, apparently
loyal audience that touches on nearly all demographic groups. A
song such as ``Hand in My Pocket,'' for example, can be equally
understood by a 4-year-old listening to Radio Disney and a boomer
tuned into KBIG-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Forthcoming tracks such as ``Baba'' and ``Are You Still Mad''
show the onetime child TV star has grown musically in the past two
years, during which she collaborated with Ballard at his Woodland
Hills home.
</P>
<P>
   On first listen, some of the songs have unusual structures with
subtle shifts in mood and tempo. They also have powerful dynamics
that keep the listener interested. Can't wait to hear the entire
album.
</P>
<P>
   The impression above all Wednesday was the strength of
Morissette's piercing delivery.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Infatuation Junkie'' comes out,'' you'll know it, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
