r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPS-FLATS-COLUMN-L     10-15 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-FLATS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KO K OMO   DID SOUL, R&AMP;B RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR;  &LR; _ Kokomo.
</P>
<P>
   To many, it's simply the name of a half-forgotten Beach Boys
single from 1988. To others, it's a small city in central Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also one of the greatest '70s soul revues you've
never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Kokomo had two strikes against it right off the
bat. The musicians, a mix of seasoned session players and
newcomers, were white and British _ although they didn't sound like
it.
</P>
<P>
   From 1974 to 1982, when this supremely talented band cut three
excellent yet hard-to-find platters for Columbia and toured the
States opening for Average White Band, there just wasn't a huge
demand for danceable funk and r&AMP;b, especially if the group on stage
wasn't Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire, Kool &AMP; the Gang or Tower of Power.
</P>
<P>
   But Kokomo had something special, including a tight, imaginative
rhythm section, several first-rate soloists, world-class vocalists
and an intuitive feel for fun and syncopation that extended to the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Others felt the same way. Pink Floyd's manager, Steve O'Rourke,
took the group under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member Kokomo boasted sophisticated originals like the
gorgeous r&AMP;b ballad ``Anytime,'' penned by guitarist Neil Hubbard,
who would play on a series of well-known records including the Roxy
Music classic ``Avalon'' and several Bryan Ferry solo albums side
by side with his longtime partner in funky rhythm, Kokomo
bassist-leader Alan Spenner.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the band's best material is collected on the anthology
``Kokomo: The Collection'' (Castle), which can be ordered through
the online mail-order shop at NME.com. Perhaps the group's
best-known track, an extended groove-alicious version of Bobby
Womack's ``I Can Understand It,'' turned up on the pub-rock
compilation ``Naughty Rhythms'' a couple of years back.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Kokomo was Spenner, a wry wit and thrilling
musician who acted as stoned master of ceremonies. After a
20-minute jam on an opening instrumental like Herbie Hancock's
``Chameleon'' or Funk Inc.'s ``Sister Jane,'' Spenner would
introduce ``the girls,'' Kokomo's superb vocal trio of Frank
Collins, Dyan Birch and Paddie McHugh.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, perennially late saxophonist Mel Collins, who went
on to record and tour with Eric Clapton, would show up on stage at
tightly packed London venues like the Hope &AMP; Anchor or Dingwall's
just in time to take a wailing tenor solo.
</P>
<P>
   Along with memorable numbers like ``Forever,'' ``It Ain't Cool
to Be Cool No More,'' ``Rise &AMP; Shine'' and ``Feeling This Way,''
Kokomo made covers of Aretha Franklin's ``Angel,'' Joe Tex's ``A
Mother's Prayer'' and the Pointer Sisters' ``Yes We Can Can'' their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Kokomo's secret weapons was guitarist Jim Mullen, a
powerfully built Scotsman who plucked a particularly soulful
Telecaster with his thumb. Years earlier, when he was part of Brian
Auger's Oblivion Express, Mullen was known as ``Jim the Thumb.''
Today, he leads a straight-ahead jazz quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the member of Kokomo to achieve the most recognition
was Boston-born conga player Jody Linscott, who joined up with
Robert Palmer, the Who and many others. She also penned a series of
children's books that did well on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   There were other fine soul-funk outfits on the far side of the
pond during those years _ AWB, FBI, Cado Belle, Gonzalez and Moon,
among them.
</P>
<P>
   But when a Kokomo reunion that had begun turning up in British
clubs in the late '80s grinded to a halt in 1991 when Spenner died,
it was a sad end to one of soul music's most neglected yet
inspirational bands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARBAGE-MUSIC-PROFILE     10-15 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-MUSIC-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBAGE DRUMMER GIVES A SAMPLE OF HIS WORK BATHED IN `ELECTRONICA' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many musicians can point to a defining moment when they knew,
absolutely, what they wanted to do with their lives. Butch Vig,
drummer/producer with the group Garbage, remembers his.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in the late '60s when he saw the Who perform live on
the Smothers Brothers television show. The band's drummer, Keith
Moon, wreaked havoc on the set, and a little kid in Wisconsin got
hooked on the anarchic spirit of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had a huge impact on me,'' Vig said. ``My mom was a music
teacher and had been making me play piano since I was like 5 years
old. I went, `Forget this. I want to learn how to play drums.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I never learned to play like Keith Moon,'' he added, laughing.
``I learned to play more like Charlie Watts, straight-ahead, 4/4
rock stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   With Garbage, which will perform a sold-out show Saturday at the
Aerial Theater in Houston, Vig is learning yet another way to play
the drums. When he hits the skins, it triggers electronic
sequencers programmed with samples and sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no acoustic drums,'' he said. ``I play acoustic drums,
but it triggers samples that we used on the records. I'm using a
much bigger drum sampler this time, so I can use sequencers in it.
Besides loops, there's a lot more sound effects.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vig adds that Garbage remains, fundamentally, a rock 'n'
roll band. He and his old college chums Duke Erikson and Steve
Marker are joined by lead vocalist Shirley Manson, the most
appealingly tempestuous female rock 'n' roll frontwoman since the
Pretenders' Chrissie Hynde.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still really are a rock band, and we write pop songs,'' Vig
said. ``But we love using technology to bring all these different
elements into the music. We use the dance grooves and electronica
and hip-hop and try to have all these different genres colliding
together to make the songs sound fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Garbage's self-titled 1995 debut album spawned several modern
rock hits including ``Queer,'' ``Vow,'' ``Only Happy When It
Rains'' and ``Stupid Girl.'' These songs combined killer melodic
hooks with state-of-the-art studio technology and electronic dance
textures. The album went on to sell more than 4 million copies
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The follow-up, ``Version 2.0,'' was released a little more than
five months ago. The first single from the album, ``Push It,''
proudly nodded to influences as disparate as the Beach Boys and
Salt 'n' Pepa. While it has yet to be certified gold in the United
States, ``Version'' has sold 2 million copies internationally. In
England, Garbage is a stadium headliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided from Day One that we wanted to be an international
band,'' Vig said. ``We didn't necessarily want to focus on one
country. And we've done really well all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Vig met Erikson and Marker while attending film school at the
University of Wisconsin in Madison. Erikson later joined Vig in the
band Firetown, which released a couple of critically acclaimed
albums of heartland rock in the mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   After Firetown's second album failed to live up to record label
expectations, Vig turned to production. Working out of his home
studio in Madison, he developed good relationships with such
indie-rock labels as Mammoth, Touch &AMP; Go, Twin Tone and SubPop.
</P>
<P>
   By 1991, he had produced and/or engineered close to 300 albums,
none of which were major hits. Then he produced the album that
changed the direction of rock music in the '90s, Nirvana's
``Nevermind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I finished it, there was a huge buzz on it, but I
had no idea it would blow up and affect people critically and
commercially the way that it did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to make a good punk record. The difference
is that there were amazing songs on there, so many amazing hooks.
And Kurt had sort of an enigma that was fascinating. You could
hear, coming out of his voice, something that a lot of people don't
have.''
</P>
<P>
   After Nirvana, Vig worked on high-profile albums by Smashing
Pumpkins, Sonic Youth, Soul Asylum, L7 and others. He became
fascinated with hip-hop and samplers while working on remix
projects for U2 and Nine Inch Nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we'd do a remix, we'd erase all the tracks except the
vocals and record new music,'' he said. ``That was the first time I
got into playing again. And that was the inspiration that got us to
start Garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   The band was looking for a female singer when Marker saw Manson
on MTV singing with her previous band, Angel Fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in love with just her singing,'' Vig said. ``There's
not a lot of histrionics, not a lot of screaming or angst. And that
was radically different compared to a lot of the other female
singers at the time, who to me either sounded really girlie or they
screamed all the way through songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea that she was going to turn into this pop diva.
We told her we wanted her to write with us, produce with us, to be
an equal member of this band. She had never had that opportunity
before, and she kind of took the ball and ran with it. She's
totally blossomed as an artist, a frontperson and a singer.''
</P>
<P>
   If one word could be used to describe Manson's no-nonsense stage
presence and sexually-charged lyrics, it would be ``attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the lyrics come directly from her,'' Vig said. ``She's
brutally honest. She didn't make up this character to become a pop
diva in Garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of the most real and most complicated people that I
know. She's very emotional and outspoken. She can be extremely
vulnerable and fragile, and then tough as nails 15 minutes later.
It's a roller-coaster ride with her, and it can be sometimes
exasperating, but it's also what keeps it so interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well aware now that Shirley's become the focal point of
the band. That's a natural thing to happen. If you look at Bono
with U2 or Michael Stipe with R.E.M., they are pretty much a
mouthpiece of the band. Shirley's become the mouthpiece for
Garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Vig adds that the fact all the members are older and have been
in bands before has allowed them to make decisions democratically.
Not everyone gets what he or she wants all the time, but members
sacrifice their individual egos for the good of the band.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the grunge era Vig helped launch with Nirvana is coming
to a close, rock music is waiting for another guiding direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone keeps saying rock is dead, but it's not dead,'' Vig
said. ``It may get a little stagnant, but it always roars back.
Something's going to twist it up and come out and light a torch to
it, but nobody knows what that is and that's what's exciting about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that our first record caught a lot of people
off-guard. Now, I've heard a lot of Garbage clones, trying to do
what we do with all these different elements. But I still think
that, ultimately, you have to be able to write a good song.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
