<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WINE &AMP; FOOD CLASSIC GETS OFF TO FINE START 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woman tugged on my sleeve. ``Have you tried the
Fredericksburg Muscat Hamburg? It's yummy!''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I said, I already had tried it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' she said, ``when I heard this was going to be just
Texas wines, I thought, `Eewww ...' But some of these are really
good. I'm very surprised!''
</P>
<P>
   She probably wasn't the only one. Fact is, while some small
Texas wineries continue to produce amateurish efforts, others have
made noticeable strides in upgrading the quality of their wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' was the first Texas Wine &AMP; Food Classic, held at the
Doubletree Hotel in Houston. With the demise of the Houston Club's
annual tribute to Texas wines, there was a void here. Now the
Classic, under the aegis of the Food and Beverage Managers
Association of Houston, appears to be on solid footing, if the
crowds and the enthusiasm at the Doubletree event were any
indication.
</P>
<P>
   The Classic was organized primarily by Randy Fournier of Amerada
Hess Corp. and Guy Stout of Glazer's Wholesale Distributors. Jeff
Graves and Kevin Simon of the University of Houston Hilton College
of Hotel and Restaurant Management provided both a venue and help
for the wine judging preceding the event. Net proceeds of the Texas
Wine &AMP; Food Classic will benefit the UH Hilton Scholarship Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Classic featured not only more than half of Texas' wineries,
with many principals and winemakers on hand, but also indigenous
Texas foodstuffs, from beef to lamb to ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the event, I gathered 10 knowledgeable wine
consumers to judge Texas wines at the University of Houston's
Hilton College of Hotel and Restaurant Management.
</P>
<P>
   To make a wine competition successful, three factors come into
play: the participation of the wineries; the knowledge of the
judges; and the efficiency of the back-room staff in pouring the
wines, removing empty glasses, etc. If there's a breakdown in any
of the three areas, disaster beckons.
</P>
<P>
   We had no disaster.
</P>
<P>
   We got a good amount of entries (105), the judges knew their
business (and none had any ties to the Texas wine industry), and
the UH students in the back room did an outstanding job.
</P>
<P>
   I have judged at more than 30 major wine competitions across the
country, but this was the first time I was on the other side of the
table. Fortunately, I had such excellent help that once things got
under way, my main contribution was staying out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, here are the results of the first Texas Wine &AMP;
Food Classic wine competition:
</P>
<P>
   Gold medals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997 Messina Hof Chenin Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Llano Estacado ``Passionelle'' (Rhone-style red blend).
</P>
<P>
   1997 Llano Estacado ``Cellar Select'' Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Fredericksburg Winery ``Fort Martin Scott'' Muscat Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   Silver medals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997 Messina Hof Gewurztraminer.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Fall Creek Chenin Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Messina Hof Johannisberg Riesling.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Messina Hof ``Late Harvest'' Muscat Canelli.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Llano Estacado ``Signature Red.''
</P>
<P>
   1996 Llano Estacado Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Fall Creek ``Meritus.''
</P>
<P>
   1997 Fall Creek Sauvignon Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Becker Fume Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Llano Estacado Chenin Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Cap Rock ``Newsome Vineyards'' Cabernet Sauvignon
``Reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   1996 Llano Estacado ``Cellar Select'' Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   Bronze medals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997 Sister Creek Muscat Canelli.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Llano Estacado ``Signature White.''
</P>
<P>
   1997 Cap Rock ``Topaz Royale.''
</P>
<P>
   1997 Hidden Springs Muscat &QL; 
Canelli.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Llano Estacado Zinfandel.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Escondido Valley Pinot Noir.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Becker Cabernet Franc.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden Springs ``Ruby Glow'' (nonvintage).
</P>
<P>
   1996 Messina Hof ``Papa Paulo's Port Private Reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   1996 Messina Hof ``Barrel Reserve'' Sauvignon Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Becker Muscat Canelli ``Amabile.''
</P>
<P>
   1997 Escondido Valley Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Becker Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Messina Hof ``Double Barrel Private Reserve'' Cabernet
Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Fredericksburg ``Maximilian Sunflower'' Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Escondido Valley Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Becker ``Iconoclast'' Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the results, I wasn't surprised that Messina Hof in
Bryan and Llano Estacado in Lubbock took a fair share of the
medals; the wineries do a good job and also send a lot of entries.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I know that at least a couple of winery
owners were disappointed they didn't win anything; in one instance,
I think the owner was right. In the other _ well, perhaps better
wines would have garnered a better response from the judges.
</P>
<P>
   October is Texas Wine Month, and the Texas Wine &AMP; Food Classic
got the month off to a good start. Messina Hof Wine Cellars in
Bryan is the closest major winery to Houston; it's a 1 {-hour
drive, and there's something going on each weekend. Give Messina
Hof a call about upcoming events; 409-778-9463.
</P>
<P>
   Also, on Oct. 24-25, the Fredericksburg Food and Wine Festival
will be under way, if you plan on a drive to the Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, we don't call it ``the Grape State of Texas'' for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth _ straight, no chaser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail correspondence to: michael.lonsford at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
