<P>
   FILM-MIGHTY (Undated) _ ``The Mighty,'' is almost
point-for-point the same movie as last month's misfit-buddy movie,
``Simon Birch.'' Mercifully, this latest version of the tale is
less clumsily manipulative and maudlin than its predecessor. Even
so, it's underwhelming to the point that fans of director Peter
Chelsom's more accomplished first two films _ ``Hear My Song'' and
``Funny Bones'' _ could reasonably feel he's been hit by the junior
curse.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SHADRACH (Undated) _ It was surely not intentional, but
Susanna Styron's film version of her father William Stryon's short
story, ``Shadrach,'' plays so uncannily like an episode of the old
'70s TV series, ``The Waltons,'' that it must have been her primary
subconscious influence.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEVIL (Undated) _ ``Love is the Devil,'' a gritty film
about painter Francis Bacon, demands patience because it's like
reading excerpts from a naughty diary, written in code. The real
narrative flow is in the film's strong, gorgeous, evocative visual
rendering. It tells us tons about Bacon's art, as well as the man
himself. Better yet, it gives us a glimpse into the macabre vision
of Bacon and his tawdry fascination with the grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MAGIC (Undated) _ In ``Practical Magic,'' Nicole Kidman and
Sandra Bullock shine as sisters who have a bond so intense it's a
blessing as well as a curse. ``Practical Magic'' needs their
gung-ho talent and charisma to draw us in and they throw themselves
into this cauldron of dark, uncomfortable comedy with gusto,
conjuring more screen magic than the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
