<SLUG> BC-JERRY-GARCIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT PENDING IN LAWSUIT BROUGHT BY JERRY GARCIA'S EX-WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The monetary dispute between the widow of
Grateful Dead leader Jerry Garcia and his former wife is coming to
a rapid close, with both sides reaching an agreement that would pay
Carolyn ``Mountain Girl'' Adams-Garcia about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got tired of fighting,'' Adams-Garcia, the band
leader's former wife, said Wednesday night from her home near
Eugene, Ore. ``I felt like it would be in the best interests of
everyone in the family to put an end to it. It's not healthy to
keep the anxiety and trouble alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The musician's first wife sued the estate after Garcia died in
1995 at the age of 53. She contended that Garcia's widow, Deborah
Koons Garcia, had stopped alimony payments that Jerry Garcia had
been making to Adams-Garcia as part of a 1993 divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A Marin County judge ruled last year that the divorce settlement
between Jerry Garcia and Adams-Garcia was valid and ordered the
late musician's estate to pay nearly $5 million to Adams-Garcia.
Deborah Garcia appealed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Adams-Garcia said her attorneys negotiated a settlement with the
attorneys for the Garcia estate so that she could end the
litigation and move on. The agreement will go before Marin County
Probate Court for approval on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned about (losing on appeal) as much as I was
concerned about the stress factor of the family,'' Adams-Garcia
said. ``It was just time to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Garcia estate could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Adams-Garcia said there was brief discussion of a settlement
during the trial last year, but it went nowhere. She declined to
disclose the exact figure of the settlement but she said it was
about $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
