<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BELOVED-SPI &LR;      10-15 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BELOVED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BELOVED' FAILS TO LIVE UP TO EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many dedicated people have invested so much time and so many
good intentions into the screen version of Toni Morrison's novel,
``Beloved,'' that it's no fun to have to report that their work has
resulted in considerably less than a classic film.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey's legions of fans are likely to respond to it as a
star vehicle, and devoted readers of Nobel Laureate Morrison will
find it a stubbornly faithful adaptation of her 1987 Pulitzer
Prize-winning novel. With its knee-jerk feminist appeal, this could
be enough to carry the film to its much-predicted multi-Oscar
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But others are likely to be profoundly confused by its
meandering structure and frustrated by the minimal emotional return
to be had from the intense, demanding, near-three-hour investment
it requires.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in rural Ohio just after the Civil War with a
horrific, ``Exorcist''-ish teaser in an (apparently) haunted house
occupied by a family of ex-slaves headed by its middle-aged
matriarch, Sethe (Winfrey). It's a manifestation so violent that it
shakes the walls like an earthquake and pops an eye of the family
dog right out of its socket.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1873 and the story proper begins with a visit to the
house by Paul D (Danny Glover), another ex-slave who knew Sethe's
family before the war back at ``Sweet Home,'' the plantation to
which they were bound across the river in Kentucky. Paul D quickly
ingratiates himself with the family and into Sethe's bed.
</P>
<P>
   As Sethe brings Paul D up to date on her life, the film flashes
back to tell the story of her unusually humiliating gang rape by a
band of neanderthal whites, her flight from slavery while pregnant
and her escape to this Ohio farm owned by her mother-in-law (Beah
Richards), where Sethe's older children already are ensconced.
</P>
<P>
   As Paul D settles in, the major plot point comes when a
mysterious, mentally handicapped young woman named Beloved (Thandie
Newton) wanders inexplicably onto the farm one day. Taken in by the
family, she becomes the companion of Sethe's teenage daughter,
Denver (Kimberly Elise), but seems to have some malevolent designs
on Sethe.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the story continues to both jump forward to chronicle
Sethe's decline, and flash back to reveal more missing pieces of
her past, until it gradually becomes apparent who Beloved is and
what she represents. The audience gets a devastating whammy _ the
revelation of a secret that Morrison has set up to be the
``Sophie's Choice'' of American Slavery.
</P>
<P>
   To those who love the book, this secret metaphorically
encapsulates the experience of slavery and its horrible
repercussions. According to Winfrey, ``I felt that `Beloved' was
part of the reason I was born, to tell that story on screen. I
wanted to do with a movie what Toni Morrison had done with a book.
She allowed us to feel what slavery felt like ... to understand
what slavery did to (the) soul.''
</P>
<P>
   That soul-destroying horror definitely is communicated here, and
Winfrey's central performance is, if not truly Oscar-worthy, at
least quite respectable _ as are the performances of the rest of
the cast, especially Kimberly Elise. She steals the movie as the
reasonably unscathed daughter who seems to have a shot at rising
above the legacy of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie ``Beloved'' loses much of the emotional impact it
deserves by being a hopelessly muddled piece of basic storytelling.
As it flashes back and forth between the pre- and post-Civil War,
between Kentucky and Ohio, and between characters with
unestablished relationships, it's virtually impossible to stay
oriented in the story unless you've read the book.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is the strange fact that, in many of the
flashback scenes, the young adult version of Sethe is played by
another actress (Lisa Gay Hamilton), who doesn't much resemble
Winfrey. So it's quite possible to follow her through half the
movie thinking she's an entirely different character.
</P>
<P>
   Also confusing is the fact that the bold, Stephen King-like
scene that opens the movie is completely unfulfilled, virtually
forgotten, as the film moves along. A few of Sethe's hallucinations
aside, the occult premise seems to disappear. On the evidence of
the movie, it's not at all clear exactly what the metaphysical
scheme of this film is.
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat daunting running time also is an obstacle. Even
with its visual sweep, Director Steven Spielberg kept ``The Color
Purple'' at 152 minutes. ``Beloved'' is 20 minutes longer, and it's
framed mostly in tight, claustrophobic settings and at a Eugene
O'Neill intensity. The experience of sitting through it just wears
you out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of these complaints are the direct result of the
fact that producer-star Winfrey, her writers and her hand-picked
director, Jonathan Demme, (``The Silence of the Lambs'') have gone
to enormous lengths to be true to the novel. Morrison is such a
current cultural icon, and Winfrey is so worshipful of her, that
anything else would have been unconscionable.
</P>
<P>
   But movie history tells us that film adaptations, even those
that seem to be most faithful to their great novel sources _ `Gone
With the Wind,'' ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' ``The Color Purple'' _
invariably required massive changes, new scenes, new structure, new
ideas. ``Beloved'' could have used a little less reverence, a
little more creative initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Beloved. Directed by Jonathan Demme. Screenplay by Richard
LaGravenese and Adam Brooks. Cast: Oprah Winfrey, Danny Glover,
Thandie Newton, Kimberly Elise, Beah Richards. Disney/Touchstone.
172 minutes. Rated R for violent images, sexuality and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
