<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MIGHTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MIGHTY' IS MOSTLY UNDERWHELMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's penchant for releasing two films on roughly the same
subject at roughly the same time has become a true phenomenon of
our time. Can good ideas be in such short supply, or is this some
calculated scheme to share publicity costs?
</P>
<P>
   Much already has been made of the fact that this fall will see
two computer-animated insect movies, two Elizabethan England movies
(both starring Joseph Fiennes), two Robin William-as-a-doctor
movies and two effects-of-slavery sagas (both with Jonathan Demme
behind the camera).
</P>
<P>
   But here's yet another match in the '98 fall line-up that went
unnoticed from the studio hand-out plot descriptions: this week's
misfit-buddy movie, ``The Mighty,'' is almost point-for-point the
same movie as last month's misfit-buddy movie, ``Simon Birch.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, this latest version of the tale is less clumsily
manipulative and maudlin than its predecessor. Even so, it's
underwhelming to the point that fans of director Peter Chelsom's
more accomplished first two films _ ``Hear My Song'' and ``Funny
Bones'' _ could reasonably feel he's been hit by the junior curse.
</P>
<P>
   The larger and healthier of this film's high school duo is the
film's narrator, Max (Elden Henson), a big, withdrawn, socially
backward kid who lives with his grandparents (Gena Rowlands and
Harry Dean Stanton) and is traumatized by a mysterious event in his
past involving his imprisoned father.
</P>
<P>
   His more vulnerable pal is Kevin (Kieran Culkin, 15 year-old
brother Macaulay), a severely handicapped but very smart and brave
boy who suffers from a degenerative, ultimately terminal disease in
which his body organs keep growing while his bones do not.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculed by their impossibly cruel Cincinnati schoolmates, the
two strike back by combining their assets _ Kevin's brain and Max's
brawn _ to become, in effect, a single unit: little Kevin sits on
Max's shoulders as if riding a horse, and they storm around their
inner-city neighborhood like an Arthurian Knight, fighting bullies,
righting wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   In its best moments, ``The Mighty'' manages to be sporadically
touching. Its ensemble of lower-middle class characters seem, for
the most part, believable, and its two teenage leads are admirably
devoid of the child-star cutsies _ especially Henson, who's been
well cast for his air of anti-social awkwardness.
</P>
<P>
   The film also provides a nice change-of-pace role for Sharon
Stone, who's surprisingly poignant in her handful of scenes as
Kevin's hard-pressed single mom. And it offers an even greater
stretch for Gillian Anderson (``The X-Files''), who is less
effective as the gang moll with a heart of gold who helps the boys
in their time of greatest need.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if you can forgive and forget its glaring similarity
to ``Simon Birch,'' the film doesn't come together to be anything
half as magical as it obviously wants to be. Its third-act
kidnapping subplot is particularly heavy-handed, its King Arthur
analogy always seems forced and too many of Chelsom's scenes simply
ring amazingly false.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty. Directed by Peter Chelsom. Screenplay by Charles
Leavitt. Cast: Sharon Stone, Elden Henson, Kieran Culkin, Gena
Rowlands, Gillian Anderson. Miramax. 106 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
elements of violence and peril.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
