A8781 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SHADRACH-SPI &LR;      10-15 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHADRACH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHADRACH' IS TV-SCALE MORALITY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was surely not intentional, but Susanna Styron's film version
of her father William Stryon's short story, ``Shadrach,'' plays so
uncannily like an episode of the old '70s TV series, ``The
Waltons,'' that it must have been her primary subconscious
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Her film is set in rural Virginia during the depth of the
Depression; it involves a large, close-knit, economically
struggling family; and it's narrated by a grown-up version of the
boy hero _ in an aristocratic voice that could well pass for Earl
Hamner Jr.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a small-scale, not-terribly-ambitious morality tale
that resolves itself rather neatly, TV-style, by the end, yet _
very much in ``The Waltons'' tradition _ leaves us with a certain
wistful, bittersweet poignancy. Goodnight, John Boy.
</P>
<P>
   We see the story from the point-of-view of Paul (Scott Tera) a
pre-teen who, when his parents go to Baltimore for a funeral, gets
to stay with the neighboring Dabney family: father Vernon (Harvey
Keitel), mother Trixie (Andie MacDowell) and their brood of kids.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his visit, a 99-year-old ex-slave named Shadrach (John
Franklin Sawyer) wanders onto the property very near death. He
tells the Dabneys he once belonged to their ancestors and wants to
die on the old Dabney plantation _ an overgrown ruin some distance
away, which Vernon still owns, and where he makes his illegal
moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon packs up Paul, the ailing Shadrach and the whole Dabney
family and makes the journey to the old home. But complications
ensue when the county sheriff tells Vernon the law now forbids
burials on private property. Thus, he will have to hire an
undertaker and have Shadrach buried in an authorized graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dabneys have no money, this is a big problem _ and,
ultimately, a moral dilemma for Vernon. It's as if fate has
conspired to make him face up to the lingering evil of his
ancestor's slave-owning past _ even though his own poverty and
white-trash social status make him as much a victim of slavery as
Shadrach.
</P>
<P>
   As he struggles to sort out the mess, the film ingratiates
itself with an incorrigibly sweet spirit; some engaging, down-home
comic situations; and winning performances by Keitel as a
frustrated man in a strange conflict with his destiny, and
MacDowell as his beer-guzzling but ultra-patient, very controlled
wife.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that director Styron never makes us ``feel'' the
important karmic kinship of Vernon and Shadrach, Vernon's moral
dilemma is resolved by a cop-out ending, and _ enjoyable as they
are in most of their scenes _ Keitel and MacDowell are never, for
one minute, believable as Depression-era Southern farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Shadrach. Directed by Susanna Styron. Written by Susanna Styron
and Bridget Terry. Cast: Harvey Keitel, Andie MacDowell, John
Franklin Sawyer, Scott Terra. 86 minutes. Rated PG-13 for language
and brief sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
