A8785 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BACON-SPI &LR;      10-15 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BACON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE IS THE DEVIL' SHINES SPOTLIGHT ON DARK WORLD OF FRANCIS
BACON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a strong stomach to wade through the demonic dysphoria
of Francis Bacon's world. The British painter was lauded for his
excessive, even hellish, paintings of humanity. Few know that many
were modeled upon his longtime lover, a low-class ``rent boy'' and
thief named George Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon achieved fame in the '60s and '70s. He was heralded as the
greatest living painter by the French in 1971, but privately his
life was like ``a bomb exploding in reverse.'' A carouser, drinker,
wit and openly gay artist who suffered from painter's block,
Bacon's motto _ ``pleasure is impossible to define; horror is of
much the same nature'' _ extended to his claustrophobic, bloody,
hallucinogenic work, as well as his passion for rough trade and
rougher sex.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, brawny Dyer (Daniel Craig) fits the bill. But
Bacon's (Derek Jacobi) razor tongue soon slashes Dyer to bloody
shreds. He so eclipses his lover in both brains and talent that the
young man erodes into an obsessive mess of suicidal tendencies and
frightening dreams that foretell his own destruction. He relies
upon pills and booze to ease his growing fright and weariness with
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon calls him ``a compulsive joke which no one knew was
funny.'' But one night Dyer stops being a bad joke and becomes
Bacon's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   English director John Maybury began his career in music videos
and graduated to featurettes like ``Man to Man,'' which starred the
late Derek Jarman's favorite actor, Tilda Swinton. Maybury received
some of his film and art training from Jarman, and Jarman's
stylized, and very personal work, strongly influenced him. But
Maybury has surpassed his master with ``Love is the Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   The film certainly isn't a linear biography. It demands patience
because it's like reading excerpts from a naughty diary, written in
code. The real narrative flow is in the film's strong, gorgeous,
evocative visual rendering. It tells us tons about Bacon's art
(though his paintings were not allowed to be used in the film), as
well as the man himself. Better yet, it gives us a glimpse into the
macabre vision of Bacon and his tawdry fascination with the
grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is the Devil'' is reminiscent of the Stephen Frears film,
``Prick Up Your Ears,'' which also was about a gay artist
(playwright Joe Orton) with a doomed lover. Yet, it's more
compelling because of its visual style and gritty realism.
Ultimately, this, plus the performances, make ``Love is the Devil''
more sympathetic and eerily moving.
</P>
<P>
   While Sir Derek Jacobi is riveting as Bacon, stage actor Daniel
Craig works miracles by supplying its heart and finding something
extraordinary in the very ordinary, sadly haunted, Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   Love is the Devil. Directed by John Maybury. Written by John
Maybury. Cast: Derek Jacobi, Daniel Craig, Tilda Swinton, Anne
Lambton. Strand Releasing. 90 minutes. Unrated, with nudity,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8817 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CLINTON-1000&AMP;     10-15 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CLINTON-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
...AND THE HORSE HE RODE IN ON
</HEADLINE>
  The People v. Kenneth Starr 
 By James Carville 
 176 pp. New York: Simon &AMP; Schuster. $14.95 
 THE CLINTON ENIGMA 
 A Four-and-a-Half-Minute Speech Reveals This President's Entire
Life 
 By David Maraniss 
 110 pp. New York: Simon &AMP; Schuster. $1 
 ------ 
 PREACHING TO THE CONVERTED 
 By JONATHAN LEAR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I find myself waiting for a New Yorker cocktail-party cartoon in
which the hostess says to a guest, ``Come meet Jason, he's the one
who hasn't written about the Lewinsky affair.'' Few events in
American history, at the time of their occurrences, have caused a
wider group of journalists, commentators, academics and politicians
to try to capture its significance. Indeed, part of what it is to
be a citizen today is to have had a conversation with one's
friends, colleagues and neighbors about what, in this whole mess,
matters. For though a federal judge said the Paula Jones lawsuit is
without merit, the case has functioned like the shot at Sarajevo in
1914: it brought to the cultural battlefield so many moral,
political, legal, sexual and esthetic issues that one has to
perform triage just to formulate a point of view.
</P>
<P>
   According to James Carville, ``it's the prosecutor, stupid!''
The fundamental evil is Kenneth W. Starr's abuse of a bad law to
subvert our democratic institutions and upend a presidential
election. ``...And the Horse He Rode In On'' doesn't pretend to be
anything other than it is: a full-throttle partisan critique, a
loud cry of ``foul play!'' For those who enjoy an occasional fix of
tabloid reading, this is what it would be like to read The New York
Post if it were owned by a billionaire Friend, rather than Enemy,
of Bill. Tabloid journalism tends, by its very nature, to preach to
the converted. But it tries to give them reasons for thinking that
their outlook is the right one. Since many Americans think that the
independent counsel exceeded his proper bounds, and many also
suspect that he has a vendetta on his mind, this is a piece of
tabloid writing for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Carvillean world looks something like this: First, there is
a right-wing conspiracy out to get Clinton. Among the most
prominent manifestations: Richard Mellon Scaife, the conservative
fourth-generation heir to a banking fortune, gave $1.7 million to
an ``Arkansas Project'' to dredge for dirt on President Clinton,
and actually ended up subsidizing scurrilous rumors. This money
found its way into the pockets of various unsavory characters,
among them David L. Hale, the only person willing to testify to
financial wrongdoing on Clinton's part in Whitewater. Another
manifestation: Judge David B. Sentelle conspired with Senators
Jesse Helms and Lauch Faircloth to remove Robert B. Fiske Jr. as
independent counsel and replace him with Kenneth W. Starr, a
right-wing Clinton-hater with blatant conflicts of interest willing
to take a poorly thought out statute to excess. After four years
and over $40 million, Carville notes, the only thing he produced
was a pornographic book and film with the president a reluctant
star. From bankruptcy to ``Boogie Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Carville argues, there has been a corrupt, and somewhat
unwitting, alliance between the press and the office of the
independent counsel. For the press, the ideal of Watergate
degenerated over a quarter-century into a competitive and
irresponsible scramble to uncover scandal. This led, in the first
instance, to confused reporting and the enhancement of rumors. More
important, Carville asserts, the press collaborated in trial by
leaks and rumors. To take one of the 24 examples he puts forward, a
``top official with the investigation'' told a journalist from The
New Yorker there was a 50-50 chance that the First Lady would be
indicted; this bounced its way around the world, defaming Hillary
Rodham Clinton and leading to nothing, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Carville's central thesis is breathtakingly simple: Ken
Starr is a creep. Carville begins with an unsettling vignette. In
October 1993, before he was appointed independent counsel, Starr,
then a perfect stranger, approached Carville (who is still an
adviser to Clinton) at Washington National Airport and started
haranguing him. ``Your boy's getting rolled,'' he said. Carville
buttresses his litany with the familiar and the less so, including
agents of Starr's office going to subpoena the 16-year-old son of a
Whitewater defendant at his school.
</P>
<P>
   Carville writes with the voice of Huckleberry Finn. Imagine that
Huck spent his early 20s on a plantation that Margaret Thatcher
bought for her retirement. She took him under her wing, and though
none of her views rubbed off on him, her in-your-face political
style did. ``I don't like Ken Starr,'' Carville says. ``I don't
like one damn thing about him.'' This book makes virtually no
mention of the many legitimate grounds for complaint one might have
about Clinton's behavior; it makes no mention of mitigating
circumstances or alternative explanations of Starr's methods.
Nevertheless, by the end of the book, I was convinced that there is
one certain good that has emerged from the Lewinsky affair: Kenneth
Starr will never serve on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, David Maraniss's book, ``The Clinton Enigma,'' does
pretend to be something it is not. The subtitle suggests
intriguingly that ``A Four-and-a-Half-Minute Speech Reveals This
President's Entire Life.'' Perhaps the president's Aug. 17 speech
does, but you won't find that out in this book. Indeed, the
strategy Maraniss uses is almost precisely the reverse: as
Clinton's biographer, he uses what he knows about Clinton's life
and personality to try to illuminate the speech. But even read that
way, the book is a failure.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking about the narrative is how staged it is. It
begins with Maraniss placing himself at the edge of the drama: ``I
suppose it had to come to this, I thought to myself as I sat in the
darkness of the NBC studio.'' And on to Chapter 2: ``Memories of
other encounters with Clinton came back to me as I waited in the
studio for him to deliver his fateful speech.'' What an
accommodating inner life Maraniss has, flowing along in just the
right way to begin his next book. I was reminded of a B movie in
which a reporter is waiting in the audience, the camera closes in
on his head, on his eye, and suddenly you are inside a flashback.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-CLINTON-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; (UNDATED: flashback.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the argument that it is somehow psychologically
revealing that Clinton ducked being interviewed by Maraniss. After
his biography, ``First in His Class,'' came out, Maraniss had heard
that Clinton ``hated the half of it that was critical of him and
that had revealed the patterns of his duplicity.'' Dick Morris told
him that ``the few portions of the book that examined his sex life
upset the First Lady so much that she had turned 'frosty' on the
President for several weeks.'' Yet it strikes Maraniss as
``peculiar'' that Clinton doesn't want to see him. After all, his
account was ``mild'' compared with some of the salacious stories
being printed and, anyway, ``Mrs. Clinton had been dealing with her
husband's waywardness for more than two decades -- why would my
book trigger such a fierce reaction?'' Is this a man you want to
turn to for psychological insight? (As for the ``fierce reaction,''
it seems just a simple interview-evasion technique, straight out of
Political Survival 101.)
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss is hurt that Clinton won't see him. In a ``final
memory,'' Clinton does come up to Maraniss to congratulate him on
winning an award and has little more to say than ``nice tie.''
Later, when George Stephanopoulos tells him the obscenity ``nice
tie'' is code for, Maraniss doesn't pause to wonder what
Stephanopoulos is doing; he simply joins the club of rejected,
angry men impelled to write about their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   When we purportedly get to the speech, in Chapter 5, what we
really get is a rambling association of family-history cliches and
psychobabble: ``For every shadow of darkness in Hot Springs, there
was a corresponding ray of light''; ``The men had a way of
compartmentalizing their lives''; ``Clinton's tendency toward
denial''; ``He might have a sexual addiction''; ``There is ample
evidence of powerful men whose political ambitions seemed matched
only by their sexual appetites''; ``Hillary's role as defender and
perhaps enabler''; ``his razor-sharp ambition''; ``The need to
rationalize was always there with Clinton,'' and so on. The
banality comes to feel like an assault. The only moment of relief
comes toward the end of the book, when, trying to explain the deep
animosity some people have for Clinton, Maraniss says, ``My answers
have never fully satisfied me.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lear is John U. Nef Distinguished Service Professor at
the University of Chicago and a member of the Committee on Social
Thought. His most recent book is ``Open Minded: Working Out the
Logic of the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
