<HEADER>
A8818 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MICROSOFT-NYT     10-15 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MICROSOFT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MICROSOFT FILE
</HEADLINE>
  The Secret Case Against Bill Gates 
 By Wendy Goldman Rohm 
 Illustrated. 313 pp. New York: Times Business/Random House. $25.95 
 ------ 
 THEY DO WINDOWS 
 By JOHN MARKOFF 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Bill Gates. Not so long ago, the world's richest man was
almost universally acclaimed as a computer hacker turned
information-age visionary. But now that image is coming under
increasing attack. The comparisons are no longer to contemporaries
like Steven P. Jobs but to John D. Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   In the revised view of Gates and his empire, the Microsoft
Corporation's business practices are predicated not on innovation
but on the leverage the company maintains through its control of
the Windows operating system, the software that serves as the
traffic cop for the overwhelming majority of the world's personal
computers. A growing chorus of critics asserts that the operating
system has given Microsoft extraordinary power over its
competitors. The blame is placed squarely on Gates's shoulders for
creating a corporate culture that has systematically imitated
technological innovation and then destroyed industry pioneers with
slash-and-burn business dealings. The critics say that by
arbitrarily redefining what is part of the operating system, by
tying new services and software applications to the program and by
attempting to extend Windows into new markets like cable
television, Microsoft has violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The darker side of Gates and Microsoft is explored in ``The
Microsoft File,'' by Wendy Goldman Rohm, who has reported on the
computer industry for many years. She sets out to draw an
unflattering portrait of Gates and his company based in part on
documents from the antitrust suits that are now swirling around
Microsoft. To her credit, she has unearthed new documents and
incidents, largely dating back to the early 1990's, when Microsoft
was concerned about a competing operating system, DR-DOS, designed
by Digital Research.
</P>
<P>
   There are intriguing parallels in the tactics she describes that
appear to foreshadow events in the more recent war between
Microsoft and the Netscape Communi ncations Corporation. In both
cases, Microsoft was threatened by a company that attacked its
operating-system monopoly. In each case, Microsoft used its
licensing power over personal computer makers to freeze out a
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, for example, Vobis Microcomputer was a major
personal computer maker that in the early 1990's sold its machines
with DR-DOS rather than Microsoft's MS-DOS. According to Rohm,
Microsoft first undercut the DR-DOS price and then insisted that
Vobis sign a per-processor licensing agreement. By linking its
operating-systems license to the availability of its Word and Excel
word-processing and spreadsheet programs, Microsoft's German sales
manager was able to persuade Vobis to stop offering DR-DOS.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, years later Microsoft sent a letter to the Compaq
Computer Corporation threatening to end its license for Windows if
it continued to include Netscape's Navigator Web browser. It was
that action that led Netscape's president, James Barksdale, to
approach the Justice Department about antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   But while ``The Microsoft File'' uncovers previously unknown
though largely dated evidence documenting Microsoft's predatory
business practices, the book fails in its broader attempt to take
the reader inside Gates's mind. Hanging much of the narrative on a
romantic triangle involving a former female Microsoft executive,
Gates and his head attorney, William Neukom, Rohm attempts to tell
us what Gates was thinking. It doesn't work. The reader is given no
hint of how Rohm, who apparently spent no time interviewing Gates
about personal subjects, would have found out about such details.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the stories may have emerged from pillow
talk by participants that she hints she has had access to. But if
that is the case, why revert to more perfunctory attribution with
the standard ``according to an insider present at the time''?
Unfortunately, what the reader is left with is a one-dimensional
picture of the man who has defined the industry for more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   John Markoff covers the computer industry for The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
