<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
  By SCOTT VEALE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 THE BOYS: 
 The Untold Story of 732 Young Concentration Camp Survivors 
 By Martin Gilbert. Owl/Holt, $16.95  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A seasoned custodian of the memory of the Holocaust puts a human
face on the catastrophe by letting a remarkable group of mostly
Polish Jews recall their childhood ordeals. Last year our reviewer,
Michael R. Marrus, called this a ``remarkable volume . . . about
survival and painful, vivid, individual memories of surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BELIEVERS: &QL; 
 &UR; A Novella and Stories &QL; 
 &UR; By Charles Baxter &QL; 
 &UR; Vintage Contemporaries, $13 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These psychologically dense tales track the unpredictable
destinies of ordinary Midwesterners, often focusing on the internal
struggle between the forces of love and violence. ``It's the
eloquence of the language -- the quirky intelligence, the humor,
the lively rhythmic assurance of sentences and paragraphs -- along
with the surprising plots, that makes these stories such a pleasure
to read,'' Francine Prose said here last year. The same publisher
has reissued an earlier collection by the author,  &UR; ``Through the
Safety Net: Stories'' &LR;  ($13), which features many middle-class
characters estranged from life -- a couple paralyzed by the death
of their child, for example, or a perpetual graduate student dazed
by the real world. In 1985 in the Book Review, Ron Hansen called
these 11 stories ``original, gracefully written, always moving,
frequently funny and -- that rarest of compliments -- wise.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEARER, MY GOD: &QL; 
 &UR; An Autobiography of Faith &QL; 
 &UR; By William F. Buckley Jr. &QL; 
 &UR; Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The author may be an imposing public intellectual but he's also
a devout Christian, and this unusually personal essay is both a
celebration of his lifelong Roman Catholicism and a doctrinal
apologia for the church. ``It is certain to provide many insights
into the mind of a polished writer . . . and it will do much to
explain how the hopefully changeless faith of a Catholic jibes with
the politics of a late-20th-century American political
conservative,'' William R. Everdell wrote here in 1997. In
 &UR; ``Living Faith,'' &LR;  by Jimmy Carter (Times Books/Random House, $13),
the former president laces his spiritual self-portrait with poems,
Scripture and frank revelations about his personal and political
lives. The book, which includes a new preface by Carter, is ``an
appealing, straightforward account of a life marked, as many are,
by unexpected successes and crushing failures,'' Michael Wright
said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUCKY YOU &QL; 
 &UR; By Carl Hiaasen &QL; 
 &UR; Warner Vision, $7.50 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JoLayne Lucks doesn't have much good fortune in the romance
department, but things look up when she wins half of a $28 million
prize in the Florida lottery: the trouble is, the other winners are
two dirtball white supremacists who aim to rip her off. ``Hiaasen
writes witty dialogue that crackles, and his characters are
eccentrically colorful,'' Charles Salzberg said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Goldwyn: A Biography &QL; 
 &UR; By A. Scott Berg &QL; 
 &UR; Riverhead, $16 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The legendary mogul who set Hollywood in motion was an inspired
ruffian whose outsize ambitions and appetites make for terrific
reading. ``This story of a grabby but imaginative man would make a
more telling movie about America . . . than Goldwyn ever produced
himself,'' Mordecai Richler wrote here in 1989. On a smaller stage,
 &UR; ``How I Made a Hundred Movies in Hollywood and Never Lost a
Dime,'' &LR;  by Roger Corman with Jim Jerome (Da Capo, $14.95),
explains how the schlockmeister responsible for fare like ``Bloody
Mama'' was able to become a major independent force in filmmaking
while running an absurdly tight ship. ``Corman comes across as
likable, admirable and, in his ability to survive in Hollywood with
his integrity intact, even awe-inspiring,'' Barry Gewen wrote here
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BYRNE &QL; 
 &UR; By Anthony Burgess &QL; 
 &UR; Carroll &AMP; Graf, $10.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The author's final novel is an audacious hybrid even for a
lifelong experimentalist: the story of a minor modern composer
whose real skills are in the bedroom unfolds in novelistic fashion
but entirely in rhymed verse. Last year our reviewer, Dana Gioia,
called this ``genuinely astonishing -- a complex dark comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PLATYPUS AND THE MERMAID: &QL; 
 &UR; And Other Figments of the Classifying Imagination &QL; 
 &UR; By Harriet Ritvo &QR; 
 &UR; Harvard University, $15.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A history professor chronicles the Victorian obsession with
classifying and categorizing God's creatures, particularly as they
relate to man and the dinner table. Last year in the Book Review,
Stefan Collini called this an ``entertaining and informative tour
of both the highroads and the hedgerows of natural history.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEEN ANGEL: &QL; 
 &UR; And Other Stories of Wayward Love &QL; 
 &UR; By Marianne Gingher &QL; 
 &UR; Zuckerman Cannon, $14 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The adolescent characters who populate these inventive tales
somehow manage to be both quirky and down to earth despite the
broken adult relationships around them. ``Gingher possesses a
stylistic deftness and a flair for comic detail,'' W. L. Taitte
said here in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAGICIAN'S ASSISTANT &QL; 
 &UR; By Ann Patchett &QL; 
 &UR; Harvest, $13 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a gay Los Angeles magician named Parsifal dies suddenly, he
leaves behind his heartbroken assistant, Sabine, and a secret past
that leads her to Nebraska and a family she never knew he had. Last
year our reviewer, Suzanne Berne, called the author ``an adroit,
graceful writer.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
