<HEADER>
A8824 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-YEAR-NYTSF     10-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-YEAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY YEAR OFF
</HEADLINE>
  By Robert McCrum 
 231 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $23.95 
 ------ 
 COMMOTION IN THE BRAIN 
 By ABRAHAM VERGHESE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a trick to ordinary living that has to do with pushing
far from the mind all thoughts of the maladies that befall hundreds
of people every day. Resolutely, we ignore newspaper headlines that
remind us of the dangers lurking in the workplace, on the freeway
and even (thanks to radon) in the basement. And we ignore the
annoying paradox that when we are having the most fun we are often
doing things that might be bad for us.
</P>
<P>
   This is why illness comes most often as a shock, as if the veil
has been stripped away to show us how vulnerable we really are.
Coleridge noted that it is the convalescent who sees the world in
its true colors. Indeed, illness has stimulated many a writer to
look back: one thinks immediately of Harold Brodkey's AIDS memoir,
``This Wild Darkness: The Story of My Death,'' and Anatole
Broyard's ``Intoxicated by My Illness.'' What makes Robert McCrum's
story distinctive is that the stroke that felled him affected the
very part of the body that must recall the illness and find the
language to describe what happened, even as language and speech
themselves are disrupted. This quality of the brain observing
itself is what gives ``My Year Off'' its particular poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   When his stroke occurred, Robert McCrum was just 42 years old;
he was the editor in chief of Faber &AMP; Faber, the London publishing
house, and also an acclaimed writer. He had been married a mere two
months (to Sarah Lyall, a journalist who writes for The New York
Times) when he awoke one morning unable to get out of bed. His wife
was away in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to drive to Cambridge that morning to visit my
parents. So, time to get up. But there it was -- I could not move.
More accurately, I could not move my left side. Overnight, my body
had become a dead weight.'' In attempting to get off the bed, he
fell to the floor and then half-fell, half-crawled down the stairs.
It took him all day, slipping in and out of consciousness, to get
to the downstairs phone and make the call for help. At the
hospital, it was clear that he had suffered a cerebral hemorrhage,
for which no obvious cause (such as raised blood pressure or an
aneurysm) was apparent.
</P>
<P>
   During his convalescence, McCrum found ``the enforced leisure
and opportunity to explore myself, to analyze what made me tick and
to discover what mattered to me. Alone in my room, with only my
right arm functioning properly (my right leg, though intact, was of
no real use to me in this state), and with the demons of physical
exhaustion constantly at hand, I began to keep a diary.'' His wife
also kept one, and excerpts from both serve to reconstruct much of
what patient and spouse were feeling and thinking during these
difficult times.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two weeks after his stroke, McCrum copied out a passage
from Marcus Aurelius' ``Meditations'': ``In the life of a man, his
time is but a moment, his being an incessant flux, his senses a dim
rushlight, his body a prey of worms, his soul an unquiet eddy, his
fortune dark and his fame doubtful. In short, all that is of the
body is as coursing waters, all that is of the soul as dreams and
vapors; life a warfare, a brief sojourning in an alien land; and
after repute, oblivion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrum tells us that he ``read this through a veil of tears with
a shock of recognition, as if spoken to across a vast abyss of time
and history.'' A few days later, his wife wrote: ``Everyone keeps
asking me if he is going through personality changes. Quite a scary
question, because the truth is I'm not sure: is he impatient and
peremptory because of the combination of his normal self (before I
came along) and the frustration of his condition, or because of a
neurological problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Once the life-threatening possibility of a fresh stroke
subsided; McCrum's efforts revolved around rehabilitation, trying
to restore function to his paralyzed left arm and leg. Six weeks
after the stroke, ``when Sarah was taking off my socks in the
evening, we suddenly saw independent movement. There they were --
my left toes moving! It was like finding life on Mars.'' McCrum's
recovery was arduous, painful and complicated by depression, shame
and self-doubt. But gradually he learned to walk again, his speech
returned to almost normal and by the end of the book, a year and a
half after his stroke, he and his wife celebrated the arrival of a
baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   With its lucid, heartfelt prose, ``My Year Off'' gives voice to
the millions of people who suffer from strokes, a quarter of whom
are under the age of 65 and most of whom have some residual
weakness or dysfunction for the rest of their lives. More
important, this book is a testament to the parallel trials and the
courage of the family members of stroke victims.
</P>
<P>
   It is human nature to want to seek both causation (beyond the
obvious anatomical one) and meaning for an illness. McCrum believes
his stroke came about because ``I'd reached a point in my
professional life when I could almost literally not see my way
forward. So it came as a physical punctuation mark, a reminder from
my body to pause and to take stock. What I needed was a season of
vulnerability. In the language of psychobabble, I needed to get in
touch with myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   The meaning McCrum finds in his ordeal is astonishingly similar
to what others who suffer a catastrophic illness also discover: ``I
have learned, in short, that I am not immortal (the fantasy of
youth) and yet, strangely, in the process I have been renewed in my
understanding of family and, finally, of the only thing that really
matters: love.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Verghese is a professor of medicine at Texas Tech
University. His latest book is ``The Tennis Partner: A Doctor's
Story of Friendship and Loss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
