<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DAYS-NYTSF     10-15 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DAYS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUNDRED DAYS
</HEADLINE>
  By Patrick O'Brian 
 281 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $24 
 ------ 
 NAVAL GAZING 
 By PAUL KENNEDY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the early spring of 1815, and two elderly English naval
lieutenants are high up on the southern slopes of Gibraltar,
observing and commenting on a squadron of Royal Navy vessels under
Commodore Jack Aubrey coming steadily closer to the harbor:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderfully beautiful day, with a slight and varying
but reasonably favorable breeze at last: the sun blazed on the
various kinds of broom in flower, upon the Rock, upon the cistuses
and giant heath, while an uninterrupted stream of migrant birds,
honey buzzards, black kites, all the European vultures, storks both
black and white, bee eaters, hoopoes and countless hirundines
flowed across the sky amidst a general indifference; for all eyes
were fixed upon the middle distance, where the squadron had come
about on the starboard tack.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins the 19th of what are now popularly referred to as
the Aubrey-Maturin novels, about naval warfare, by Patrick O'Brian.
They are part of that genre of naval historical fiction that
stretches back to Frederick Marryat and C. S. Forester and reaches
forward to such contemporaries of O'Brian as Alexander Fullerton
and Alexander Kent -- a genre that seems to be booming in recent
years, and capturing male and female readers alike.
</P>
<P>
   That said, a reading of only the first few pages of any book in
the Aubrey-Maturin series would tell the readers that they were
being presented with something different from, and more than,
fictional accounts of naval actions and storms at sea. Battles
there are aplenty, and O'Brian matches Forester in the excitement,
detail and bloody realism of his reconstructions. But these naval
tales are blended into a larger panorama of Georgian society and
politics, science, medicine, botany and the whole conspectus of
contemporary Enlightenment knowledge about the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   Consider simply the above quotation, taken from the second
paragraph of ``The Hundred Days.'' The overall scene is about
British warships coming into Gibraltar; but only O'Brian among the
naval writers would think to slip into that long sentence on the
migrating birds, and detail specific types. How many other naval
authors, one wonders, would actually have known that the Strait of
Gibraltar is one of the great crossing points for the northward and
southward avian migrations, or even cared? By contrast, O'Brian's
works abound with captivating descriptions of fauna and flora all
over the globe, of classical concerts (with a Locatelli or Haydn
piece being expertly described), of gossip about the changing fate
of the Whigs and Tories at Westminster, all forming a rich and
varied complement to sections about naval rigging and life below
deck.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brian's brilliant device for making his works into more than
naval history is, of course, his invention of dual heroes, the
bluff and ultracompetent Aubrey being always accompanied by his
eccentric ship's surgeon, Stephen Maturin -- a naval surgeon, yes,
but also a highly regarded British intelligence agent, a former
Irish radical, a multilingual polymath, a natural philosopher with
a passion for beetles, sea creatures, birds and animals that often
tempts him to linger on strange shores when the impatient Aubrey is
urgent for the next battle. This character mix works so well, and
all is written so beautifully, that O'Brian's worldwide fans have
come to expect a new novel every year. ``The Hundred Days'' is this
season's offering, and there is no doubt the fans will like it.
</P>
<P>
   THE novel is set in the ``hundred days'' between Napoleon's
escape from Elba and his final defeat at Waterloo in mid-1815, and
our heroes must thwart dastardly efforts by Balkan mercenaries and
North African potentates to assist a Bonapartist victory. Naval
actions off the Adriatic coast, strenuous secret journeys into the
interior North African wastes by Maturin and a decisive battle to
seize a gold convoy attempting to run the Strait of Gibraltar are
typical high points of this tale, though always interspersed with
those special O'Brian features. As the creators of other paired
characters like Holmes and Watson or Spencer and Hawk long ago
discovered, once you have found a good fictional recipe, it doesn't
pay to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Is this, then, the end of the line for the O'Brian series?
Napoleon, against whom Aubrey and Maturin have waged an almost
personal battle through 19 works, is now en route -- on a Royal
Navy frigate -- to lasting exile on St. Helena; and the ``Great
War'' (as 19th-century Britons called it) is over. Yet, in the last
paragraph, as Aubrey's warship casts off from Gibraltar on its
passage home, he is urged to ``liberate Chile.'' Since the
real-life character whom it is thought Aubrey most resembles, the
great frigate captain Thomas Cochrane, left the Royal Navy in 1814
and went on to fight for Chile and Peru against Spanish rule in
South America, it seems a fair guess that our famous duo will
shortly reappear in that very hemisphere for further adventures.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kennedy is a professor of history at Yale University. His
books include ``The Rise and Fall of British Naval Mastery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
