<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FRANKENSTEIN-     10-15 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FRANKENSTEIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKENSTEIN
</HEADLINE>
  By Mary Shelley 
 Illustrated by Philippe Munch 
 255 pp. New York: Viking. Paper, $17.99. (Ages 12 and up) 
 FRANKENSTEIN 
 Adapted and illustrated by Chris Mould 
 Unpaged. New York: Oxford University Press. $16.99. (Ages 7 and
up) 
 ------ 
 By JAMES HYNES 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apart from scholars of Romanticism and students of genre
fiction, does anyone past the age of 18 ever read Mary Shelley's
``Frankenstein''? A number of books we read when we were young --
``The Lord of the Rings,'' ``The Red Badge of Courage'' -- have a
fighting chance of appealing when we're older, but ``Frankenstein''
is probably a once-in-a-lifetime experience. Let's face it: when
you're 11, ``Frankenstein'' is a disappointment. Even if a young
reader hasn't seen the 1931 James Whale film, the director's Gothic
imagery is deeply ingrained in our collective lizard brain. The
chief result of wading through Shelley's 19th-century prose in
one's youth is the sinking feeling of discovering that there's no
castle, no villagers with torches and pitchforks, no Igor. There
are no lightning rods or crackling sparks or humming machines; in
the novel, the creature's birth is treated offhandedly, in a
paragraph. And there's no Boris Karloff with neck bolts, lurching
gait and bad haircut; Shelley's monster is described only vaguely,
as huge, misshapen and hideous (the one consistency through all the
versions is Victor Frankenstein's clumsy workmanship).
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a shame, because, as this middle-aged reader is
happy to report, the novel ``Frankenstein'' is quite a read. It may
be the best prose work ever written by an 18-year-old. It's highly
Romantic, in the literary sense; there are pages of landscape
description, pages of passionate declarations and a good deal of
attractive torment and self-doubt, from both Victor Frankenstein
and his creation. In fact, the monster is a wonderfully appealing
character, likely to have a visceral appeal (so to speak) for an
adolescent: he's ungainly, misunderstood and often self-loathing.
He craves approval from others, hates the way he looks and thinks
all his problems would be solved if he only had a mate. In other
words, Frankenstein's monster is just another lonely teen-ager in
love.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading a youngster who's probably already reading Stephen
King or Anne Rice to give it a whirl, though, is still a problem.
The prose is very much of its period, and for a generation of
children who grow up watching Freddy Krueger, all of the offstage
murders here are going to seem a letdown. If ever a book needed to
be placed in context, it's ``Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   Viking's handsome unabridged edition in their ``Whole Story''
series is an admirable solution. Based on a French edition by
Editions Gallimard, it features annotations and period artwork on
nearly every page, keyed to the text: when Victor is tried for
murder, the margins display pictures of late-18th-century
courtrooms, prisons and some very uncomfortable-looking iron
restraints. There are plenty of cultural references as well,
especially asides about Mary Shelley's family (husband Percy) and
the larger circle of Romantic poets (Coleridge and Wordsworth).
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, during the passages where not much is going on,
there are too many old paintings of Alpine glaciers, peasants in
colorful costumes and views of Lake Geneva from every imaginable
angle, but otherwise the annotations are always informative, and
often surprising and fun. There are also several two-page sidebars,
including one about the Romantics and the famous ghost story
competition that led to the novel, and another about the various
film versions, from Boris Karloff to Mel Brooks. Best of all,
though, are the finely detailed colored illustrations by Philippe
Munch. He is especially good at the large-scale illustrations of
landscape -- the Alpine mountain dells, the bleak Orkney Islands,
the Arctic desert -- that reinforce the impression that this novel
is best approached as an epic. My only quibble is the monster
himself; for a character regularly described as hideous, he's
awfully handsome, and often downright hunky.
</P>
<P>
   For younger readers, there is a new retelling of the story in
attractively cartoony pictures by the British artist Chris Mould,
who has written his own adaptation. Both Victor and the monster are
appealingly goofy, with bug eyes, long faces and prominent jaws.
There's a spirit of cheery, Halloweenish fun to the drawings,
dominated by autumnal orange or a deep, macabre green. Too much of
the story is crowded into the narration, with a number of moments
that might better have been dramatized -- the monster recoiling
from his own image in a pool, for example -- and one scene is
understandably softened for younger readers when the monster's
murder of a child is changed into an accident.
</P>
<P>
   But even Mould's chipper retelling achieves some of the pathos
of the novel's final pages, as Frankenstein and his monster head
for their ultimate encounter on the Arctic ice. His final picture
is haunting, as the creature, silhouetted against a blaze in the
midst of a frozen waste, reaches imploringly for the sky. It's an
image to send chills of terror and pity up the spine of any kid, no
matter how old he is.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   James Hynes is the author of ``Publish and Perish: Three Tales
of Tenure and Terror'' and ``The Wild Colonial Boy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
