<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NEST-NYTSF     10-15 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORN FROM THE NEST
</HEADLINE>
  By Clorinda Matto de Turner 
 Translated by John H. R. Polt 
 174 pp. New York: Oxford University Press. $30 
 ------ 
 BANNED IN LIMA 
 By JOANNA O'CONNELL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Torn From the Nest'' first appeared in Lima in 1889, it
was a sensation. Clorinda Matto de Turner brought her passionate
demands for social reform to the center of national attention. The
president of Peru wrote her that he was one of many readers moved
by her forthright denunciation of abuse of the indigenous majority
at the hands of the Creole minority. At the same time, because the
novel advocated an end to celibacy for priests, it was banned by
the church; Matto was excommunicated and burned in effigy.
</P>
<P>
   This new and engaging translation by John H. R. Polt is part of
Oxford University Press's wonderful Library of Latin America
series. For most of this century, ``Torn From the Nest'' was one of
very few works by a woman in the Latin American literary canon,
both as an early example of literary naturalism and, more
significant, because it anticipated one of 20th-century Latin
American literature's major tendencies, the indigenista novel _
writing by non-Indians denouncing the exploitation of indigenous
people as the unresolved legacy of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   In her preface, Matto echoes the credo of realism when she says
she wants the novel to be a ``photograph'' of Peruvian life. But it
is also a romance; as in many other 19th-century Latin American
novels, a love story displays the symptoms of deep-seated national
contradictions. Antonio Cornejo Polar's introduction places Matto's
work in the context of Latin American intellectual life and of
national debates in Peru. He helps us understand how the realist
elements of Matto's narrative _ the detailed representations of
landscape and custom, the emphasis on social corruption _ showed
her contemporaries a new way to understand relations between
Creoles and Indians and challenged them to identify with her
strongly ethical vision.
</P>
<P>
   Lucia and Fernando Marin, an educated Creole couple from Lima,
have come to live in the Andean provincial town of Killac. Lucia
tries to help Marcela Yupanqui, an Indian woman whose family is in
a desperate situation because of the corrupt practices of the local
priest, politicians and gentry. Lucia's well-intentioned efforts
precipitate a violent reaction that results in the death of Marcela
and her husband, leaving their two daughters orphans; the Marins
are forced to return to Lima, taking the girls with them.
Meanwhile, the Governor's son has fallen in love with one of the
girls, but (of course) their love is doomed by a terrible secret.
</P>
<P>
   The women in the novel are the moral center of Matto's
alternative vision. Because they cannot participate in public life,
their influence on men is their only means of pursuing change.
Matto pushed to the limit the sphere of public action allowed women
in her society. She was one of an extraordinary group of female
intellectuals in Latin America engaged in redefining women's
citizenship. She wrote and published widely before her husband's
death in 1881, but it was as a widow that she embarked on her
career as a professional intellectual. In addition to writing
novels and articles, she edited a major newspaper in Arequipa as
well as Lima's weekly literary review, El Peru Ilustrado, and
founded a feminist press.
</P>
<P>
   If in many respects her ideas were typical of liberal
intellectual circles, her critique of church corruption, her
feminism and her energetic engagement with politics were radical.
In 1895 she was forced to flee Peru, leaving her manuscripts behind
in a house and publishing office ransacked by mobs. She enjoyed
success in Buenos Aires, but died in exile in 1909. When we read
``Torn From the Nest,'' we may see her vision of redeeming the
downtrodden Indians through enlightened Christian charity and
education as paternalistic, but in her day her views were a
courageous attack on the colonial underpinnings of Peruvian
society.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Joanna O'Connell, who teaches in the department of Spanish and
Portuguese at the University of Minnesota, is the author of
``Prospero's Daughter: The Prose of Rosario Castellanos.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
