<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8840 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     10-15 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICANS IN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  America's Journey Through Slavery 
 By Charles Johnson, Patricia Smith and the WGBH Series Research
Team 
 Harcourt Brace, $30  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until 1639, when the colony of Maryland declared that heathen
slaves could no longer gain freedom through baptism, enslavement
had little to do with skin color. Settlers most often referred to
themselves as Christians or Englishmen, not whites. But shortly
after Maryland's grave pronouncement, color became the chief
determinant of fate, with black equaling slavery and white equaling
freedom. In ``Africans in America,'' the companion volume to a
public television documentary on slavery, Patricia Smith, the
former Boston Globe columnist who was forced to resign last summer,
and Charles Johnson, the novelist who won the National Book Award
in 1990 for ``Middle Passage,'' tell the story of American slavery
by drawing on firsthand accounts and historical documents. While
Smith provides excellent in-depth coverage of the complicated role
played by blacks in the Revolutionary War, and of the politically
powerful Philadelphia black community, her writing lacks a
distinctive voice or critical vantage point. She gives insufficient
attention to the Civil War, and her decision to conclude with that
event without even briefly discussing Reconstruction or the civil
rights movement, seems rather short-sighted. Johnson's 12 highly
detailed short historical fictions, which are interspersed
throughout the narrative, bring to life this most shameful period
in our nation's history. _ JOHANNA BERKMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYRIL CONNOLLY: A Life &QL; 
 &UR; By Jeremy Lewis &QL; 
 &UR; Jonathan Cape/Trafalgar Square, $50 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the distinguished English critic and editor Cyril
Connolly played a leading role in English literary life from the
1930's until his death in 1974, he seldom lived up to his own
uncompromising standards. In fact, to judge by Jeremy Lewis's
surprisingly candid authorized biography, Connolly was accurate
when he described himself as a ``lazy, irresolute person, over-vain
and over-modest, unsure in my judgments and unable to finish what I
have begun.'' Born in 1903 and educated at Eton and Oxford,
Connolly was a perfectionist who provided in his best-known book,
the semiautobiographical ``Enemies of Promise,'' not only a
portrait of his early years but an apologia for his own failure to
produce great literature. An elegant curmudgeon with expensive
taste and a stinging wit, Connolly was as ambivalent about his
career as a literary journalist as he was uncompromising in his
critical pronouncements. He tended to look down on the highly
polished essays, reviews and satires at which he excelled and which
make up the bulk of his writings. Yet he managed to complete only
one novel, and, perhaps fearful of not fulfilling his own promise,
he abandoned any number of ambitious literary projects. Further,
despite his complaints about the drudgery of journalistic work, he
clearly enjoyed the power he wielded as a prominent literary editor
and reviewer for The New Statesman, The Observer and The Sunday
Times of London and, from 1939 to 1950, as the founder and editor
of Horizon. In Lewis' detailed and gossip-filled portrait, Connolly
comes across as a brilliant but difficult and often downright
distasteful man. It is left to the reader to wonder how Connolly
nonetheless managed to befriend so many luminaries and charm his
way into the hearts of three wives and several lovers. _ DIANE COLE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY SINATRA MATTERS &QL; 
 &UR; By Pete Hamill &QL; 
 &UR; Little, Brown, $18 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra's death in May was the occasion for a flood of
overripe, unilluminating prose, most of it obviously prepared well
in advance of the long-anticipated event. Now Pete Hamill, who has
written intelligently about Sinatra in the past, weighs in with a
book that does much to make up for the treacly obituaries and
self-serving memoirs of the last few months. A graceful
reminiscence of Sinatra after hours serves as the frame for shrewd
reflections on the singer's art (``as an artist, Sinatra had only
one basic subject: loneliness''), his personality, his audience and
_ most interesting _ his ethnicity, a subject about which Hamill,
against all odds, contrives to say fresh and persuasive things.
Outside of a few fleeting spasms of vinous sentimentality, the only
thing wrong with this brief but penetrating essay is that it is far
too short. It seems Sinatra once wanted Hamill to ghostwrite his
autobiography; judging by ``Why Sinatra Matters,'' it is a pity
that he did not encourage him to write a full-length biography
instead. _ TERRY TEACHOUT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SEASON IN HELL &QL; 
 &UR; A Memoir &QL; 
 &UR; By Marilyn French &QL; 
 &UR; Knopf, $23 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn French compares the five years she spent negotiating
with death to the torment described by Rimbaud, who used
intoxicants to write as ``a soul condemned to hell.'' In 1992, when
she was 61 years old, Ms. French was told she had esophageal
cancer. The malignancy was cured by simultaneous radiation and
chemotherapy, a treatment that possibly precipitated six weeks in a
coma and a series of other medical crises.Subsequent
life-threatening kidney infections, pneumonia, agonizing
compression fractures and a permanently disabling heart attack soon
made her an invalid. An impatient patient, French, the author of
the novel ``The Women's Room,'' vowed she would ``remain a human
being, a thinker and a writer who was temporarily ill'' rather than
accept a life of debilitating illness.It was a vow that would
become impossible to keep.From grief and paralyzing depression to
fury and fleeting optimism, French obsessively documents her every
reaction, even asking ``the reader's indulgence'' for her ``long
recital of personal ills.'' Written ``to lay the past to rest,''
this memoir is flawed but fascinating.French tends to lecture. Her
frequent digressions into feminist dialectic and descriptions of
book tours are distracting and irritating.Her angry diatribes at
the medical establishment, when juxtaposed with a 46-year,
pack-a-day cigarette habit, seem misdirected, even petulant. ``My
illness shriveled the future up and blew it away,'' French
concludes, adding with some wonder that being ``stuck in the
present'' is the best thing that ever happened to her.Rarely
thinking beyond the next day, she has learned to savor the joy of
small moments, moving ``from pleasure to pleasure like a woman
walking through the halls of a great art gallery.'' _ LESLIE CHESS
FELLER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORY OF OPERA &QL; 
 &UR; By Richard Somerset-Ward &QL; 
 &UR; Abrams, $49.50 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opera is an art form that has always required the collaboration
of many different kinds of people, all of them, to judge by THE
STORY OF OPERA (Abrams, $49.50), at least a little neurotic. About
Mlle. de Maupin (1673?-1707), a famous French contralto, for
example, Richard Somerset-Ward, a former head of music and arts
programming for BBC Television, writes, ``She made her debut as a
22-year-old in one of Lully's operas at the Academie, but by then
she had (in no particular order) married, run away with a fencing
master, taken vows as a nun in order to get into a nunnery to
seduce a girl with whom she had fallen in love, and been condemned
by a court in Avignon to be burned alive.'' This book, with a
fascinating and handsome picture or two on every page, is a serious
and lively history. The story begins in the late 16th century and
continues up to the present, tracing the swervings toward and away
from drama that are the form's essence. Plenty of mediocre operas
have been composed for famous castrati and prima donnas, but the
most important opera composers have always sought to involve the
audience in a human drama by creating music that powerfully
expresses the text. ``What changed in the 20th century was that
opera finally became a genuine branch of theater,'' Somerset-Ward
writes. ``The drama got on equal terms with the music.'' This book
persuasively describes opera as a thriving, complex art that has
never been more appealing than it is right now. _ RICK WHITAKER
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
