<HEADER>
A8856 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHARITY-NYTSF     10-15 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHARITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET CHARITY?
</HEADLINE>
  Emergency Food and the End of Entitlement 
 By Janet Poppendieck 
 354 pp. New York: Viking. $26.95 
 ------ 
 SPARE A DIME? 
 By DANA MILBANK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each Wednesday morning I get up early to volunteer at a local
soup kitchen. I pour the juice, clean the tables and, with a bit of
luck, get to scramble the eggs or stir the oatmeal. I often wonder
whether it does much good. The place is not terribly efficient, and
it has more volunteers than it can use. But, hey, I'm trying. It
eases the guilt when I pass a panhandler on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, comes Janet Poppendieck, a sociology professor at
Hunter College, to say that I am part of the problem. As a
volunteer, I have unwittingly joined a nefarious plot to undermine
and replace the government safety net with an inadequate private
network of food pantries and soup kitchens. ``The proliferation of
charity contributes to our society's failure to grapple in
meaningful ways with poverty,'' Poppendieck says in her book,
``Sweet Charity?'' Soup kitchens have created a moral safety valve
that lets government off the hook for the nation's poor, writes
Poppendieck, who sees a right-wing conspiracy that uses soup
kitchens and food pantries to justify destroying the welfare
system: ``In short, by engaging the contributions of millions of
donors and volunteers, emergency food has 'proven' the conservative
contention that voluntary sector programs are 'cheaper' than public
sector efforts.'' Feeding programs meant by their organizers to
offset the decline of public benefits are being used instead to
justify further cuts.
</P>
<P>
   This raises an important point that Congress, which overhauled
the welfare system in 1996, still has not addressed. House Speaker
Newt Gingrich and other proponents of that reform hope the
legislation will spark a charitable revival, because nonprofit
organizations, Gingrich says, get more done at less cost. That's
true enough, but the nation's charities simply aren't big or strong
enough to take on the role supporters of the welfare reform measure
want for them. The government, by some estimates, spends 10 times
as much as charities spend on the poor, and charities get about a
quarter of their own funds from the government. Churches and other
charities would need to double or even triple their budgets just to
offset the cuts that are allowed under the welfare reform law. And
Americans, who give under 2 percent of their income to charity,
clearly aren't going to pick up the slack on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Poppendieck sullies this timely argument by
pairing it with an unworkable solution. She wants the government to
raise taxes, spend more money and rebuild a welfare state. And she
wants charities to spend less time being charitable and more time
lobbying the government to put them out of business. The act of
feeding the hungry, she says, ``could probably be accomplished far
more simply by raising the food stamp allotment, or the minimum
wage.'' Volunteers, in essence, should drop their oatmeal ladles
and call their representatives. ``Because food programs are
logistically demanding, their maintenance absorbs the attention and
energy of many of the people most concerned about the poor,
distracting them from the larger issues of distributional
politics,'' she writes. Her argument amounts to cursing the
darkness instead of lighting a candle -- or, more accurately,
lobbying Congress about the darkness so the government can turn on
the lights.
</P>
<P>
   We have been down this road before. Poppendieck, admirably,
wants to ``unite and integrate people'' instead of ``separating and
segregating them.'' But the very government programs Poppendieck
wishes to revive with vast new financing have proved powerless to
stop increases in inequality. Worse, they have encouraged
dependency and the sort of permanent, segregated underclass that
she rightfully deplores. Poppendieck herself notes that inequality
has grown to its worst in half a century -- this despite all the
government's poverty programs. The debate has moved from cash
handouts to jobs and ways to help the poor help themselves. But
Poppendieck takes us through a time warp back to the rhetoric of
the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   She began her project seven years ago, and changing times have
made holes in her argument. We hear about how rampant unemployment
spurs demand for emergency food. ``Our overall rate in the United
States averaged 4.6 percent in the 1968-73 period and 7.2 percent
in the 1980-89 period,'' she writes. Fine, but this is 1998, and
the latest jobless figures are at 4.6 percent, yet demand for
emergency food continues to soar. Indeed, Poppendieck barely
mentions some of the most significant reasons people land in soup
kitchens: mental illness and drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Charity?'' is far more convincing as a sociological
study than as a political action plan. Author of ``Breadlines Knee
Deep in Wheat: Food Assistance in the Great Depression'' (1986),
Poppendieck tells the interesting story of the rise of emergency
food distributed through food pantries as groceries and through
soup kitchens as meals. Their rise began in the early 1980's when
the federal government, sitting on vast surpluses of dairy
products, began a cheese give-away, thus creating a need for the
pantries and kitchens to distribute the food. This became
institutionalized in 1983 when Congress created the Temporary
Emergency Food Assistance Program, which was not, as it turns out,
temporary. The increased supply fed the demand, and everyone --
corporations, politicians, celebrities -- had selfish motives to
continue the program. Eventually, the program switched from being a
temporary surplus disposal program to a permanent food procurement
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Charity?'' demonstrates, convincingly, that the growing
emphasis on emergency food for the hungry is a Band-Aid that
distracts from the fundamental goal of solving poverty. But it does
not entertain the idea that charitable work is as much a part of
the solution as government intervention. Poppendieck rightly senses
reluctance among charities and volunteers to turn themselves into
lobbyists, as she proposes. ``Volunteers are often less
enthusiastic about advocacy than about direct service,'' she
writes. ``Preparing a meal with a group of other people and serving
it is fun; writing to your representative is work.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe these volunteers believe that the government is not the
only answer. Indeed, many charities are working on substantive
solutions to poverty, though the notion gets scant mention in the
book. Many soup kitchens, including the one at which I volunteer,
offer a whole range of rehabilitative services: job search
programs, job training, alcohol and drug treatment, care for the
mentally ill, community organizing. Government, of course, must do
its part. It cannot abandon its responsibility for the poor. But,
rather than supplanting charities, government can --and should --
do more to strengthen them.
</P>
<P>
   Some ideas have already been floated. A group of lawmakers, for
example, is promoting a charity tax credit that would give each
taxpayer a $500 credit for donations to charities dealing with the
poor; this would bring billions to nonprofits. The states, under
the new welfare law, are also boosting charities in new ways. In
Michigan, for example, the state has financed a group of churches
that offer mentoring for welfare recipients, providing help with
child care, car payments and groceries. But the church volunteers
also offer friendship and encouragement to build self-esteem. That
is the sort of thing the government cannot provide -- at any price.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Dana Milbank is a senior editor of The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
