<HEADER>
A8858 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TOMB-NYTSF     10-15 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TOMB-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOST TOMB
</HEADLINE>
  By Kent R. Weeks 
 Illustrated. 330 pp. New York: William Morrow &AMP; Company. $27.50 
 ------ 
 SPLENDID DIGS 
 By JOHN RAY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time there were two brothers. Contrary to the usual
pattern, the younger, whose name was Decimus Burton, worked hard
for a living and went on to be a distinguished architect. The
elder, James, was a wastrel. A Cambridge graduate, he turned up in
Egypt looking for coal mines, but he soon found more interesting
things. In the slave market in Cairo he acquired a Greek woman,
whom he later married, and in 1835 he returned to England with an
entourage consisting of his wife, other redeemed slaves and a
troupe of performing animals. These were not the virtues that had
triumphed at Waterloo, and his father disowned him. Not that this
deterred James; he simply sold his large collection of Pharaonic
antiquities and lived well enough off the proceeds until his death
at 73.
</P>
<P>
   In 1825, James Burton had found himself in the Valley of the
Kings, which was then scarcely explored. At some point he decided
to rummage inside a tomb near the entrance to the valley. It was in
a very poor state, and so dangerous that further exploration seemed
pointless. Burton drew a quick sketch plan, and left his name in
lampblack on the ceiling of the main chamber. There were other
things for him to do in the valley. The sketch of the tomb, which
is now known as KV 5, passed together with the rest of his papers
to the British Museum. These papers have scarcely been studied,
even by other Egyptologists.
</P>
<P>
   With the confidence of hindsight we can say that Burton's quick
map, incomplete as it is, is enough to show that there is something
strange about KV 5. The entrance bears the name of Ramses II, a
character familiar to every visitor to Egypt, and one of the great
monomaniacs of history. One school of thought makes him the Pharaoh
of the Exodus, and his essential odiousness was captured by Yul
Brynner in the 1956 film ``The Ten Commandments.'' Perhaps KV 5 was
a false start by one of the Pharaoh's architects, something quite
likely in a reign devoted to ceaseless building and ever more
grandiose plans.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's strange tomb is now famous, so much so that it has been
given the indispensable feature of celebrity, its own Web site.
Since 1989 it has been partly explored and cleared by a team headed
by Kent R. Weeks, an Egyptologist with the American University in
Cairo, who gives us the story in ``The Lost Tomb.'' KV 5 is to the
ordinary tomb in the Valley of the Kings, like Tutankhamen's, what
a supermarket is to the corner shop. Unfortunately, it contains
hardly anything of its original contents, but at last count the
number of its chambers totaled 108, and there are certainly more to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Working inside this tomb means coming to terms with rock falls,
malodorous dust and faulty electrical supplies. A modern sewage
pipe runs through part of it, and it leaks. But painstaking
clearance can recover things. One of the original decorators, in
about 1270 B.C., kicked over a dish of blue pigment in a dark
corner, perhaps at the end of a shift (ancient lamp wicks were
timed to last four hours). The paint was still there, after more
than 32 centuries.
</P>
<P>
   It may never have been the tidiest tomb in the valley, but KV 5
was certainly the biggest. Little was known about it before Weeks
began his work, though the Egyptologist Elizabeth Thomas had
guessed that it could be the tomb of the royal children of Ramses
II, which is mentioned in an official report about tomb robberies
prepared by a commission of government inspectors a couple of
centuries after KV 5 was built. Another court transcript, written
about 50 years after the death of Ramses, describes how a workman
named Kenena, son of Ruta, was caught stripping stone from above
the tomb, either because he liked the stone in that particular spot
or because he was looking for a way in.
</P>
<P>
   KV 5 may have remained intact for centuries, but the eventual
breakdown of administration allowed a later generation of tomb
robbers to go about its work in peace. However, enough fragments of
inscriptions and broken statuettes remained to show that Elizabeth
Thomas was right. Ramses, like any Mafia boss, had great plans for
his family, and why should these plans not extend to the afterlife
as well? His sons were going to join the gods. Ramses boasted about
50 sons, and there may have been others he did not boast about. The
seeds of future anarchy were already in place, in a country where
Ramses' monumental ambitions may well have helped to bankrupt the
government.
</P>
<P>
   He was succeeded by his 13th son, Merenptah, a 60-year-old of
proven mediocrity. The fourth son, on the other hand, was
Khaemwese, an intellectual who deserves to be known as the first
Egyptologist in history. His inscriptions show deep piety,
scholarship and an acute historical sense. Perhaps Khaemwese took
after his mother. Neither of these princes was buried in KV 5, but
others must have been. So far the names of four sons have been
found in the tomb, and four skulls have been identified. This is
presumably a coincidence, given the size of the monument and its
complexity. However, the chambers of KV 5 are on the small side for
conventional royal burials, and its true history is not yet clear.
Perhaps enough remains farther inside the tomb to fill out the
story.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks tells his account readably, though at the expense of a
little repetition and loose organization. He is generous toward
colleagues, and he has an obvious affection for his Egyptian
workmen, together with the ordinary inhabitants of Luxor, whose
livelihoods in tourism have been damaged by recent terrorist
actions. This affection extends to their ancestors, whose lives as
masons, painters and quarrymen he is good at picturing.
</P>
<P>
   He seems sanguine in the face of a discovery that has
interrupted all his schedules and that promises decades of work to
come. He reconstructs Ramses' motive as an attempt to deify himself
in his own lifetime, an idea that involves him in resurrecting a
theory about the heretic Pharaoh Akhenaten occupying the throne at
the same time as his own father. Most Egyptologists had been hoping
that this theory was dead and gone, since it appears to raise more
problems than it solves. But we are still far from understanding
how ancient Egypt worked, and there is little doubt that KV 5 has
yet to tell us all its secrets.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   John Ray is the Herbert Thompson Reader in Egyptology at
Cambridge University and a fellow of Selwyn College.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
