<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WHEREABOUTS-N     10-15 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WHEREABOUTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
------ 
 THE WANDERER
</HEADLINE>
 
 THE WHEREABOUTS OF ENEAS McNULTY 
 By Sebastian Barry 
 308 pp. New York: Viking. $23.95  By AOIBHEANN SWEENEY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The happy childhood is hardly worth your while,'' Frank
McCourt writes in ``Angela's Ashes,'' his memoir of a miserable
Irish childhood, and it seems true enough. These days, nothing
really goes down without a good dose of irony. ``No happy
stories,'' a friend of mine tells his writing classes at the
beginning of each semester, and he means it. After all, who's going
to read them?
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Barry's novel ``The Whereabouts of Eneas McNulty''
opens with an unabashedly joyous account of Eneas McNulty's
childhood in Sligo. It is full of ``the utter merriment of
mornings,'' ``gangs of wallflowers'' and a ``thrumming of crickets
to beat the band.'' Eneas has a Pappy who plays the piccolo and a
Mam who dances a jig by the hearth. Though misery closes in on
Eneas with satisfactory swiftness, Barry's sweet, lyrical pitch
never falters; the novel has a bold measure of old-fashioned
blessedness.
</P>
<P>
   The author of three collections of poems, three books of prose
and several plays about the history of Ireland (including ``The
Steward of Christendom''), Barry affords himself a little
sentimentality by assiduously pinning his hero's fate to its
historical context. The opening of the book describes Ireland's
childhood as well as Eneas's: these are the days just before ``your
man Pearse and the rest'' make history with the Easter Rising --
Ireland has not yet seized independence.
</P>
<P>
   As Eneas reaches his 20's and World War I comes to an end, he
finds himself out of work among the returning veterans. In a muddle
of innocence and despair, ``Eneas looks at it all with simple eyes
and having no desire to loiter the rest of his days, joins at the
hint of his Pappy the Royal Irish Constabulary,'' the English-led
police force. ``Ferocious events are afoot in the sacred web of
fields and rainy towns'': Ireland has awakened, and as his father
gently puts it, ``It's a bad sort of time to have your head up, you
know, in any class of political matter.'' In his ``bright peaked
cap and shining boots,'' Eneas quickly ends up on the Irish
Republican Army's blacklist. His boyhood friend Jonno Lynch has
become one of the I.R.A.'s enforcers and delivers his death
sentence just as the Anglo-Irish Treaty is signed. Eneas flees the
Irish Free State to spend the rest of his days in fear and exile,
while Ireland spends the ensuing years in civil war and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Eneas is as long-suffering and piously devoted to his homeland
as his classical namesake, but unlike Virgil's hero, he is no
nation-builder. Though he ``weeps mightily'' at the sight of the
land whenever he dares return, his ``childhood singing in him,'' he
has nothing but scorn for the ``murdering likes'' of the
self-important men who are ``driving the pony and trap of
Ireland.'' In exile, ``fierce, close work'' becomes his only
directive. He humbly fishes, bearded and tired, the waters of
Greenland; he binds the vines of France with ``the same stooping,
the same peering and care''; he drives his spade into 200 miles of
Nigerian soil, digging a canal to bring water to the ``numbed
countryside'' of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what makes Eneas McNulty a hero is the very ``fire
of concern and regard'' that glows so cozily in the hearth of his
youth. Barry vividly creates Eneas's warm humanity. Whether he is
standing deaf on the beaches of Dunkirk, watching the moon
``blowing like a flag'' or sitting up ``in the ragged dark''
listening to his friend Harcourt ``breathing lightly in the mercy
of sleep,'' Eneas's tenderness is powerfully apparent and casts a
gentle, clarifying light on the hardship around him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is easy to find virtue in a lonely man, much the way
it might be to find joy in childhood -- but in the murk of war it
seems all the more necessary to do so. Eneas McNulty's happy
childhood provides a momentary glimpse at the stark, troubling
contours of Ireland's somber history.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Aoibheann Sweeney is finishing her first novel, ``Lucky Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
