<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BOOKSHELF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S BOOKSHELF
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 HOME RUN: 
 The Story of Babe Ruth 
 By Robert Burleigh 
 Illustrated by Mike Wimmer 
 Silver Whistle/Harcourt Brace. $16. (Ages 6 to 10)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the glow of this year's slugfest completely fades, or
perhaps to burnish it during the off-season, here, told in lushly
romantic full-page paintings, mostly of the subject himself, and in
data-filled old-style bubble-gum baseball cards, is the story of
the Babe. His record of 60 home runs stood for 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HELLO TOES! HELLO FEET! &QL; 
 &UR; By Ann Whitford Paul &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Nadine Bernard Westcott &QL; 
 &UR; DK Ink. $15.95. (Ages 2 to 4) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A full day of adventures for one little girl and her feet. From
first touching the floor to kicking the stairs, jumping from rock
to rock, squishing in the mud, washing in the tub and then to bed
-- busy feet, busy girl. Exuberant verse, delightful watercolor
illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMELIA TAKES COMMAND &QL; 
 &UR; Written and illustrated by Marissa Moss &QL; 
 &UR; Tricycle Press. $14.95. (Ages 6 to 10) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth in the popular ``notebooks,'' the adventurous
Amelia has returned from space camp to address the challenges of
fifth grade. Part of the fun of the series is that the books look
like the lined notebooks with black-and-white marbleized covers
that children use for journal writing all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAVEN IN A DOVE HOUSE &QL; 
 &UR; By Andrea Davis Pinkney &QL; 
 &UR; Gulliver/ Harcourt Brace. $16. (Ages 11 and up) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nell, who is 12, spends August in Modine, N.Y., a community that
was originally settled by freed slaves after the Civil War. She
stays with Aunt Ursa Grady, who raised Nell's father, but this
summer there is a crisis of conscience involving an illicit favor
her cousin Foley asks. Engrossing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIMPLE GIFTS: A Shaker Hymn. &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Chris Raschka &QL; 
 &UR; Holt. $15.95. (All ages) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This lush, complex, nearly abstract setting of the well-known
hymn is something of a homage to the work of Paul Klee. It involves
a cat and some familiar creatures, including a squirrel, a rabbit
and a blue jay. It is perhaps most appealing to school-age children
who can hum the tune while puzzling out the illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BACK TO SCHOOL FOR ROTTEN RALPH &QL; 
 &UR; By Jack Gantos &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Nicole Rubel &QL; 
 &UR; HarperCollins. $14.95. (Ages 4 to 8) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sarah and her wicked red cat, Rotten Ralph, are back. In their
ninth adventure, Sarah is old enough to go to school, and Ralph is
so frantic about remaining her best friend that he goes too. His
extravagant naughtiness is so silly he's hardly bibliotherapeutic.
Of course a young reader doesn't need to be having trouble settling
into a classroom to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEI FUH: Memories From China &QL; 
 &UR; By Edith Schaeffer &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Lesley Liu &QL; 
 &UR; Houghton Mifflin. $16. (Ages 5 to 9) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The author was born in Wenzhou, near the China coast, on Nov. 3,
1914, and was nicknamed Mei Fuh, meaning ``beautiful happiness.''
This memoir of her first five years has an exotic sweetness, as
shown in her account of raising some silkworms and harvesting the
silk. The line drawings are delicate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE LOVE OF VENICE &QL; 
 &UR; By Donna Jo Napoli &QL; 
 &UR; Delacorte. $15.95. (Ages 12 and up) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Percy's father is a civil engineer and his current floodgate
project involves taking the family to Venice for the summer. In the
most exotic and romantic of all Italian cities, the American
teen-ager falls in love with Graziella, a politically minded girl
who opposes the tourists who keep the economy going. Ripe romantic
fiction, but given the setting, why not?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEVER WERE MEN SO BRAVE: &QL; 
 &UR; The Irish Brigade During the Civil War &QL; 
 &UR; By Susan Provost Beller &QL; 
 &UR; Margaret K. McElderry. $15. (Ages 10 and up) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Brigade fought with Union forces at the battle of
Antietam in 1862, and 535 of its members were among the dead or
wounded. The story of Thomas Francis Meagher and the unit is a
vehicle for the story of the Irish in America to that date.
Skillfully told.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981015.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRI     10-15 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRIEF: CHILDREN'S BOOKS 
 THE GINGERBREAD MAN
</HEADLINE>
  Retold by Jim Aylesworth 
 Illustrated by Barbara McClintock 
 Scholastic, $15.95 (All ages)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The anthropomorphizing of food has had a long history in
children's stories. Occasionally the food in question actually
wants to be eaten, and feels hurt when it/he/she is overlooked or
rejected by a hungry child, adult or animal. But usually _ and this
seems to make a lot more sense _ the food doesn't want to be eaten
but would rather be spared and allowed to live life fully, or at
least until spoilage sets in. The age-old tale of ``The Gingerbread
Man'' is of the latter variety. In Jim Aylesworth and Barbara
McClintock's extremely appealing version, a little old man and a
little old woman lovingly fashion a cookie and then bake it in the
oven, anticipating the gustatory pleasure that will soon be theirs.
But as soon as the oven door is opened, ``out popped the
Gingerbread Man, and he ran across the floor.'' And here the
excitement begins.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock's spirited, memorable illustrations feature fully
clothed animals and are greatly influenced, according to the
illustrator's note, by the 19th-century French illustrator
Grandville. But McClintock's depiction of the Gingerbread Man
himself feels contemporary, providing an interesting counterpoint
between the hero of the story and his adversaries. Children will
respond to the sassy, boastful facial expressions and exclamations
of the Gingerbread Man. (Actually, he bears a resemblance to the
Pillsbury Doughboy.) And they will quickly be drawn into the story,
familiar though it is, following the sure-footed cookie as he
confronts a variety of creatures who wish to gobble him up,
including a butcher, a cow, a sow and a fox. As the story proceeds
and tensions mount, Aylesworth's words demand to be read aloud in
an increasingly feverish, fast-paced manner. As if to emphasize
this to readers, the hero's final speech in the story is printed in
large type.
</P>
<P>
   As a character, the Gingerbread Man is full of himself and
immensely cocksure, and perhaps this is why children hardly ever
seem upset at his inevitable ``death'' at the end of the story. In
fact, children seem to understand that all cookies -- even those in
literature -- are meant to be eaten. With this in mind, a recipe
for gingerbread cookies appears on the back of the book jacket. _
MEG WOLITZER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I DID IT, I'M SORRY &QL; 
 &UR; Written and illustrated by Caralyn Buehner and Mark Buehner &QL; 
 &UR; Dial, $15.99. (Ages 5 to 9) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caralyn and Mark Buehner's 1995 book, ``It's a Spoon, Not a
Shovel,'' is an imaginative, involving picture book designed to
teach manners -- primarily table manners -- to young children. ``I
Did It, I'm Sorry'' is about ethics and is nearly identical in
format: an unruly cast of animal characters faces human choices; a
simple quiz with zany wrong answers follows each example; brightly
colored, somewhat outlandish illustrations depict the scenes; and
hidden animal figures and letters (denoting the correct answers to
the quiz questions) pose a challenge for young readers. But
although their new book bears a strong resemblance to ``It's a
Spoon, Not a Shovel,'' this time the Buehners seem to pitch both
the text and the illustrations to an older, more sophisticated
audience, and the result is a confused and sometimes troublesome
book. Pola Bear swears and tells dirty jokes. Sheila the sheep
fends off the peer pressure of her friends who are dyeing their
wool purple and sporting tattoos. More worrisome, three bored
camels, portrayed grotesquely in stylized fashion, search for fun,
and Cory the camel suggests, ``Let's stomp on that nomad, and chew
up his tent!'' The intended humor of some situations -- the McFly
family frequents an all-you-can-eat buffet called Frontier Cow Pies
-- will be lost on most youngsters, and the tastelessness
undermines the book's central message: the importance of good
morals and manners. _ CONSTANCE DECKER THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HATMAKER'S SIGN: &QL; 
 &UR; A Story by Benjamin Franklin &QL; 
 &UR; By Candace Fleming &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Robert Andrew Parker &QL; 
 &UR; Orchard, $15.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're the last words any writer wants to hear: ``May I make a
suggestion?'' But you'll hear them a lot if you want to write,
because revision is part of the game, as Benjamin Franklin knew.
The Hatmaker's Sign: A Story by Benjamin Franklin (Orchard, $15.95;
ages 5 to 9) is a true tale of writerly frustration, written by
Candace Fleming and illustrated by Robert Andrew Parker. As the
story-within-a-story begins, it's July 1776, and Thomas Jefferson
is writhing in pain as the Continental Congress debates changes (he
calls them ``mutilations'') in his draft of the Declaration of
Independence, which he believes to be perfect as it is. The
delegates noisily argue over every treasured syllable, striking
out, adding, inserting, toning down, beefing up, rewording,
rephrasing and reordering. On the sidelines, meanwhile, the
distraught Jefferson is consoled by his friend Ben Franklin.
``Tom,'' he says, ``this puts me in mind of a story.'' The story he
tells (one that Jefferson later recalled in his memoirs) is about a
Boston hatmaker who's on his way to the sign shop with a plan for a
new sign. On his parchment are the words ``John Thompson, Hatmaker.
Fashionable Hats Sold Inside for Ready Money,'' and below them a
drawing of a hat. Along the way, he meets a few people who have
suggestions to offer. Each one seems to have a good idea: The
hatmaker's name is irrelevant, isn't it? And why say ``inside''?
Where else would the hats be sold? One by one and two by two, the
carefully chosen words are struck out, and finally even the picture
of the hat disappears (after all, there are hats in the shop
window, aren't there?). By the time he arrives at the sign shop,
his parchment is empty. But the sign maker has an idea too. ``May I
make a suggestion?'' he says. ``How about: 'John Thompson,
Hatmaker. Fashionable Hats Sold Inside for Ready Money.' '' Under
them, he'll draw a hat. ``It's perfect!'' says the hatmaker.
Fleming's retelling captures the humor of Franklin's tale and adds
charming period detail, while Parker's richly colored
ink-and-watercolor paintings are the perfect accompaniment. I
wouldn't change a thing. _ PATRICIA T. O'CONNER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU NEVER KNOW &QL; 
 &UR; A Legend of the Lamed-vavniks &QL; 
 &UR; By Francine Prose &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Mark Podwal &QL; 
 &UR; Greenwillow, $15. (Ages 5 to 8) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to an ancient Jewish legend, there are always 36 holy
people in the world. They are known as Lamed-vavniks (from the
Hebrew for 36). These people are so righteous and just that their
prayers are always answered. Yet they live in secret, disguised as
ordinary people, humble and often poor. Stories involving secret
identities are greatly appealing to children, and Francine Prose
has written a lovely tale around this intriguing legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Never Know'' is the story of a Lamed-vavnik named Schmuel,
a poor cobbler who is so kind and generous that the townsfolk think
he must be stupid. When Schmuel's prayers save the town, they
wonder why God listens to poor stupid Schmuel. They ask the rabbi,
who has a dream in which Schmuel's true identity is revealed. The
next morning the rabbi tells the townsfolk, but when they go to
find Schmuel he has already moved on. A few months later, a new
cobbler comes to town, and even though he's poor, the people treat
him with respect, thinking that he too could be a Lamed-vavnik.
``After all,'' they reason, ``you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Prose delivers her moral gently, offering children a new way to
look at the poor and the homeless. Without preaching, she
encourages us to remember that beggars and ditchdiggers may not be
what they seem, and suggests that we treat everyone with respect --
just in case. Mark Podwal's pictures are strongly atmospheric, and
go well with the text. The Lamed-vavniks, though faceless, somehow
appear peaceful and content as they go about their daily business.
Children and adults will linger on the pictures of these holy men
and women, studying them as though allowed a privileged glimpse at
the secret lives of these wonderful, mysterious people. _ ROBIN
TZANNES
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
