<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LIONS-NYTSF     10-15 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LIONS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LION'S PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
  Theodore Roosevelt and His Family in Peace and War 
 By Edward J. Renehan Jr. 
 Illustrated. 289 pp. New York: Oxford University Press. $27.50 
 ------ 
 CHARGE! 
 By ROBERT W. MERRY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the presidents, none glorified the arts and lore of
battle quite like Theodore Roosevelt. From youth to dotage, he
reveled in tales of derring-do, celebrating the patriotism of the
citizen-warrior and the sacrifice of blood on the hallowed field of
combat. His martial idealism poses a question: Was he an American
patriot in the truest sense of the word, or was he a warmonger,
driven simply by a conviction that battle purified the manly soul?
</P>
<P>
   The historian and biographer Edward J. Renehan Jr.'s beguiling
book ``The Lion's Pride,'' which chronicles the Roosevelt family's
participation in the Spanish-American War and the European
conflagration two decades later, doesn't purport to answer that
question. But it does provide a revealing portrait of the old
Anglo-Saxon elite that once dominated American society. No family
personified that elite quite like the Roosevelts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you afraid to stand up when I am on horseback?'' Teddy
Roosevelt admonished his infantry troops before his famous charge
up San Juan Hill in 1898. The 39-year-old colonel then galloped
toward the enemy as his troops rallied behind him. The war
correspondent Richard Harding Davis said it was the bravest thing
he'd ever seen _ and the most foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the remainder of his days, Roosevelt viewed this
``crowded hour'' as his finest moment, the defining act of his
life. Later, he agitated for America's entry into World War I, and
when it came sent his four sons off in search of glory _ causing
some discomfort at the departure pier when he speculated aloud, and
with apparent satisfaction, that one of his boys might well be
wounded or even killed in the righteous cause of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, two suffered serious wounds. And young Quentin,
an aviator barely past his 20th birthday, was killed, shot down
over German territory. ``Poor Quinikins! Poor Quinikins,'' the
former president, now nearly 60 and infirm, was heard to mutter as
he rocked back and forth in a chair once used to soothe the
agitations of the infant Quentin. When his friend Edith Wharton
suggested he write a book about his fallen son, Roosevelt replied
that he couldn't, ``for I should break down.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet he never manifested a particle of doubt about the
worthiness of Quentin's destruction. ``For nothing under heaven,''
he wrote to a colleague from his own days of military heroism,
``would I have had my sons act otherwise than as they acted.'' With
fatherly satisfaction, he added: ``They have done pretty well,
haven't they? Quentin killed, dying as a war hawk should. . . .
Archie crippled, and given the French war cross for gallantry; Ted
gassed once . . . and cited for 'conspicuous gallantry'; Kermit
with the British military cross, and now under Pershing.''
</P>
<P>
   How could an American father relish so philosophically the
demise of one son and the mortal dangers faced by three others in a
distant war that had almost nothing to do with American security?
Renehan suggests that the reason lies in Roosevelt's time and
class. By the turn of the century, America had pushed to the
Pacific and fulfilled its continental destiny. Now the mind of the
Northeastern elite danced with visions of a global alliance with
Britain to insure peace and stability throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Late in life, Roosevelt chafed in frustration at his inability
to make this dream a reality. That grand task fell to his cousin
and nephew-in-law, Franklin, who idolized his older relative and
steeped himself in the writings of Teddy Roosevelt's close friend,
the naval historian Alfred Thayer Mahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``F.D.R.,'' Renehan writes, ``was sympathetic to Mahan's
arguments for a strategic Anglo-American imperium . . . through
which the United States would . . . assume an inevitable task, an
appointed lot in the work of upholding the common interests of
civilization.'' Ultimately, that was the cause for which Theodore
fought and young Quentin died.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Merry, president and publisher of Congressional
Quarterly, is the author of a biography of Joseph and Stewart
Alsop.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
