<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ANGELS-NYTSF     10-15 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ANGELS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ANGELS REST
</HEADLINE>
  By Donald Harington 
 250 pp. Washington: Counterpoint. $24 
 ------ 
 RETURN OF THE STAY MORONS 
 By SCOTT BRADFIELD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald Harington is the sort of regional writer who keeps
American fiction honest. Instead of recycling the same old genre
junk (thrill killers on a tear, noble housewives saving dimes in a
jam jar, and so on), he concentrates on the people and
neighborhoods of his own experience, embroidering the life he knows
rather than fabricating a life he doesn't. And while the
post-trendy post-moderns continue playing with the fantasy of
closure and the unreliability of narrators, Harington keeps his eye
on the narrative ball, sacrificing neither believability nor
composure. Which is to say that Donald Harington's books are both
unclassifiable and a genuine pleasure to read. There aren't enough
writers like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Angels Rest,'' like most of Harington's novels, is set in
the backwoods Ozarks hamlet of Stay More, Ark., an appropriately
named pocket-sized Yoknapatawpha where few residents ever work up
enough ambition to leave. At the top of the social ladder are the
Ingledews, an oddly reticent founding family whose members brought
banks, commerce and backroom politics in their wake. At the bottom
are the Dingletoons, a Snopes-like breed of scroungers who move
into every abandoned space they find and don't seem very shy at all
-- at least not when it comes to reproducing. With so many odd
people living so close together, morality has become something of a
slipshod concept in Stay More. Everybody is circuitously related to
everybody else, and this includes (according to rumor, anyway) the
antithetical Dingletoons and Ingledews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Angels Rest'' concerns the coming of age of a 12-year-old
reporter named Dawny. Inspired by his hero, Ernie Pyle, Dawny
produces the town's only halfway reliable newspaper, composing all
the stories himself and hand-delivering each issue to every
out-of-the-way customer who can't be reached through the post
office. Published weekly and printed by means of a mail-order
gelatin board, The Stay Morning Star doesn't just disseminate news;
its aim is to follow Pyle by making ``heroes out of common men.''
And in Stay More, as it turns out, there are plenty of common men.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Stay More is located so far off the conventional map
that its residents don't mind taking their own personal liberties
with history. So while World War II rages many thousands of miles
away, the children of Dawny's generation battle one another on the
field of make-believe:
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the student body had been divided, for going on four
years, practically since the war started, into two factions, rival
camps who opposed each other not only in baseball but in war games
such as Dirt War and Dare Base and all-out Capture the Flag. . . .
These two factions occupied opposing sides of the schoolroom with
the aisle as a divider, a demilitarized zone across which spitballs
flew.''
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the aisle sit the Allies, all the most popular
boys and girls in the area. On the other sit Dawny and his fellow
Axis members, the class's most miserable-looking geeks and dweebs.
Even imagination, it seems, has its class system.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, though, the games of children give way to the
world's grubby, often brutal authenticity. And when armed American
training forces are secretly dropped into the hills to act out
possible battle plans for the taking of the Pacific, real war comes
to Stay More -- and it looks as if it will never leave. If history
was once simply ``a subject in school that bored most of us to
death,'' Dawny recalls, it now ``thundered into our own little
world of make-believe warfare and snatched us up.'' In other words,
the town's guardian angels have decided to take a little nap.
</P>
<P>
   There is something Edenic about the benign simplicity of Stay
Morons, those backwoods children of Harington's fiction who refuse
to grow up. And in many ways, the failure of Harington's latest
novel is that it doesn't manage to grow up either. For while the
opening chapters describing childhood during the war are both
charming and funny, the intrusion of the real world in the second
half of the novel often feels stagy, preachy and false.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking an introduction to Harington's excellent fiction
would be better off with the brilliant bug-eye view of things in
his 1989 novel, ``The Cockroaches of Stay More.'' No matter how
much we want this latest installment to work, in the end it simply
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bradfield's most recent books are a novel, ``Animal
Planet,'' and a collection of stories, ``Greetings From Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
