<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SHEETS-NYTSF     10-15 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SHEETS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIP SHEETS
</HEADLINE>
  By Ellen Hawley 
 227 pp. Minneapolis: Milkweed Editions. Paper, $13.95 
 ------ 
 HACK WORK 
 By DWIGHT GARNER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ellen Hawley's earnest, amiable first novel takes its title from
the logbooks that cabdrivers keep _ a collection of addresses that
tells them where they've been that day (everywhere, nowhere) and
how much money they've made (peanuts). ``Trip Sheets'' reads like
its own kind of scattered logbook. It's a series of barely
sequential vignettes about a streetwise 28-year-old woman and her
attempts to rid her life of two things: (a) her job as a hack and
(b) sex with men.
</P>
<P>
   Ditching men is the easy part. Hawley's protagonist, Cath
Rahven, has always ignored her mother's strictures to cut out her
tomboy act (``If you'd only try, Cathy. You're not bad- looking''),
and by the time we meet her, she's already dropped in on a lesbian
poetry reading and started puzzling over her life's new sexual
geometry: ``What she can't imagine is ... how two women go from
vertical and dressed to horizontal and panting.'' Cath quickly
solves this equation. Before long, she's gathered so many lovers
that Hawley is reduced to issuing summary statements like
``Experience accumulates. Women accumulate.'' You'll be tempted to
pencil the words ``You go, girl!'' in the margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trip Sheets'' is set in Minnesota, and Hawley _ who lives in
Minneapolis _ writes about the lesbian scene there with a mixture
of fondness and satirical whimsy. At that poetry reading, for
example, the only words Cath can seem to decipher are ``blood,
moon, tree, goddess, earth.'' Cath often verges on becoming a
lesbiancliche herself (she takes karate lessons, has a degree in
social work and aspires to be a writer), but her good humor and
distaste for ``New Age hoo-rah'' rescue her _ and us _ from that
fate.
</P>
<P>
   The best writing in ``Trip Sheets'' isn't about sex or goddess
worship, however, but about Cath's improvised career as a cabby.
``You don't choose your company'' when you drive a cab, she notes,
and we're both horrified and delighted by the misfits and
miscreants she scoops up off the streets. Cath frequently feels
like a miscreant, too. She works for a company that is ``so cheap
it has to glue down a $5 calculator'' _ an object she often feels
like prying up herself. ``Not because she wants a calculator, but
because it's the company's. And because it's glued down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cab driving, like the Midwest's gay and lesbian subculture,
offers Cath something she's never received from her family _ a
sturdy sense of belonging. As she debates quitting her job, she
realizes she'll miss ``belonging to a secret elite that owns
nothing and controls nothing but knows every bar, every
supermarket, every business that's gone belly up, everything that
moves down a city street, and how to pry a living from all of it.''
Leaving won't be easy, a fellow driver warns. ``Love doesn't last
forever,'' he says. ``There's only one thing lasts forever, and
that's cab driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawley relates Cath's wandering tale in prose that's spare to
the point of self-denial; her sentences rarely break into metaphor
or poke you awake with sudden flashes of insight. At times, this
spareness resonates with meaning. At other times, ``Trip Sheets''
merely seems flat and banal. When Cath makes a list of what's good
about being single, women's-magazine platitudes are all she can
come up with: ``It makes us take friendships more seriously; it
turns us toward a larger world instead of to one other person all
the time; it makes us self-reliant.'' Worse, there's little here in
the way of momentum or drama. Whenever ``Trip Sheets'' threatens
seriously to snag your interest, Hawley cuts away to another
vignette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trip Sheets'' lacks the lusty, wild-eyed comedy of Blanche
McCrary Boyd's lesbian love story ``Terminal Velocity,'' as well as
the starkly rendered emotion of Dorothy Allison's strongest work.
But Hawley's novel sneaks up on you. Toward the close of the book,
as the pieces of Cath's life begin to fall into place _ she finds a
better job and a secure relationship _ ``Trip Sheets'' becomes
unaccountably moving.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving her apartment one evening, Cath checks the mirror
``to see if she's gotten any thinner, stronger, more graceful or
more likable.'' Nah, she tells herself. In our minds, however,
she's been quite lovely _ and quite likable _ all along.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Garner is a senior editor at Salon, an Internet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
