<HEADER>
A8875 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     10-15 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRIEF: FICTION 
 FLIGHTS OF ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
  By Ellen Gilchrist 
 Little, Brown, $24  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her 16th book, Ellen Gilchrist returns once again to the
decadent, arty, emotionally indulgent Southern women who have
appeared in so many of her previous works. Characters like Rhoda
and Crystal are now middle-aged, observing life from the perimeter.
In ``The Carnival of the Stoned Children,'' when Rhoda discovers
LSD in her young son's pants pocket, she is horrified: ``I fished
it out and laid it down upon Jimmy's bed, right in the middle of
his University of Mississippi victory quilt that my brother had
given him for Christmas.'' It isn't clear why Gilchrist is
interested in keeping up with these women -- like the writing,
they're dull and predictable. What was clever and sharp in her
award-winning 1984 collection, ``Victory Over Japan,'' is now
simply quaint. So it's a relief to meet fresh characters like
16-year-old Aurora Harris, who is truly hilarious. Especially
amusing is the ironic eye Aurora casts on the feverish antics of
her born-again younger sister, who's preparing to entertain her
church group in ``Witness to the Crucifixion.'' Both girls are
struggling with the death of their older brother, a fact that
Gilchrist keeps nicely in the background. But within these 19
stories such control is the exception. Instead, a lazy kind of
shorthand permeates the collection: men are philanderers, Jews have
a talent for making money and blacks are gorgeous. Points of view
swing from speaker to speaker and many of the stories end abruptly.
Perhaps Gilchrist should be more concerned with honing new material
and less with reporting on the old. _ ERICA SANDERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BELONG TO ME &QL; 
 &UR; By Kai Maristed &QL; 
 &UR; Random House, $23.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The language of the horse world, so brusque and unromantic it's
almost combative, sets the rhythm for this admirably unconventional
collection of stories. Maristed's characters are dedicated horse
people, but her depiction of their feelings for these animals is
refreshingly free of predictable symbolism. In one story, an
ungainly woman does a melancholy striptease in a cornfield in
exchange for a trailerful of old nags bound for the knacker. In
another, a little girl impulsively dumps her toy horses into the
ocean, unaware that her trainer father, miles away at a racetrack,
is at that very moment watching his best hope for the future break
down. The equestrian jargon in ``Belong to Me'' is so perfectly
rendered it's hard to imagine what a reader who's never spent time
in the saddle will make of it; even for the initiated, the prose
may at times seem too laconic. But if winning a reader's complicity
is a writer's biggest obstacle, Maristed clears it with style. _
SALLY ECKHOFF
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEYOR &QL; 
 &UR; By G. W. Hawkes &QL; 
 &UR; MacMurray &AMP; Beck, $20 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul and John have spent over 30 years living in the New Mexico
desert, surveying the land for a foundation that has never made its
reasons for hiring them entirely clear. Now, as a team of
paleontologists, a beautiful young filmmaker and various other
interlopers suddenly appear in their lonely outpost, their lifework
begins to look fragile and their friendship -- perhaps their very
reason for living -- is challenged. In this spare yet vibrant
novel, G. W. Hawkes often pleases the reader with his sharp, terse
dialogue and his knack for imbuing a potentially monotonous setting
with color and meaning. The subtle permutations of his central
characters' shifting relationship are also interesting to follow.
It's in the novel's larger thematic statements -- its investigation
of human responses to mortality in the face of nature's seeming
permanence -- that ``Surveyor'' can appear arch and unconvincing.
Here what Hawkes may have meant to be suggestive seems
frustratingly vague or uncertain -- or, on the other hand, far too
predictable. Despite its small successes, ``Surveyor'' demonstrates
that its author has yet to learn how to shift such a delicate story
into a wider context. _ PATRICK GILES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CATCH &QL; 
 &UR; By Kim Wozencraft &QL; 
 &UR; Doubleday, $23.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too close to its beginning, Kim Wozencraft's latest novel starts
to telegraph its ending. It quickly becomes obvious, for instance,
that Kurt the drug smuggler will find it difficult to give up the
thrills and income of the game, despite frequent promises to his
wife, Annie. For her part, Annie will have an even more difficult
time reconciling her role as a responsible parent of their two
young sons with her love for Kurt. And Joseph Kessler, a narcotics
agent with a heart, will himself fall for Annie, making his dogged
pursuit of Kurt a much more complicated affair. Most predictable of
all is the finale: from early on, it's clear that ``The Catch'' is
heading toward a confrontation that will involve all three main
characters -- and their deepest hopes and deepest fears -- and will
probably end in violence. But surprisingly, the foreshadowing
detracts less than one might think from the novel's force. This is
probably because Wozencraft (the author of the well-received novel
``Rush,'' and herself a former undercover narcotics officer) has
some pertinent things to say about the seductive qualities of a
life lived outside the law and the nature of the addictive
personality -- not only among those who supply an illegal market
but among those who try to stop them. It's also because she
cleverly portrays Kurt and Annie as typical middle-class parents
with typical middle-class concerns -- bringing up the boys in a
healthy environment, spending quality time together and dealing
with the everyday stresses of a marriage in which one partner must
spend considerable time away from home. Just don't ask what Dad's
doing while Mom's at the Little League game. _ JAMES POLK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FOREIGN STUDENT &QL; 
 &UR; By Susan Choi &QL; 
 &UR; Harper Flamingo, $23 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Choi's first novel is a richly detailed exploration of a
young man's escape from the nightmare of a country torn by war.
During a stint as a translator for the American information
services in Seoul, a young Korean named Chang Ahn is caught up in
the political turmoil and forced into a life on the run. By August
1955, two years after the cease-fire has ended the war, Chang has
managed to emigrate to the United States, where he attempts to
settle into the life of a scholarship student in the university
town of Sewanee, Tenn. Yet he is unprepared for the smallest shocks
of a vastly different world: even the realization that people in
Sewanee go to sleep at night without locking their doors is
unnerving. Choi (herself the daughter of a Korean immigrant father)
catches such moments under a very clear glass, wisely resisting the
urge to embellish. Instead, she allows the story to blossom slowly
after Chang (renamed Chuck) makes his first real friend in America:
Katherine Monroe, his 28-year-old neighbor. Caught in a poisonous
relationship with a popular professor, begun while she was only 14,
Katherine is nearly as wounded as Chuck. Together they begin to
heal, not with the dreamy pleasure of romantic young lovers but
tentatively and painfully, mindful of all that has gone wrong in
their lives -- and all that might still go wrong. Moving from the
present to the past, from America to Korea, Choi brings hundreds of
small scenes to life, then uses them to construct an intricate
portrait of lovers who must also prove (to themselves and others)
that they are survivors. _ KIMBERLY B. MARLOWE
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
