<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-15 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS NEED TO RECONSIDER SICK-LEAVE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Part of me wishes that all the workers on Earth
would call in sick tomorrow and keep calling in sick every day
until they use up all the sick days their employers offer.
</P>
<P>
   I can't honestly recommend that because it would cause so much
chaos, but at least it would wake up all those companies that have
antiquated sick leave policies _ policies that essentially
discriminate against dedicated workers.
</P>
<P>
   Unscheduled absenteeism is up 25 percent nationwide from a year
ago, according to a recent study by CCH Inc., an Illinois provider
of information on human resources and employment law. The survey
also found that the absenteeism was the highest it has been in
seven years, and employers expect the situation to get worse over
the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the last decade, that shouldn't be a surprise.
Companies laid off people, leaving more work and more stress for
those who remained. Long-term loyalty pretty much disappeared.
Job-hunting gurus advised workers to constantly build their skills
_ on their own time _ to stay competitive. Many employees were
afraid to miss work because of the fear of more layoffs, adding
still more stress. Then a lot of the fear disappeared because so
many employers became so desperate for workers.
</P>
<P>
   If that makes your head spin, good. Call in sick.
</P>
<P>
   About one-fourth of the unscheduled absences are because of
family issues, with the rest divided among illness, personal needs,
stress and ``entitlement mentality'' _ the feeling of workers that
they are entitled to take every day off they can get, including all
their sick days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional `sick days' often encourage unscheduled absences
because employees have to call in `sick' at the last minute when
they may really be taking the day for personal or family matters
that they've known about well in advance,'' says Paul Gibson, a CCH
attorney and human resources analyst. ``However, they're supposed
to be sick, so they have to wait until the last minute to notify
their employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can further raise stress for an employee who needs the
time off, but is uncomfortable lying to the employer. It's also
difficult for the employer who has to scramble to figure out how to
cover for the absent employee.''
</P>
<P>
   And often the ``cover'' is provided by putting extra strain on
the most dedicated workers _ those who seldom call in sick. Even if
they understand why their colleagues are absent, it can lead to
resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional sick leave policies, giving each employee 10 days or
so a year, have become out of date for at least a couple of
reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ More families have both parents working, meaning that one has
to miss work if a child is sick or child-care plans fall through.
If the employer doesn't consider that a legitimate reason for
calling in sick, the parent will either resent the employer or lie
about it and call in sick anyway. And if the employer does consider
it legitimate, people without children can resent it if they aren't
granted similar leniency when they need time off for personal
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ People used to build up sick days by not calling in sick for
years, partly out of loyalty and partly as protection in case a
serious illness hit. But as loyalty and job security have faded,
those reasons aren't as compelling as they used to be. Take it from
one who's been there: Having 80 sick days in the bank doesn't do
you a whole lot of good if your company goes out of business.
</P>
<P>
   What has worked well for many companies, the survey says, is to
offer paid time-off programs. Instead of having, say, 10 vacation
days and 10 sick days a year, an employee would get 20 days of paid
time off. That way many people could schedule most of their days
off, except for those times when they are really sick, allowing
managers and co-workers to prepare for it. And the dedicated
employees wouldn't feel slighted.
</P>
<P>
   My two cents: If a company now offers 10 vacation days and 10
sick days, give workers 15 days of paid time off and have other
policies regarding funeral leave, jury duty and serious illnesses.
Let them save up a few days a year if they want, with the
understanding that they will be paid for those days if they are
laid off, quit or retire.
</P>
<P>
   The survey says other effective methods of reducing unscheduled
absences have included flexible scheduling, emergency child care, a
compressed workweek and letting parents have time off to attend
school functions. About half the companies surveyed do allow
flexible scheduling, but fewer than one-fourth use any of the other
methods, including paid time off.
</P>
<P>
   In professional sports, when a player misses a regular-season
game with a relatively minor injury, he'll often say, ``If it was a
playoff game, I would have played.''
</P>
<P>
   In the workplace these days, though, there aren't as many
playoff games as there used to be. Employers need to recognize
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
