<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING LAWSUITS IS MUCH EASIER THAN WINNING THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be careful what you say around the office, or you could wind up
in court.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for what you write, too: What you assumed was
long-erased e-mail may come back to haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   American businesses are spending a lot of time in court these
days, according to St.Louis-based attorney Thomas Schweich. And
thousands of cases are being built on seemingly chance
communications, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: It's costing a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical large company has over 450 lawsuits going on at any
given time,'' Schweich writes in his new book. ``Thanks to the
litigation explosion, legal costs are now running at 5 to 10
percent of earnings for some of the nation's biggest
corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a small company can easily be forced into bankruptcy
over a single case, Schweich adds.
</P>
<P>
   An insider's description of the legal mania occurring in the
business world, and some solid suggestions of how to prevent your
company from wallowing in the mire, are in Schweich's book,
``Protect Yourself From Business Lawsuits (... and Lawyers Like
Me)'' (Scribner, 223 pages, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Armed with degrees from Yale and Harvard and 13 years of legal
experience as a trial lawyer, Schweich takes an interesting
approach to the massive problems in the U.S. legal system. He
blames neither judges nor lawmakers for the problems, instead
narrowing it down to one issue: caseload.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 cases were filed in federal court in 1996,
which translates to 471 cases per federal judge, added to a docket
already crowded with pending cases. Each judge completed 27 trials
in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics speak for themselves: The judge simply does not
have time for your case,'' Schweich writes. ``Most judges are
conscientious and honest. The problem is that they will exhibit
these qualities only during the two minutes that they have to
address your case. That means that trying to obtain justice these
days is always a very big gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Schweich estimates that the very best cases have an 80 percent
chance of winning, something he calls the ``arbitrary factor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of larger dockets, broadening causes of action,
liberal rules of discovery, unscrupulous lawyers, and unpredictable
juries is what I call the `arbitrary factor,' '' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   That means a case that is merely good has just a 60 percent
change of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those odds, Schweich says, the only responsible
action is to be proactive in avoiding lawsuits _ an interesting
twist from someone who is a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Schweich then goes on to the meat of his book, which is to
discuss what he terms eight big mistakes made in companies that
often lead to lawsuits, and then four ``shields'' to help protect
companies from being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mistakes that need to be avoided:
</P>
<P>
   Watch what you write. Complaints against your boss, gossip or
irreverent comments, whether in internal memos, meeting notes or
even e-mail, can be obtained and scrutinized by opposing lawyers in
trail. A marking of ``confidential'' won't protect you, and hitting
the delete button on your e-mail won't erase it, Schweich warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you contemplate writing something down, assume that
it will be read by twelve jurors who do not know you and who do not
know your company,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Watch what you say. Speculation on areas you know nothing about,
even to your closest office mates, can be used against you in court
if the opposing attorney finds out about it. Example: A design
engineer said a new computer was not on schedule because
manufacturing was having quality problems. In fact, the customers
had not provided information about their needs in a timely fashion.
But in court, the engineer was called on to restate his uninformed
opinion. The result was a bad settlement for his company.
</P>
<P>
   Watch whom you hire and do business with. Many companies do not
do even the most basic background checks on people they hire or
companies they work with. Resume fraud is rampant, Schweich warns.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the book provides excellent and practical advice on how
to avoid walking into the litigation trap.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``But Which Mutual Funds: How to Pick the Right Ones to Achieve
Your Financial Dreams''
</P>
<P>
   By Steven T. Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger Books, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   As mutual funds columnnist for Kiplingers' Personal Finance
Magazine, author Steven Goldberg is deluged with letters and
e-mails with one question: With the thousands of funds for sale,
which one is right for me? In response, he has written this book.
It covers 12 groups of funds suited to people with specific needs,
from parents saving for college for their children to retirees
living on their income. The book is packed with useful information.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting Computer Crime: A New Framework for Protecting
Information''
</P>
<P>
   By Donn B. Parker
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $34.99
</P>
<P>
   Cybercrime specialist Donn Parker brings to this book 28 years
of experience studying computer criminals and helping their
victims. The first half tackles computer criminals and users who
make major errors. He also looks at the terrible state of
information security. The second half turns to building a new
foundation and framework to protect your information and yourself.
With 512 pages, the book weighs in as a dense look at a big
problem.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing in REITs''
</P>
<P>
   By Ralph L. Block
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Press, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1998, real estate investment trusts have delivered
an average annual total return of 15 percent. REITs can offer lower
market-price volatility and limited investment risk when compared
with stocks. For an excellent primer on this once-again popular
investment vehicle, this book can deliver. Author Ralph Block is
chief REIT analyst and senior portfolio manager at a San
Francisco-based asset management firm.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
