<HEADLINE>
`TRINITY' CAN'T HOLD A SCALPEL TO `ER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trinity's'' sleek look, richly layered story lines and
multiple-lead character structure is the same route to riches taken
by John Wells' perennial hit ``ER.'' But judging from Friday
night's pilot, the producer may have trouble striking gold this
time.
</P>
<P>
   This new dramatic series about a large, working-class,
Irish-Catholic family in Manhattan's Hell's Kitchen is not only
surprisingly contrived, but it even has the nerve to strut in a
high-minded manner while giving us secondhand characters and
battle-scarred subplots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinity'' (8 p.m. CDT Friday night, NBC) centers on the
McCallisters, five adult siblings covering all the common Irish
bases: Brothers include Bobby (Justin Louis), a police detective
with a frustrated wife (Kim Raver); Liam (Sam Trammell), a union
worker with ties to the lowlifes Bobby is trying to lock up; and
Kevin (Tate Donovan), a parish priest who shoots hoops and is on a
first-name basis with the local barflys.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters include Fiona (Charlotte Ross), a thriving
stockbroker in the dumps because her lover is going on vacation
with his wife and kids (''He said this would be the month he'd
leave!'' she says, weeping), and Amanda (Bonnie Root), a wild,
self-destructive sort who, judging by her perpetual hangover, is
the ignored baby of the clan who has seriously gone astray.
</P>
<P>
   Story lines hinted at include how another McCallister brother
was killed at 15, whether Amanda is pregnant, and just how involved
Liam was with Bobby's wife, who has her own insecurities. (''Is she
cute?'' Bobby's wife wants to know after learning that his new
partner is a woman. At least they end this discussion by slinging
dinner off the table and going at it right there.)
</P>
<P>
   The way ``Trinity'' is structured, characters will trip over one
another, generating conflict and the usual family angst. In Friday
night's pilot, Bobby finds himself at odds (this promises to be an
ongoing fight) with Liam over a murder case, while Kevin is brought
into the melee to set Bobby up for a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin is in another story line in which a friend wants his
counsel on leaving his wife and kid for a man.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers are the parents, Simon and Eileen, played by
John Spencer, whom you might remember from the dying days of ``L.A.
Law,'' and film actress Jill Clayburgh in a thanklessly frazzled,
dutiful mother/wife/superwoman role.
</P>
<P>
   We don't see much of them in the pilot pilot, except at the
beginning and end when the clan sits down for family dinner,
laughing and chatting like any fun-loving tribe. Let's hope they'll
be more than simply stock characters who turn up only as sounding
boards of reason.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for Friday nights, ``Trinity'' will be in the same
boat as ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' which understands a thing
or two about luring viewers on the week's least-watched night.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to offer something decidedly different. Let's see
what happens in future episodes with ``Trinity.'' So far, we've
been there and done that.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
