<SLUG> BC-TRINITY-TV-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRINITY' THE BETTER OF TWO NEW NBC DRAMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is fitting, in this the season of the Irish theme, that two
of the final shows to debut focus on close-knit clans of Irish
descent.
</P>
<P>
   There are the McCallisters of ``Trinity,'' the follow-up series
for ``ER'' executive producer John Wells, and the Connollys of
``Wind on Water,'' which is likely the worst new series of the
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SHOW: TRINITY
</P>
<P>
   The first scene of ``Trinity'' looks a lot like the opening
scene from any episode of ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some kids are playing in a Manhattan landfill when one of them
happens upon a pair of decaying hands.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent scenes of ``Trinity,'' however, lack the punch
and drama of even the worst hour of ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some dreadfully boring scenes in this family drama,
which includes several Irish stereotypes played by an outstanding
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   One son, Bobby, is a police officer, who is married to a drunk
and jealous flirt; another, Liam, is an up-and-comer in the crooked
rackets who has fooled around with the drunk, jealous flirt; and
the third boy in the family is a rebellious priest.
</P>
<P>
   The women in the family have their own problems _ a boozer who's
pregnant and a stockbroker who's having an affair with a married
man.
</P>
<P>
   They all meet once a week for dinner and, of course, beers at
the folks'.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are likable caricatures, and the show has a
classy look, but its dramatic themes are too contrived _ for
instance Bobby (played by Justin Louis, the show's potential
breakout star) is investigating a murder in which Liam (Sam
Trammell) is tangentially involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinity'' is a tough sell for NBC on Friday nights. Even the
network's ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' which is an infinitely
better program, has had to battle back from near-cancellation on
several occasions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Trinity.'' &QL; 
WHAT &UR; : &LR;  A close-knit Irish family lives in manhattan. among the
group is a cop, a union operative and a priest. Beers are downed,
and problems are manufactured for the sole purpose of being
solved. &QL; 
THE STARS &UR; : &LR;  Jill Clayburgh, Tate Donovan, Justin Louis, Kim Raver,
Bonnie Root, Charlotte Ross, John Spencer, Sam Trammell. &QL; 
WHERE &UR; : &LR; !off! NBC &QL; 
WHEN &UR; : &LR;  9 p.m. Fridays. &QL; 
OUR RATING: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW SHOW: WIND ON WATER
</P>
<P>
   This laughable NBC drama can be summed up in one word: bad.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Derek makes her debut as a television-series regular in this
hideous program. She plays Ciel Connolly, the matriarch of a big
and beautiful family of hard-bodied athletes who run a cattle ranch
in Hawaii. Early in the show, her husband dies, and she has to
fight back the family rival, land developer Gardner Poole (Lee
Horsley). She will not, for the sake of her husband's memory, sell
the land.
</P>
<P>
   Her two daredevil sons _ Cole (William Gregory Lee) and Kelly
(Brian Gross) _ hit the extreme-sports circuit in an attempt to win
contests to save the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The show looks like a seventh-grader edited it; cuts from actual
surfers to the actors trying to look like they are on 900-foot
waves wouldn't fool a blind man. The stories are stupid and acting
is poor. The only thing that looks good in the show is the cast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE  &LR; SHOW &UR; : &LR;  ``Wind on Water.'' &QL; 
WHAT &UR; : &LR;  A family of Hawaiian cattle ranchers needs two of its brood
to make money by using their skills at extreme sports to keep the
farm alive. &QL; 
THE STARS &UR; : &LR;  Bo Derek, Lee Horsley, William Gregory Lee, Brian
Gross, Jacinda Barrett, Shawn Christian, Matt George, Matthew
Stephen Liu. &QL; 
WHERE &UR; : &LR; !off! NBC. &QL; 
WHEN &UR; : &LR;  8 p.m. Saturdays. &QL; 
OUR RATING: 1/2 star &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
