<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ Spot coverage of the talks between
President Clinton and Israeli and Palestinian leaders to move the
long-stalled Middle East peace talks. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ANNIVERSARY _ VATICAN CITY _ Pope John Paul II, Superstar.
The leader of the billion-strong Roman Catholic Church marks his
20th year on St. Peter's throne on Friday (Oct. 16). He has brought
a new vitality and graciousness to the papacy during two momentous
decades, though now at 78 he is fragile and fading. But in his
prime, John Paul II helped hasten the collapse of communism and
energized his church by traveling to almost every country on earth
except China and Russia. In the age of TV and the Web, he humanized
what for centuries was a unapproachable, authoritarian job. It will
be a hard act to follow. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ In the wake of the
agreement that averted NATO airstrikes and stopped the bloodshed in
this southern province of Kosovo, international relief
organizations are scrambling to try to figure out how to get aid to
the 250,000 refugees who have been forced out of their homes here.
By some estimates, it may be as much as six weeks before the bulk
of the food and other aid can make it to those who need it most,
long after the winter is expected to set in. Developing. (Roughton,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF-BOX _ A list of those humanitarian relief groups
operating in Kosovo and what they are doing there. (Roughton, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-DRUGS _ MIAMI _ Anti-drug czars from 15 Caribbean
countries and Mexico are working at a three-day conference in Miami
this week to hammer out new methods of halting illegal drug transit
into the United States. America's drug czar Barry McCaffrey
discussed the results and plans for the future. Officials plan to
also discuss replacing America's controversial drug certification
process with a multinational approach. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With DRUGS-DATA _ MIAMI _ Data on illegal drug traffic. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-COLUMN _ LONDON _ It bugs fair numbers of intellectuals
and traditionalists, but the Americanization of Britian marches on.
(Campbell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE _ WASHINGTON _ The White House holds a daylong
conference on school safety that is expected to focus on successful
strategies for protecting students. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ Glenn and the Discovery astronauts have their final
press conference in Houston. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GLENNGLANCE _ Glance box. (Dayton Daily News). 3.
</P>
<P>
   ETA: Thursday, Oct. 15, 7 p.m. EDT (The press conference begins
at 2 p.m. EDT)
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Second news conference on charges against Rudolph. In
Atlanta. Feds are expected to release some, maybe a lot of,
additional details, possibly a timeline. (Scruggs/Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CARTER-NOBEL _ The rife speculation over who will get this
year's coveted Nobel Peace Prize will end early Friday morning when
the five-member selection committee announces the winner in Oslo,
Norway. Former President Jimmy Carter is among the record 139
nominations that were considered this year. He is not considered to
be a front-runner, according to the Norwegian press, which has
reported that the favorites for this year's prize are Czech
President Vaclav Havel, the parties in the Northern Ireland peace
agreement, the aid group Medicins Sans Frontieres and U.N. human
rights workers. In keeping with its strong tradition of secrecy,
the committee says nothing about the winner until the announcement.
Nor do members divulge the names of nominees. Those details are
sealed for 50 years, in accordance with the wishes of Alfred Nobel,
who endowed the Nobel prizes in his 1895 will. In an unusual breach
of secrecy, a non-voting official with the Norwegian Nobel
committee confirmed last week that Carter was denied the Nobel
Peace Prize 20 years ago because of a technicality: he had not been
nominated by the deadline. (Kurylo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RIGHTS _ One the eve of the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, veteran human rights activists,
scholars and journalists from around the world will gather at the
University of Texas today (Friday and) Saturday to discuss how to
best get the word out internationally about human rights.
(Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RALLIES _ Gay activists at Emory and UGA holding rallies
Thursday to commemorate slain U of Wyoming student Matthew Sheperd,
who was beaten to death last weekend. Emory's gay alliance is
showing a documentary to recognize the anniversary of Harvey Milk's
murder. The film will be shown from 7-9 p.m. after that, they plan
to have a candlelight vigil for Shepherd. GLOBES, a UGA
organization for Gay, Lesbian, or Bisexual Employees and their
Supporters, are sponsoring the rally in Athens, a candlelight vigil
at 8 p.m. at the UGA Arch. In addition, Atlanta City Councilwoman
Cathy Woolard plans to introduce legislation at Monday's council
meeting asking the General Assembly to pass hate crimes legislation
when it reconvenes in January. (McCarthy/Visser, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDDIE _ NEW ORLEANS _ Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, who earned his
nickname ``Fast Eddie'' the same way President Clinton earned the
nickname ``Slick Willie'' _ by escaping scandals that would have
de- stroyed lesser politicians _ could see his good luck run dry
this week. A two-year federal investigation that involved
wiretapping, searches, and seizures of large amounts of cash from
Edwards' home and office, as well as hundreds of hours of secret
grand jury testimony, is coming to a close. And the noose could be
tightening around the neck of the once-invincible, always colorful
four-time governor. He could be indicted this week. (Rochell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
