<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME GUN MAKERS NOT INSTALLING CHILD-SAFETY DEVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last October, President Clinton stood in the Rose
Garden with a group of gun manufacturers at his side, hailing the
industry's voluntary agreement with the White House to put
child-safety devices on guns.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, it appears that the promises of that ceremony
have not been realized. Sixteen out of 20 of the firearms
manufacturers that signed on to the agreement are not selling
child-safety devices with their handguns, according to a national
survey by the Violence Policy Center in Washington and two other
handgun-control groups.
</P>
<P>
   The center released its findings Wednesday. Clinton on Thursday
hosted a White House conference on school safety and the need to
find new ways to protect children from violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Violence Policy Center report conducted three surveys of six
major firearms distributors, seven retail firearm outlets, and 45
gun retail gun dealers in 25 states. Four of the 20 manufacturers
were complying with the voluntary agreement, and of the four, three
already sold safety devices with their guns before the agreement
was reached, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives criticized the findings, saying the
line of questioning used by the center was misleading and that its
findings were not reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the survey accurately shows the extent to
which manufacturers are packing safety devices with their guns,''
said Bob Delfay, president of the Connecticut-based National
Shooting Sports Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R 1817 Inc., a Gardner, Mass., gun manufacturer cited for not
selling guns with child-safety mechanisms, said it was in fact
complying because it sold its handguns with a ``lockable'' case for
the gun and a $5 coupon for a lock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it is important that every person have a choice to
store their gun in whatever way they see fit and we feel a lockable
case is more important than a trigger lock,'' said Jim Garrison,
H&AMP;R president.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Feldman, who brokered the deal with the White House,
agreed with Delfay, adding that most major handgun manufacturers
were in the process of deciding which safety devices best suited
their guns. The industry had until the end of this year to comply
with the agreement, said Feldman, executive director of the
American Shooting Sports Council, a trade group representing the
gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rose Garden ceremony a year ago, Feldman said, ``Within
the coming year, most major handgun manufacturers will institute
company policies of providing safety devices with all handguns
shipped in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Violence Policy Center said Feldman had not lived up to his
statements from last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those devices are not out there now, and for Richard Feldman
to create the impression that any other than a handful of
manufacturers are systematically using safety devices is completely
and utterly misleading,'' said Kristin Rand, director of federal
policy at the Violence Policy Center.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reached last year's agreement with gun
manufacturers as gun-control legislators on Capitol Hill were
stepping up efforts to pass a bill requiring that guns be sold with
safety devices such as trigger locks. Those efforts were abandoned
after the deal was struck, according to congressional staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to announce that eight of the largest handgun
manufacturers will now provide child-safety devices with every new
handgun they sell,'' said Clinton as he announced the agreement at
the White House. ``This will now affect eight of 10 handguns made
in America, and it will save many young lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was followed by advertisements in Washington papers
celebrating the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Violence Policy Center attacked the entire agreement because
it is voluntary, which means not all manufacturers have to use
safety locks, and because neither party ever produced a written
version of the agreement, making it impossible to ensure the
industry complies.
</P>
<P>
   The center also said _ and Feldman agreed _ that the quality of
safety devices ranges from the high-quality to the cheap and
ineffective, including plastic boxes that are easy to cut through
and trigger locks that can be broken off guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree, if it's a poorly designed lock, it won't work, which
is why it makes sense to have the manufacturer decide what lock is
best ... and have the industry set the standard,'' said Feldman.
</P>
<P>
   The White House referred inquiries on the issue to the Justice
Department. ``We haven't seen the report but we'd like to look
closely at it and review it,'' said Gregory King, a Justice
Department spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
