<HEADER>
A8926 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAGUE-FOOD-LADN     10-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAGUE-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ADV.: HAS COLOR ART) 
IF LOOKS COULD THRILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You don't have to be a cook to enjoy the Junior
League of Pasadena's new cookbook, ``Dining by Design _ Stylish
Recipes, Savory Settings'' (Favorite Recipes Press; $24.95).
Compiled with the help of the American Society of Interior
Designers (ASID), Pasadena Chapter, the hard-cover book is a feast
for the eyes as well as the palate.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-page hard-back book is filled with 40 lavish color
photographs of beautiful, decorative interior settings and
landscapes _ including kitchens, dining rooms, libraries, offices,
patios, pools, family rooms, bedrooms, bathrooms and butler's
pantries along with more than 250 recipes. ``Americans now eat in
every room in the house including the bathroom (i.e. champagne in
the Jacuzzi),'' pointed out Pasadena-based interior designer Ann
Fletcher, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The tempting-sounding recipes make you want to run into the
kitchen and try them. And the stunning photographs make you want to
rush to the telephone, call one of the decorators and start redoing
your home (of course, that's if your budget will allow such an
extravagance.)
</P>
<P>
   The book _ the league's sixth _ came about when the Pasadena
Chapter of ASID, which had been talking about doing a cookbook,
approached the league. ``We figured it was time to do another, as
our last cookbook, `California Sizzles,' which came out in 1992 and
sold 40,000 copies, was so successful,'' said Amy Lamb, Pasadena
Junior League president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about this partnership,'' said ASID Pasadena
chapter member Fletcher, ``is that it showcases our members' work
(each designer is credited) within the book _ and it was a natural
tie-in with our annual kitchen tour.'' The designers in the
Pasadena chapter submitted photos of their works in more than 150
settings; 40 were chosen in a blind selection process by a Junior
League committee. While most of the settings were photographed in
color especially for the book, a few, created for special design
projects _ such as design houses _ were photographed previously.
The food included in the photographs is incidental and does not
include any of the dishes in the cookbook. However, that doesn't
detract from the glory of this volume.
</P>
<P>
   The book's recipes, culled from more than 1,000 submitted by
league members, friends, relatives, co-workers and designers, were
tested and tasted by a cookbook committee made up of league
members. ``We received a good variety of recipes and very few
duplicates,'' said Mary Snider, who was in charge of the pasta and
appetizer sections, ``and we tested more than 500 recipes in nine
months to come up with those that made it into the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Each recipe in the book was tested three times, noted Ann
Murphy, cookbook committee chairwoman, and at each tester's own
expense. Any league member was welcomed and encouraged to test
recipes. ``People were always bringing recipes to general meetings
to taste _ and we also had three or four testing parties _ to
sample and evaluate recipes,'' she noted. The book took a year to
complete _ and is just now rolling off the presses.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was looking for easy but good-looking recipes
suitable to serve family and guests at home. They appear to have
succeeded, as many of the recipes seem to have upscale flavor and
flair and look fairly simple to make. Of course, some require more
time, effort and ingredients _ and are more complicated than others
_ but many recipes will appeal to busy, in-a-hurry cooks. Among
them are dishes like Easy Chocolate Torte, Grilled Balsamic
Chicken, Spicy Cajun Shrimp, Basil and Tomato Torta, Artichoke and
Smoked Ham Strata, Chile and Tortilla Souffle, Carrot Coconut
Bread, Penne With Spicy Vodka Sauce, Wedding Shower Chicken Salad
and White Chicken Chili. ``We opted for different recipes rather
than the standards _ Lime Bars instead of Lemon Bars, for
instance,'' noted Snider.
</P>
<P>
   The nine chapter titles in the book have been designed to tie in
with the photographs _ and include At the Doorstep (appetizers);
Scones and Sconces (breakfast items); By the Hearth (soups and
chilis); In the Garden (salads); Patterns and Pasta (pasta); Sides
on the Sideboard (accompaniments and side dishes); the Foundation
(entrees); Decorative Decadence (desserts); and Let's Play (fun
creations for kids to make, such as Spaghetti Pie, Breakfast Pizza,
Dirt Cake and nonedible clay for play).
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled randomly throughout the book are special recipe
memories that some contributors shared along with recipe hints and
tips.
</P>
<P>
   According to Murphy, the best part about compiling the book was
that it was a unifying force in the league. Besides bringing
excitement and pride to members, it is currently bringing
visibility to the league and its programs in the community, she
noted. The worst part of the venture, of course, was the hectic
rush to get everything completed in just a year.
</P>
<P>
   The league's last cookbook raised $250,000 for Junior League
community programs _ and with this volume the league is hoping to
raise even more.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find the book at local bookstores, you can order it
by mail ($32.01 including California state tax and shipping) by
calling the Junior League of Pasadena Inc. at (626) 796-0162.
</P>
<P>
   To get a taste of ``Dining by Design,'' whip up some of these
recipes from the cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   (RECIPES to follow) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
