<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8927 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISONS-ARIZ-BOS &LR;      10-15 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-ARIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCARCERATION TAKES ITS TOLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF
 &HT;    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PHOENIX _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio was gleeful about his newfound
ability to charge jail inmates for meals. But there was a down
side: He felt obligated to improve the food, if only a little.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the new dollar-a-day food charges, the man who
proclaims himself ``America's toughest sheriff'' last month
reluctantly ordered that tiny packets of salt and pepper be
provided with meals in the Maricopa County jail system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you try some of the food? I hope it wasn't too good,'' a
pained Arpaio asks a visitor who had just taken a jail tour.
Brightening, he adds, ``Hey, did you know it costs more to feed our
guard dogs than it does the inmates?''
</P>
<P>
   After reinstating chain gangs and requiring inmates to wear pink
underwear beneath zebra-striped uniforms, Arpaio has joined a
nationwide movement toward requiring prisoners and jail inmates to
pay for the services they receive behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriffs, wardens, and corrections officials are passing along
the costs of everything from food and medical care, to laundry
services and electricity, to family visits and nightly ``rent'' on
cells. A survey by the National Prison Project of the American
Civil Liberties Union found such fees assessed in 21 states, though
some charge only prisoners who are earning money in work-release
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has taken small steps in that direction, with
several counties charging new jail inmates a $30 processing fee and
small copayments for infirmary visits. The state Department of
Corrections takes 15 percent of the salaries of prisoners in
pre-release work programs, and charges them $5 for
prisoner-initiated medical visits.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the dollars-for-detention programs serve a dual
purpose: They ease the burden on taxpayers for the cost of keeping
1.7 million Americans incarcerated, and they are a small but
psychologically important deterrent aimed at encouraging ex-inmates
to never return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should law-abiding citizens continue to pay the whole
freight, building prisons and taking care of people who are
violating the law?'' said Sheriff Donald Zeller of Linn County,
Iowa, who charges inmates $60 a day, among the highest such fees in
the nation. His jail's per-inmate costs are about $64 a day, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do the crime, you're not only going to do
the time, you're also going to pay for it,'' Zeller said.
</P>
<P>
   But prisoners' advocates and civil libertarians say the fees
ultimately punish inmates' families, and could backfire by creating
new financial burdens _ and incentives for crime _ among newly
released inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``By adding punishment on top of punishment, to make them pay
for going to prison, is absurd. The evidence is overwhelming that
treating these individuals poorly in prison makes them even worse
when they get out,'' said Dennis Palumbo, professor of justice
studies at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Gotsch, public education assistant at the ACLU's National
Prison Project, said health-care fees block access to medical care
among inmates, many of whom are poor. She also said jailers are
motivated in large part by the public relations points they score
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to vilify prisoners because people like to see that
prisoners have it hard,'' Gotsch said. ``People have this idea that
prison is a country club, and it is not.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly is true of the maximum-security Madison Street
Jail in downtown Phoenix, and Arpaio wouldn't have it any other
way.
</P>
<P>
   The jail's 1,452 inmates spend most of their days inside their
cells, and rules are not flexible. Last week, a group of about 40
inmates groused about losing all privileges for two weeks _
including no visitors, telephone calls, or television _ because two
among them were hoarding towels.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-floor kitchen, a meal crew of about 20 inmates
wandered around in knee-high rubber boots, complaining about having
to pay for the food they slop onto brown plastic trays. They are
not paid, but working in the kitchen gets them out of their cells;
for some, it can also mean a shortened sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner this night was a brown agglomeration the guards swear is
beef stew on mashed potatoes, along with cooked carrots, bread and
butter, and watermelon slices. Watery fruit punch washes it down.
Some of the food is donated _ Arpaio says companies get tax breaks
for doing so _ but the inmates say they have to weed out green
bread and spoiled vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Older inmates yell at a new worker on the food assembly conveyor
belt _ ``Hey potato guy, get it in the hole'' _ for missing the
proper tray compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all are angry at the dollar-a-day food program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scam. It's bad enough we're in jail. Then we have to
pay for this?'' said Eric Olsen, 25, who has three months to serve
for violating his parole on an earlier grand theft charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a publicity stunt,'' said Anthony Thomas, 25, serving
time for domestic violence. Arpaio ``wants to keep getting elected,
so he has to show people he's giving us a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Farnsworth, 29, serving time on a drug charge, said the
food isn't worth even a dollar a day, but that's the whole point.
In words that would warm Arpaio's heart, he said: ``We're not
supposed to like it. We're not supposed to want to come back to
this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners' advocates say one of their many objections to the
fees is that many of the inmates in Arpaio's jails are awaiting
trial and therefore still considered innocent. Even some of the
most aggressive prison-fee programs elsewhere charge only those
inmates who have already been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio counters that he doesn't care if they're innocent or
guilty. ``If they were on the outside, they'd still have to pay for
meals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Hamm, executive director of Middle Ground Prison Reform,
Arizona's leading prison rights group, said there is no evidence
any of Arpaio's high-profile actions _ putting men and women to
work on chain gangs, forcing them to wear pink underwear, or
lodging some inmates in a ``tent city'' in the desert to alleviate
overcrowding _ have done anything to reduce recidivism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about politics and the mean-spiritedness which
permeates our society,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   If every inmate paid for meals, Arpaio could collect roughly
$2.5 million a year toward his $70 million jail budget. However,
for now at least, Arpaio is collecting only from inmates who put
money in their jail bank accounts, which more normally are used for
purchases of candy, stationery, pens, and hygiene items. Some
inmates said they are purposely leaving their accounts empty _ and
forfeiting the ability to buy personal items _ to avoid paying for
their food.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arpaio said he collected more than $80,000 in the
program's first two weeks. And regardless of how much money the
effort yields, Arpaio is already basking in satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just to save money. I'd do it if I could afford
steak. They should not like jail, and paying for it helps that,''
said Arpaio, a Springfield, Mass., native who spent 1974 to 1978 as
deputy director of the Boston office of the US Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the salt and pepper packets rankle him, especially their
$20,000-a-year cost. But he takes solace in already having taken
away coffee, a $150,000-a-year savings, and eliminating mustard and
mayonnaise from inmate menus.
</P>
<P>
   Though Arpaio takes particular pleasure in the fees, he was
hardly the first to put them to use.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the earliest ``user fees'' were adopted in 1985 by
Macomb County, Mich., and since then the county has collected more
than $7 million. Charges there are on a sliding scale depending on
how much inmates earn outside prison, up to $56 a day. Doctor and
dentist visits cost $15, and prescriptions cost $5.
</P>
<P>
   The county also aggressively pursues inmates after release,
filing more than 400 collection suits this year alone, said Lori
Nyovich, Macomb County reimbursement coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taxpayers love it, the inmates hate it,'' said Nyovich.
``They don't want to pay to be here. But we always say that we get
so many repeat customers, they must enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Told about the Michigan program, Arpaio pauses for a rare moment
of reflection. Behind him, a neon ``vacancy'' sign flickers on a
mock advertisement for his beloved tent city jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't charge them for the room,'' he said. ``Maybe I
should.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
