<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES GENDER GAP IN COMPUTER TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Girls still trail boys in math and science
achievement, and an emerging gender gap exists in the number and
difficulty of computer classes they take, according to a new
national study.
</P>
<P>
   But boys have their own problems. The report, released Wednesday
by the Education Foundation of the American Association of
University Women, found that boys lag behind girls in reading and
writing, and are more likely to drop out of school.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnicity and social class were linked to equally profound
differences in many of the 1,000 research studies synthesized in
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The association's landmark 1992 study, ``How Schools Shortchange
Girls,'' documented a pattern of teachers steering girls away from
math and science, favoring boys in these subjects, and using
textbooks rife with sexual stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools and girls have made a lot of progress over the last
five years, but we need to remain vigilant because there are some
quite alarming gaps in technology and career preparation,'' said
Pamela Haag, a senior research associate for the American
Association of University Women.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 25 percent of high school girls take computer
science, compared with 30 percent of boys. Only 17 percent of all
students taking the computer science advanced-placement test were
girls, according to the report, ``Gender Gaps: Where Schools Still
Fail Our Children.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cites a dearth of female role models as one reason
girls look elsewhere for career paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medium of technology education has been inhospitable,''
said Cornelia Brunner, associate director for the New York-based
Center for Children and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner said many children first interact with computer games
that often are geared toward boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have a population that's noticeably not entering
a profession, you have to look at what the profession is doing to
make itself attractive, not at the population,'' Brunner said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers argue that the new report, with a more sophisticated
breakdown of where schools run into trouble with girls, boys and
minorities, should help educators target their teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Recent articles have examined the role of schools in the low
reading scores among boys, as well as school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Real Boys: Rescuing Our Sons From the Myths of
Boyhood,'' William Pollack, a clinical psychiatry professor at
Harvard Medical School, argues that schools fail to channel boys'
high energy into performance, hurting their self-esteem and
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers for the American Association of University Women
also urged educators to look at such nuances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly recommend that excellence and equity go hand-in-
hand,'' Haag said. ``Schools need to look at what specific groups
of students _ African-Americans, whites, girls and boys _ need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
