<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREATER THE GOP VICTORY, THE BETTER IT MAY BE FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 mid-term elections will likely be a boost to the
fortunes of Vice President Albert Gore, proving once again that the
law of unexpected consequences is immutable.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, things could hardly be worse for Gore. He is
inextricably tied to an administration synonymous with scandal. He
is the subject of a 90-day review by the Department of Justice,
which could result in the appointment of a special prosecutor to
investigate his role in the fund-raising scandals of the 1996
campaign. And the global financial crisis is threatening to
undercut domestic economic growth that has been the political
underpinning of the Clinton-Gore years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republicans are all but certain to make significant
gains this November. Midterm elections historically go against the
party that holds presidential power. Midterm elections in the sixth
year of a two-term presidency are especially difficult for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates this year vary, but the rough consensus among the most
experienced political analysts is that the GOP will pick up seven
to 15 seats in the US House of Representatives, three to six seats
in the US Senate, a gubernatorial seat to add to the 32 now under
their control, and somewhere between 200 and 350 state legislative
seats across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Weird as it might seem, however, the better the Republicans do
this November, the better it is for Gore. If a Republican landslide
occurs, the impeachment and conviction (or resignation) of
President Clinton becomes much more likely. In that event, Gore
becomes president, names Dianne Feinstein as vice president, and
proclaims that the long national nightmare of Clinton scandals is
over. Running for president is a whole lot easier if you are
already the president.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans make only modest gains, Gore will still be
the most direct beneficiary. The more Republican the political
landscape becomes, the less likely it is that Democrats will
tolerate a fractious presidential primary season in the year 2000.
In the same way that uncertainty breeds a flight to quality in the
financial markets, being outnumbered in the political arena creates
a flight to safety. Gore's candidacy is safe, familiar ground.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, modest or dramatic Republican gains in this
year's November elections give Gore the one thing he desperately
lacks: an argument. Gore's problem now is that when he boasts of
the economic success of the Clinton administration, it sounds
hollow. Most voters think Clinton is responsible for fostering a
positive economic climate. Opinion-makers and elitists credit
Treasury Secretary Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan for the economic boom. Virtually no one thinks Gore had
much to do with it. It's nice that he was there. He didn't do any
harm. But the perception is that he was not at the wheel when the
ride turned smooth.
</P>
<P>
   What Gore's presidential campaign has lacked is an argument that
voters and opinion-makers listen to and say: ``That's right.''
Republican gains in November assure Gore that he will have just
such an argument, regardless of whether the economy continues to
perform at its recent peak levels. That argument is, in the
venacular, ``don't let the lunatics take over every wing of the
asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   This message essentially reelected Clinton in the 1996 campaign,
even though Clinton's opponent (on the ballot) was one of the last
great men of American politics. But Clinton did not run against Bob
Dole, he ran against Republican extremism, using the loonier
elements of the GOP coalition as his foil.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for Gore, Republicans are famous for repeating their
mistakes. In 1994, they imagined that the election returns were an
endorsement of each and every one of their policy initiatives
spelled out in the Contract for America. Wrong. In 1998, they are
likely to misread the election results as affirmation of their
agenda, even though they don't have one, so far as anyone can tell.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also tone deaf to the realities of modern
American politics. They forget that the average American voter
today is female, not male; tolerant, not intolerant; concerned, not
angry; and skeptical, not certain. Her preference is what decides
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   If this average American voter thinks that giving the GOP
complete control of every elected branch of government doesn't work
for her, then it will not happen. Clinton probably understands this
better than any American politician alive. Gore understands it
because he has been studying national politics at Clinton's side
for six years and has watched his boss survive all manner of peril
by never losing sight of the critical decision-maker in American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore may well be the only national Democrat smiling on
election night. Amidst the gloom of lost seats and diminished
Democratic influence in Congress, he will have the one true thing
that has been absent from his year 2000 presidential campaign: a
message that resonates with the average American voter. It's a
message he can run with until, as his boss might say, ``the last
dog dies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
