<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERAPEUTIC GARDEN BRINGS HOME NATURE'S BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ Traumatized at an early age by a painful,
lonely hospitalization, a 5-year-old boy was so tuned out that he
was tested for autism. When he was first introduced to the
Therapeutic Garden for Children here, he would retreat into a
hollow in the side of a ravine, where a spreading yew creates a
roof over a stone bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hillside with pine trees behind the cave,'' said the
boy's therapist, Sebastiano Santostefano, director of the Institute
for Child and Adolescent Development, which commissioned the
garden. ``After several months, he would run up there, press the
pine needles into his palm, say `Ouch!' and run back into the cave.
He was reliving his trauma by saying the world outside hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Over two years of visits to the garden, the boy talked to the
plants and watered them ``to make them feel better.'' He ran
through a sprinkler he said rained poison water, and was not hurt.
He sent popsicle sticks down the garden's water rill, freeing them
when they got stuck and cheering them when they reached the pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spring, the boy ran up to those same pine trees and
leaned his cheek to the needles, called me over, and said, `Look
how nice this feels.' I said, `Oooh, that feels really good!'''
said Santostefano. ``He went from construing a world that hurts to
a world that is affectionate, experiencing it like the fingers of a
glove in a hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Therapeutic Garden for Children, which last year won the
landscape design profession's top honor, the President's Award of
Excellence of the American Society of Landscape Architects, was
designed by Douglas Reed of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Wellesley garden works by providing a range of emotionally
evocative settings that help traumatized youngsters heal
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As the idea of the healing landscape gains currency, more and
more versions of therapeutic gardens are being built at hospitals,
nursing homes, prisons, hospices, and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's garden differs from most, however, in being a research
model for psychoanalytical ideas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It is also an example of an unusual collaboration between
landscape designer and therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Santostefano's first therapeutic garden was created when he was
at McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass. When he opened his nonprofit
institute in a suburban Victorian home here to help traumatized
youngsters, Santostefano enlisted Child Associates in Boston, where
Susan Child and Douglas Reed worked on the initial schematic-design
and land-form phase of the project. The mission was to design and
construct a $250,000 landscape to supplement the indoor playroom
setting traditionally used for child-therapy sessions. Reed, who
had gone on to start his own firm, was hired to finish the project.
Judy Pillsbury, a Paris-based dealer of fine art prints, was the
principal donor and wanted the design to have artistic as well as
therapeutic merit.
</P>
<P>
   Reed described his job as giving form to Santostefano's ideas.
``We really had a process with the institute's staff, where we
visited the Garden in the Woods and the Arnold Arboretum and we
showed slides of all sorts of different landscape elements to ask
if they had relevance. We talked about the dunes along the beach.
We looked at streams and I showed them photos of Indian mounds and
the rill at Rousham, which was an important influence.'' That
18th-century English garden has a stone-sided serpentine rill as
one feature in a series of landscape events that the visitor
journeys through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to learn about landscape,'' said Santostefano, and
Reed ``tried to learn about child therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a water course became the unifying theme of the
garden, inspired by the fact that the yard contained a wide swale 9
feet deep left over from the time when it was part of a stream that
drained into the Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   The water course begins as a fountain on the stone patio that
links the clinic's playroom to the garden. Each child can choose to
stay indoors, but a bubbling basin of green granite overflowing
with water beckons.
</P>
<P>
   The stream travels through steel pipes under the terrace and
flows into a steel-sided rill only 8 inches wide that wends its way
down through the garden and into a small pool. ``The movement of
the water ties into the whole objective of drawing the child out,''
said Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Along the journey, the child encounters many land forms that can
evoke a wide range of emotions, such as ``the cave,'' with its
sense of security; ``the island,'' which is a thicket of shrubs for
hiding; ``the ravine,'' with its shaded walks and views that invite
exploration; ``the bridge,'' which is really a set of
steppingstones across the rill that invite risk-taking; ``the
mount,'' for climbing and confidence-building; and ``the glade,''
an expansive area for running and playing.
</P>
<P>
   Almost devoid of flowers, it's a garden of grass, trees, shrubs,
water, and sculpted hills that invite participation. Like Frederick
Law Olmsted's Arnold Arboretum, another of Reed's influences, the
design skillfully combines many elements in a small area without
seeming cramped or contrived. It's a child-scale miniaturization
that contains many experiences in a single acre.
</P>
<P>
   In almost daily use by outpatients for several years now, the
garden is used for diagnosis as well as therapy. Therapists use a
map to record the parts of each garden used by patients on each
visit, collecting information for Santostefano's ongoing research.
</P>
<P>
   As in the case of the little boy who had been hospitalized, the
parts of the landscape where a traumatized child chooses to spend
time often follow a narrative from insecurity to increased
risk-taking. But the landscape does not work the same way for every
case. ``It's not a prescribed series of progressive experiences,''
said Santostefano. ``Each child picks what feels right for him.''
</P>
<P>
   One adolescent girl who had been been deeply affected when her
mother gave birth to a baby who died, would lie on top of ``the
mount'' and fantasize that she was lying on the belly of a pregnant
woman. ``She never went into the cave at all. Her mind chose `the
mount.' She sat on it for a number of weeks, and then she began to
lie down on it, while she worked on all the sadness and depression
that resulted when that sibling died,'' said Santostefano. ``A
piece of landscape doesn't have a meaning, except the meaning a
person's mind gives it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the parent's body being replicated by landscape is
related to psychiatric theories about feelings held in the body
that are gaining more attention among therapists. ``The first
landscape a newborn engages is the body of the caregivers, being
held against their chests, being nibbled on the neck,'' explained
Santostefano. ``The mind gradually extends the world to the kitchen
and then to the back yard or alleyway, our first landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardens themselves don't heal people, Santostefano believes.
``It's a person engaging and acting on the landscape that heals.
You give symbolic meaning to it. A child is constantly fantasizing.
Child therapists typically work with children by using symbolic
puppets in a playroom, and that's valuable. The problem in
manipulating toys is that they are several steps removed from
embodied experiences, which are experiences of the body, which are
the earliest experiences. Toys are more conceptual.''
</P>
<P>
   Santostefano believes children need bushes and places to hide,
enclosures, inclines to climb, rocks to step over where they're
testing their willingness to take risks. ``All of which you would
see if you rambled through the woods.'' And all of which have been
re-created at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything we can learn from this for our own back yards?
</P>
<P>
   Santostefano thinks that overmanicured home landscapes work
against children's sense of discovery. Often, he said, it's
neglected corners _ like abandoned lots or the weed patch behind
the garage _ that become children's special hideouts and forts. If
such places are lacking close to home, he added, children should be
taken on outings to woods and wilder areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increased interest in incorporating gardens and
landscape that relieve stress and provide a refuge so that a person
can restore their emotional and physical health,'' said Reed.
</P>
<P>
   His five-year-old firm, Douglas Reed Landscape Architecture
Inc., is busy these days. One commission is to create a garden for
patients with physical rather than emotional problems at the
Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital on the Charles River in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to create an intimate garden for physical
therapy and resolve all the requirements of a hospital, such as
parking, ambulance access, service, and delivery,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
