<HEADER>
A8973 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN &LR;      10-15 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
  
( Star ratings restored to reviews) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
BELLE &AMP; SEBASTIAN/``The Boy With the Arab Strap'' (Matador)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fragile left-field music of this enigmatic dream-pop octet
from scotland named for a French novel garners the kind of
superlatives rarely seen in this era of one-hit wonderdom. The
band's 1997 debut, ``If You're Feeling Sinister,'' was more
immediately lovable, so if ``The Boy With the Arab Strap'' is your
introduction to the darkly romantic songs of Belle's primary
singer-songwriter Stuart Murdoch, expect to spend some time with
the album. The production here is expansive, with muted horns and
overdubbed guitars weaving a spell around painterly songs that deal
with 20-something stroke victims (``It Could Have Been a Brilliant
Career''), wasted time (``A Summer Wasting''), promises of fame
(``Seymour Stein'') and a reflective walk in the park (``Sleep the
Clock Around''). A quiet beauty. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
SOUL COUGHING/``El Oso'' (Slash/Warner Bros.)
</P>
<P>
   Like Beck and the Beastie Boys, New York's Soul Coughing has
always been inspired by the beats and wordplay of hip-hop but for
the first time, the quartet has cooked up the grooves to match. On
this third album, singer-guitarist M. Doughty and company have
clearly been soaking up Euro drum 'n' bass rhythms as well, as
evidenced by the cyber-production skills of Brit dance-music
maestro Optical on two doomy tracks. As always, though, it's down
to Doughty's wry lyrics and sardonic delivery on such winners as
``So Far I Have Not Found the Science'' and ``Circles'' that put
this quirky noise across. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
BOB DYLAN/``Live 1966: The `Royal Albert Hall' Concert (Bootleg
Series Vol. 4)'' (Columbia Legacy)
</P>
<P>
   The goon who shouted ``Judas!'' at the newly electrified Dylan
at a British venue more than 30 years ago didn't know it then, but
he was making rock history. That moment, replete with the angry
boos and hisses of hostile folk purists who couldn't stomach their
hero embracing an electric guitar and rock band, is captured here
along with Dylan's caustic retort: ``I don't believe you. You're a
liar.'' For more than a quarter-century, bootlegs of this
extraordinary gig have circulated, misnamed the Albert Hall concert
when it actually took place at Manchester's Free Trade Hall. In any
case, this superb two-CD document captures Dylan at the peak of his
powers, opening with a stirring solo acoustic set that includes
``She Belongs to Me,'' ``Fourth Time Around,'' ``Visions of
Johanna'' and a beautiful ``Desolation Row.'' The second disc
reveals Dylan and his backup group (later known as the Band)
scorching through ``Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues,'' ``Leopard-Skin
Pill-Box Hat,'' ``Ballad of a Thin Man'' and ``Like a Rolling
Stone,'' which comes after the angry exchange with the audience.
Terrific stuff that recalls a time when rock music had the power to
divide. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
SON VOLT/``Wide Swing Tremelo'' (Warner Bros.)
</P>
<P>
   Alt-country mainstays Son Volt seem to have embarked on a new
beginning with their third album. While the group's previous
release was mostly disappointing, ``Wide Swing Tremelo'' harkens
back to the quartet's eye-opening debut, ``Trace,'' with its weepy
pedal-steel, sagebrush-swaying acoustic guitars, well-crafted tunes
and leader Jay Farrar's rough, world-weary baritone. This time
around, the downbeat midtempo rockers are even more convincing and
hook-filled. At the heart of the matter, as always, are Farrar's
sublime vocals. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
ARETHA FRANKLIN/``You Grow Closer'' (Peacock/MCA)
</P>
<P>
   At the tender age of 16, the Queen of Soul was already a force
of nature. Here are Aretha's first gospel recordings, made as a
teen in the '50s at her father's church in Detroit. The strength in
her voice, the jaw-dropping delivery, her intuitive feel for the
blues on such standout cuts as ``While the Blood Runs Warm,''
``Yield Not to Temptation'' and ``Never Grow Old'' immediately
brings the listener to the Aretha of today. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
VARIOUS/``Rare on Air (Vol. 4)'' (Mammoth)
</P>
<P>
   Showcasing the intimacy and spontaneity of Santa Monica, Calif.,
public-radio KCRW-FM's studio, the latest volume in this popular
series highlights the familiar mix of established artists and
underground faves. Some of the best of the new crop includes the
six-minute opening track ``Cut Chemist Suite'' from popular club
act Ozomatli, a lovely ``Subterranean Homesick Alien'' by two
members of Radiohead, and a five-minute blast of vocal fireworks on
``So Real'' from the late Jeff Buckley. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
THE BAND/``Jubilation'' (River North Records)
</P>
<P>
   With just three orginal members left, the Band marks the 30th
anniversary of the release of their groundbreaking debut, ``Music
From Big Pink,'' by recording 11 new songs, plus cameos from Eric
Clapton and John Hiatt, in a converted Woodstock, N.Y., barn. Still
able to put across warm folk-rock sounds and ragged rhythms, the
Band manages to create a vibe that's both familiar and fresh.
Clapton's solo on ``Last Train to Memphis'' is relaxed in the
front-porch style of J.J. Cale while Hiatt shares the microphone
with Rick Danko on the sturdy ``Bound by Love'' In the end,
``Jubilation'' is so good you almost don't miss Robbie Robertson. 3
stars
</P>
<P>
   Fred Shuster &QR; 
 &QL; 
CAKE/``Prolonging the Magic'' (Capricorn)
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll, stripped of fashion, can still be engaging _ the
proof is in a slice of Sacramento's Cake. The catchy songs, crisp
yet raw production, clever and absurdist lyrics come mainly from
John McRea who delivers the best ironic, monotone vocals since
Flash &AMP; the Pan. Following the band's brilliant 1996 breakthrough
disc ``Fashion Nugget,'' this album's standouts include ``Mexico,''
``Sheep Go to Heaven'' and ``Never There'' _ as fine a rock tune as
you'll never hear on radio. If you're among the lucky few to have
tickets to Cake's sold-out Troubadour show Oct. 26, feel free to
gloat. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ James Hames &QR; 
 &QL; 
JACK SHELDON &AMP; RUSS TOMPKINS/ ``Class Act'' (Jadi)
</P>
<P>
   This recording pairs world-class musicians Sheldon (maybe best
known for his vocals on the animated ABC-TV Saturday morning
``Schoolhouse Rock'' shorts) on vocals and trumpet and Tompkins (a
20-year veteran of the ``Tonight Show'' orchestra) on piano.
Sheldon's voice brings a quiet resignation to the forlorn torch
songs here and Tompkins' tasty chops counterpoint delightfully. As
a duo, it's hard to tear into some of the standards here, so the
arrangements are suitably solemn. Although a heart-pounding swing
arrangement would improve the pace, the pure craftsmanship and
flourish are plenty. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   James Hames &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
