<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST GRADE MAY BE THE HARDEST FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With one hand holding ``There Was a Mouse'' aloft so students
can see the pictures, Angela Hodgdon settles her free hand in the
lap of the child seated next to her on the rug. The little girl has
been squirmy while Hodgdon reads. Now she smiles shyly and falls
silent, happy to have this connection to her teacher. In the next
seven minutes, there are 15 more times when Hodgdon needs to reach
out, literally or otherwise, to keep the 10 children in the circle
focused.
</P>
<P>
   For mid-October in a first-grade classroom, this isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the primary grades, first grade is the one that educators
typically say is hardest for children. One word sums up the reason
why: transitions.
</P>
<P>
   As she speaks, Hodgdon's class at Davis Elementary School in
Bedford, Mass., illustrates the point. It's time to stop drawing
and have a snack, and even though this is a desirable activity, it
brings a myriad concerns and uncertainties, from ``I'm not
finished!'' to ``Is it OK for me to have water?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from one activity to another is hard because the
structure falls down,'' says Hodgdon. ``Expectations aren't always
so clear. In snack, you can eat, drink, read, talk. `Well, what do
I want to do first?'And what about the drawing they weren't ready
to stop working on? Do they trust me enough yet to believe me when
I say there'll time for it tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Even trickier are the less obvious transitions, like going from
being a child whose mother walks you into the classroom to one who
takes the bus, or going from being a child who sees herself
primarily as a playmate to seeing herself as learner.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that children don't realize they are making this leap.
Indeed, they're so aware of it, they call first grade ``real''
school. That in itself speaks worlds about why the transition to
first grade can be so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great expectations for themselves,'' says early
childhood educator Amelia Klein of Wheelock College. When they
can't read a book the first week, or don't get homework, or can't
write as well as an older sibling, they are not just disappointed,
they feel as if they failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year in which children are aware of their
comparative ability,'' says early childhood educator Lilian Katz, a
professor at the University of Illinois and director of Educational
Resources Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   While children may begin to notice differences even at the age
of 3 _ ``She's taller,'' ``His skin is darker'' _ it's typically in
first grade that they notice differences based on achievement: ``He
can write his name and I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big thing,'' says Katz. ``It begins to set in place
a self-attribution of being a fast or slow learner.''
</P>
<P>
   Identifying yourself as a good or bad student can have
long-lasting implications, says Katz, even for the child who sees
himself as more competent than peers. ``That child may worry, `Will
it last?' `Maybe next time I won't be able to do this,''' says
Katz. ``The child who decides he isn't as smart as he should be
begins to give up: `I can never learn this.'''
</P>
<P>
   What mitigates most against destructive self-comparisons is an
environment in which teachers work to reduce competition, says
Katz. ``There are no posters that say `Best reader of the week' or
`Super spellers!' Any time you have trophies or prizes, you're
communicating the importance of outranking each other,'' she says.
``First grade is way too early for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz and early childhood educator Susan Andersen prefer
first-grade classrooms where all contributions are valued _ ``Ian
is a person who's good at spelling, Jane is someone who's good at
singing ...'' _ and where cooperation is expected: ``You're so good
at writing a `g.' Can you help Mary?''
</P>
<P>
   This also is the year when the gap between the characteristics
of the child and the expectations of the classroom is widest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical 6-year-old is active, curious, talkative, easily
distracted, hands on, exhuberant,'' says Andersen. ``The typical
first-grade classroom expects this child to follow directions, not
interrupt, sit quietly, raise hands.'' Andersen is a consultant to
the Iowa Department of Education and on the governing board of the
National Association for the Education of Young Children.
</P>
<P>
   The wise teacher, she says, brings children through the
transition slowly, building in flexibility and giving them
challenges that are within their grasp so they see success. In
Hodgdon's class, for instance, mornings are devoted to academics,
afternoons to art projects and free choice. Mornings, she expects
children to raise their hands and not to talk out of turn;
afternoons are less structured.
</P>
<P>
   ``In October, the afternoons look like kindergarten. By January,
they'll look like first grade,'' Hodgdon says.
</P>
<P>
   The last transition first graders are going through is a
social/emotional one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be accepted by the group and they see that to
stay connected, they need to make a contribution,'' says Klein.
They quickly learn what does and doesn't work but a child who sees
that pushing in line doesn't get you friends must weigh his need to
be liked against his need to be first in line.
</P>
<P>
   Some children obviously are more socially aware than others.
``Not all children notice or care that someone else can tie his
shoe, or wait his turn patiently, or follow two directions at
once,'' says Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   This is one more way in which teachers and parents need to be
sensitive to developmental differences. Andersen reminds parents
that first graders can vary widely in terms of competence levels,
including from one sibling to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect too much of them,'' she says, and don't be
worried if they seem to have lost some skills since September;
they'll regain them as they gain confidence in school.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgdon says first graders are more likely to be successful in
school when parents share observations and problems with teachers
and when we stay connected to the school. Klein says, ``It's a
major transition for them not to see you in the classroom the way
they did in kindergarten or preschool. You need to find other ways
to stay connected because that translates to them not only that you
care about them, but also that you place a value on school.''
</P>
<P>
   Because 6- and 7-year-olds are not able to identify their own
emotions, she urges parents to ask questions about school. The more
specific you are, the more likely you'll get into a conversation.
Not ``How was school?'' but ``How was gym?'' ``Did you like the
book in literature group today?''
</P>
<P>
   Although your child's end of the conversation may be a long,
rambling discourse, don't tune out. What she's feeling will be
embedded in the narrative: ``I never have time to finish what I
like.'' ``I'm afraid to go on the field trip.''
</P>
<P>
   It's mid-October and even though the children in Hodgdon's class
look more and more competent every day, she knows they are still
scared. Just last week, she asked them what was hard about first
grade. Their list was a reminder of just how much energy it takes
for them to get through the day:
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus. It's too loud and it gives me a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the rug (for circle time) and having to think about
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids on the rug (at circle time) who are too silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to stay in the lines when you write letters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being inside. I really want to get outside (to play).''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not (always) being first in line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much homework.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not enough homework.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be
reached via e-mail at meltz(AT)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
