<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-15 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S PUT LAUGHTER, SUNSHINE AND NUTRITION INTO LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm feeling inspired these days by Dr. Christiane Northrup, a
physician whose video, ``Women's Bodies, Women's Choices,'' is
startling in its challenge to many of the cultural norms that
govern this culture. In speaking about the ways a woman can improve
her chance of having a long and active life, she offers her
strategy for maintaining vibrant health.
</P>
<P>
   She's not talking about how to drag yourself out of bed and go
through the motions. Nor is she offering techniques for fighting
off exhaustion or reducing the stress of an intolerably harried
life. She's actually talking about the possibility that human
beings can live with vibrancy, or ``pulsating with vigor and
energy,'' as the dictionary puts it, from cradle to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Northrup suggests we build into our regimen in
order to become fully alive: 1.) Laughter and a sense of humor; 2.)
Sunshine and natural light; 3.) Nutritious food; 4.)  &UR; rr Clean air
and water; 5.) A fulfilling sex life; 6.) Uplifting relationships;
7.) Outdoor exercise; 8.) A satisfying living and work environment;
9.) Natural sleep and relaxation; 10.) Inspiring music; 11.)
Rhythmical dance.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a simple prescription. When you try to implement her
recommendations, it turns out to be a very complicated business.
</P>
<P>
   Take laughter. People hardly ever laugh alone. Even a recorded
laugh track isn't enough to do the trick. To laugh, we need friends
who take life lightly, co-workers who can see the humor in the
glummest situation, and we not only need to know them, we need to
be with them long and often enough to supply a medically beneficial
dose of snickers, chuckles, and peals. I suspect that women who
make time to laugh with friends spend far less time at the
drugstore filling their prescriptions for Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   In listing clean air and water, it's clear Northrup assumes
human health depends upon a healthy planet. Who can live a
wholesome life in a blighted setting? Yet, bizarrely, we act as if
we didn't know that our physical, as well as our mental, health
depends on an unspoiled environment. Even psychotherapists these
days are beginning to link our connection with nature with our
state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us now experiences in some way _ physically,
psychologically, economically, politically _ `the earth hurting,'''
writes clinical psychologist Sarah Conn, a lecturer at Harvard
Medical School. The therapist's task, she says in an essay called
``When the Earth Hurts, Who Responds?,'' is to hear the world
speaking through a patient's personal suffering and to help clients
develop an awareness of how that larger world is affecting them.
Tuning in emotionally, becoming better informed, and taking action
are the best ways, she believes, to overcome the denial, numbness,
confusion, and feelings of helplessness that beset so many of us.
</P>
<P>
   I also love the idea of a doctor insisting that we settle for
nothing less than ``uplifting relationships.'' What a great excuse
to avoid the aggravating, depressing, and demoralizing folks whose
feelings we're usually trying not to hurt. According to Northrup,
not only are these people no longer our obligation, they're a
hazard to our health.
</P>
<P>
   And no more feeling that a woman is ever obligated to go to bed
with a man who doesn't consider her happiness as important as his
own. Here's a line I'd love to hear used more often: ``Sorry, but
my doctor's forbidden me to engage in unfulfilling sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor exercise? Maybe Northrup is hoping that while we're
outside walking, running, or bicycling, the sight of a tree or a
bluejay will wake us up to the extraordinary beauty around us.
Perhaps she's trying to disengage us from our machines, if only for
a little while. Or perhaps, as we move in a realm of sun and wind
and sky, she's counting on our feeling protective toward this world
that nurtures us in every way.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad she threw in music and dance. One morning last week,
after spending an hour in aerobics class, pretending to be a
Rockette, I visited dear friends who always play tapes when they're
home. As we chatted, lovely music soothed and lifted my spirits. We
laughed and laughed. I rode my bike home.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't anyone ever tell me it could this much fun to take my
medicine?
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner is a Boston freelance writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
