<HEADLINE>
SKIRMISHES IN THE GREAT PATRIOTIC MILDEW WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the coming of autumn, and cool, dry (we hope)
weather, we can kiss the old mildew problem goodbye forever. Or at
least until next spring, when it starts all over again.
</P>
<P>
   We have treated our patios, decks, steps, siding, and roofs with
bleach and water or other mildew-killers, and things look pretty
good outdoors. Good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   Guess again, soldiers of the great patriotic mildew wars.
</P>
<P>
   The mildew may be gone from outdoors (too cold and too dry), but
it has just moved indoors, where conditions are ideal for the mold
spores to grow: warm and moist.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the mildew grow in familiar areas such as
bathrooms and kitchens but also in unexpected areas such as
closets, in trunks, even on walls and ceilings, particularly on
walls behind large bureaus or bedsteads.
</P>
<P>
   The mildew is usually black, but can come in virtually any
color, and smells ``creepy,'' like a crypt. And, people allergic to
it suffer that much more.
</P>
<P>
   But how can it happen in a nice, tight house that is heated in
winter? Ah, there is the clue: that nice, tight house. New houses
are tight, well sealed with vapor barriers and insulation, to keep
water vapor out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they can be too tight, allowing water vapor to build up
to critical concentrations, enough to condense on cool surfaces.
Water vapor is humidity in the air, invisible, except when it
appears as steam coming out of our teakettle or when you can see
your breath.
</P>
<P>
   This water vapor finds its way to cool surfaces: the toilet tank
and bowl, the kitchen sink, walls of closets, and walls behind
bureaus and bedsteads. The walls behind bureaus and bedsteads are
cool, cooler than the rest of the room.
</P>
<P>
   A house too tight is no reason to make it loose again; a tight
house retains heat. But again, the immediate solution is to
ventilate. Such ventilation will allow water vapor to escape
outdoors. Despite such ventilation (temporarily and for short times
in winter), there will be no significant loss of heat.
</P>
<P>
   Mildew spores, invisible seeds, really, are forever floating
around, ready to land on a hospitable surface and grow. And grow.
And grow.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes mildew appears on exterior walls and maybe ceilings,
even in corners, where the surfaces are cool.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the great patriotic indoor war on mildew, you
can kill the mildew by treating it with a solution of liquid
chlorine bleach and water; a 1 to 3 ratio is adequate. This
solution will not harm any painted or varnished surfaces, or hard
plastic, Corian, granite. It will bleach untreated wood, and will
ruin unfast dyed cloth, fabric, and upholstery. If you have to use
a bleach solution on such materials, start out with a 1 to 10
ratio, and make a test treatment to see if it will work safely or
not.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the first skirmish. Now comes the biggest battle:
keeping mildew away. The solution is simple, the execution more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Ventilate: Make sure there is good air circulation in affected
areas. Reduce moisture, mainly by ventilating.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the bathrooms, which are the most notorious places
for mildew. Install an exhaust fan, or make sure the window is open
during showers and other ablutions. No window? Then an exhaust fan,
exhausting to the outdoors (not indoors or into the attic), and use
it regularly and for long periods of time, enough to take the fog
off the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a special paint will help reduce the growth of mildew.
Zinsser makes what it calls Perma-White Mildew-Proof bathroom
paint, ``guaranteed to remain free of mildew for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a phenomenal guarantee, but all you can do it try it.
Zinsser says it will also stick to painted surfaces, and can be
custom-tinted to off-white or pastel shades. It is acrylic, and can
be cleaned up with water.
</P>
<P>
   Ventilation can also be applied to kitchens to keep down the
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Water vapor builds up in closets with closed doors; closets are
usually chilly, ergo condensation and mildew. Again, ventilate.
Keep the door open. If that does not appeal, install louvered
doors. Keeping a 100-watt bulb lit in the closet (keep it away from
flammables) will help dry out the closet and keep it warm enough to
prevent condensation.
</P>
<P>
   For areas behind bureaus and bedsteads, the only solution is to
pull out the furniture six or more inches from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   But the exterior walls and ceilings where mildew grows seem a
mystery: Why there? It's no mystery; those parts of walls and
ceilings are cool because of indequate insulation, maybe even no
insulation at all, or where, in walls, blown-in insulation may have
settled, leaving a gap at the tops of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms where the mildew occurs can be ventilated, but that is a
constant battle in our patriotic mildew war. A more permanent fix
is difficult: Insulation must be added.
</P>
<P>
   If the ceiling is under an attic floor, it might be a simple
matter to add insulation, or at least to make sure there are no
gaps in the insulation already there.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, ventilate, ventilate, ventilate. And wait'll
next year, when you can do it all over again outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Peter Hotton is a Globe columnist)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
