<HEADLINE>
LATEST PUBLISHING TREND IS TO GET TOUGH ON MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men Are Jerks'' and ``Let's Face it, Men are (AT)$$(NU)%/(CT)$''
are new books aimed at women who want to understand men, a
seemingly limitless audience because what women doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Labeling all men jerks and (AT)$$(NU)%?(CT)$ may seem harsh, but
publishing these days is a cutthroat business. These titles are
meant to grab the attention of buyers of relationship self-help
books, nearly all of whom are women.
</P>
<P>
   Look through the self-help shelves and there, alongside ``Women
Who Love Too Much'' and ``How to Make a Man Fall in Love With You''
are such titles as ``A Field Guide to Impossible Men,'' ``101 Lies
Men Tell Women,'' ``A Dog in Heat is a Hot Dog,'' and ``How to Dump
a Guy.'' Dayle Deanna Schwartz, author of ``All Men Are Jerks,''
says she thinks her title appeals to what many women are feeling.
``There's a ready audience who wants to hear this stuff,'' she
said. ``It's unfortunate, but if I'd called it `How to Find
Yourself,' no one would notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers hoping that Schwartz's book will be an antimale diatribe
will be disappointed. The complete title is ``All Men are Jerks
Until Proven Otherwise.'' In fact, ``How to Find Yourself'' would
have been a more appropriate title, because Schwartz's book
encourages women to concentrate on improving their own lives
instead of using all their energy trying to get a man. ``I believe,
if you want a man, get a life,'' she said. ``You have to make
yourself happy first.''
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Let's Face It, Men Are (AT)$$(NU)%/(CT)$'' isn't at
all misleading. The authors, psychologists Joseph W. Rock and Barry
L. Duncan, are extremely tough on (and very funny describing) their
own sex, writing about difficult men and offering women advice
about how to deal with them. The garbled word of the title stands
in for what Rock and Duncan refer to as ``the A epithet.'' Their
publisher, Health Communications, Inc., which published the
``Chicken Soup'' series, wanted them to remove the offending word
from the title.
</P>
<P>
   The authors learned from their experience with a previous book,
``Overcoming Relationship Impasses,'' which sold poorly. ``We had
such trouble trying to publicize that title,'' Rock said, from his
Ohio office. ``I used to joke that we should write a parody called,
`Let's Face It, Men are (A-epithets).'''
</P>
<P>
   Rock said whenever he mentioned the joke title to a woman, she'd
say one of three things, ``You're kidding,'' or ``Where can I buy
it?'' or ``I want to write a chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years both psychologists have treated many women in bad
relationships. ``It's usually the women who come in,'' Rock said.
``Women are so used to picking up the emotional slack, looking for
potential instead of looking at what's there. Taking blame. They're
much too easy on men. I get enraged listening to some of the stuff
they tell me. As a guy, I feel embarrassed for my gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock said he and Duncan don't think that all men are
(AT)$$(NU)%?(CT)$. ``But a disturbing percentage are,'' he said.
``Most men have it in them. My partner and I are fairly enlightened
people, but we've got it in us too, if we're not watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors have been promoting the book on the talk show
circuit, where they've been accused of male-bashing. Rock said,
``It's always a male talk-show host who says, `Men aren't like that
anymore. Men have changed; we're sensitive.' Well, maybe, but we're
still getting clients telling us these stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock says readers have to look hard to find positive references
to men in ``Let's Face It ...'' But when he and Duncan are asked,
as they often are, if they're being too hard on men, they have one
answer: ``Hell, no.''
</P>
<P>
   They may be part of a publishing trend. Carrie Lewis, publicity
director for Adams Media Corp., publishers of ``All Men Are
Jerks,'' says their spring list has a book titled ``Women are From
Venus, Men are From Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
