<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WATER-BOS &LR;      10-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYRICAL LESSONS ON ROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIND OVER WATER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lessons on Life from the Art of Rowing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Craig Lambert &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jaffe/Houghton Mifflin, 184 pp., $22 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first time I climbed into a racing shell, a friend's 26-foot
Van Dusen, I capsized within about 60 seconds, falling into the New
Hampshire lake I'd just finished swimming. This comically brief
sojourn and its upset accomplished three things. I had taken the
plunge awaiting every rower, albeit not for the last time. I'd
gotten a humbling notion of the sport's precision and difficulty.
And I'd managed five or six strokes _ enough to feel like a
dragonfly skimming the surface of the water, and to perceive, even
for a moment, that rowing might change my life.
</P>
<P>
   If that transient awareness sounds dramatic, I suspect it's a
fairly common phenomenon among novice rowers. What lesser
experience could make so many otherwise sensible people head for
the water at 6 a.m., waking to aching muscle groups they didn't
know they possessed, undeterred by any weather but ice or
lightning? Like any challenging sport, rowing (whether competitive
or recreational, whether single-oar sweeps with a crew or
individual, two-oar sculling) demands physical prowess, mental
focus, and sufficient social skill to abide by the rules _in this
case, of the coach, the crew, or the course. And as with any sport,
its rewards are both biological and psychological, a boon to muscle
mass as well as to confidence and well-being. But rowing seems to
give back something tenfold. Balanced somewhere between river and
sky, the rower has the chance to overtake the water by listening to
its counsel. The stroke, self-willed and self-propelled, can leave
the self behind.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Lambert, who knows all this firsthand, resonantly
describes the arcane universe of the sport in ``Mind Over Water,''
capturing its inner dimensions as well as its athletic trials.
After a brief but rigorous entry into the world of rowing as a
coxswain (or steersman) for Harvard's freshman crew in the
mid-1960s, he returned to it as a sweeps rower 20 years later. For
the past decade, he's rowed in single sculls on the Charles, where
he has encountered Olympian rowers; the terror of race traffic; and
_ best and hardest of all _ his own internal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The literature of rowing is scant indeed; David Halberstam's
``The Amateurs,'' which followed the 1984 Olympic trials, is
probably the best-known book on the subject (and now more than a
decade old). Part memoir and part ode to rowing, Lambert's work
brings to the field some of the rower's subjective experience: the
extraordinary mesh of mind and body in the natural world, the
intuitive grace that is the triumph of any great rower, the moment
_ I think of it as the lemur hang _ when the rower, suspended,
becomes a part of the boat's rhythmic glide.
</P>
<P>
   A versatile athlete through his 20s and 30s, Lambert began
rowing at 37; at the time, he had a doctorate in sociology, played
jazz and classical piano, and had just left the field of preventive
medicine to write full time (he's now an associate editor at
Harvard magazine). He brought this eclecticism of body and soul
with him to the river, and it's part of the sensibility of ``Mind
Over Water'': Lambert glides easily from the history of rowing (the
Greeks rowed three-tiered battleships, with 170 oarsmen) to the
torturous consequences of contemporary rowing machine trials (one
elite rower's thighs turned blue).
</P>
<P>
   He lovingly evokes the sweet synchronicity of a fast-moving
eight, where everything but the rowers' heartbeats (and maybe even
those) are in precise accord. He takes us into races through Tokyo
headwinds, to the dank and dreary indoor winter tanks at Harvard,
down the Charles in his own innocent attempt to compete in a double
at the 1986 Head of the Charles: ``By the one-mile mark we have a
firm grip on last place: the river is all ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert unabashedly waxes romantic about the magic of rowing,
but who can blame him? If a trouble spot exists in ``Mind Over
Water,'' it's one of metaphorical excess: rowing may be a microcosm
of balance, determination, and grace under pressure, but trying to
connect it to the rain forest or the human immune system is what a
coach might call a precarious reach. When Lambert simply writes
about the sport itself, he evokes the spare eloquence of an M.F.K.
Fisher: ``The stroke seat offers both anguish and glory.'' More
than once he brought chills to this reader, as in his memory of a
former crewmate who was blind _ an oarsman whose Labrador retriever
led him each day to the boat, where he then set the stroke for the
rest of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind Over Water'' is really a minor odyssey along the Charles
River itself, as well as the story of the clubs and characters who
belong there, from Community Rowing, founded 15 years ago in an
effort to democratize the sport, to the legendary Harry Parker, who
has brought far more glory than anguish to his Harvard crews in the
past three decades, and whose taciturn eloquence and grit epitomize
the sport. If there is a reluctant hero to this tale, it is Parker,
though he would surely eschew that stardom for the higher premise
of a well-manned boat, where a star could get a race into trouble.
Lambert has finished the course well in ``Mind Over Water,'' which
has the same attributes as the rowing he adores: precision, grace,
and total immersion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
