<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: `CLOCKWATCHERS'; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   4 Young Women Watch the Clock
</P>
<P>
   For a challenging little movie with good reviews but without a
lot of promotion, ``Clockwatchers'' has done quite well for itself
in theaters, where it has played for five months in about 80 cities
and earned more than $500,000 at the box office. Now it is time for
video.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which stars Parker Posey, Lisa Kudrow, Toni Collette
and Alanna Ubach, is a drily funny and disturbing look at four
young women squelching their promise and dreams as temporary office
workers. ``It's a very quiet movie, and will play well in a
person's home,'' said Jill Sprecher, the director. ``It will seem
more intimate if people are in a contemplative mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most filmmakers, Ms. Sprecher prefers her work on the big
screen, but she also appreciates video, for a variety of reasons.
``We're just happy for the video market because that helped us get
the movie out and shown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   From its first appearance at the 1997 Sundance Film Festival,
``Clockwatchers'' has been guided along the distribution path by
BMG, an independent company that specializes in small movies of
worth that are not picked up by larger independents like Miramax
and October. BMG, which will release the film on tape Oct. 27,
plans theater runs for its properties but it aims for home video.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, company and movie made a match, if not immediately
at Sundance. At first, the film's cast and subject generated a
pre-screening buzz among those anticipating a broad comedy along
the lines of ``9 to 5.'' But then ``Clockwatchers'' revealed a
split personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the screening, all the theatrical distributors were there
and because they were expecting a comedy, they were laughing their
heads off during the first half of the movie,'' Ms. Sprecher said.
While there are humorous moments, they aren't that humorous. ``In
the last half, the laughter died down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larger distributors passed on the film and so did smaller ones.
``Even independents typically expect something more mainstream,''
Ms. Sprecher said.
</P>
<P>
   In stepped BMG. ``Correct me if I'm wrong, but how many normal
people get to go to Sundance anymore? `` said BMG vice president
Mindy Pickard, who was attracted to ``Clockwatchers'' at the
festival and helped start the process that led to the film's sale
several months later. ``It's all industry types.'' Ms. Sprecher's
film, she added, was overhyped at Sundance. ``A whole frenzy thing
happens, so sometimes it's not so smart for some films to go
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among rank-and-file film enthusiasts at other festivals, Ms.
Pickard said, ``Clockwatchers'' caught hold. Having judged its
quarry accurately, BMG had a property it could put into theaters
and prepare properly for video. ``There's star power and Gen-X
appeal,'' she said. ``Also it's a serious effort by a filmmaker
with vision who has something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   One paradox, however. Among video dealers movies are as
categorized as they are at Sundance. ``For video, we're marketing
much more comedic,'' Ms. Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Hope Floats
</P>
<P>
   Seen cheerleading in a flashback, Sandra Bullock plays Birdee
Pruitt, who as everybody's high-school sweetheart rode on beds of
flowers made of toilet paper in sweet, little Smithville, Texas.
Later, though, life takes a chomp out of Birdee, and after her
husband cheats on her, she beats it back to Smithville for some
down-home guidance on such matters as divorce and single
motherhood. Aiming to dispense cheery succor, Forrest Whitaker's
film gets seriously over-cute in places but, Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times, still scores ``with a pajama-party intimacy
that can be disarming when it isn't overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $19.98. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dancer, Texas, Pop. 81
</P>
<P>
   For absolute Texas down-homeness, there's no beating Dancer,
where the widows besiege the lone widower with yummy Jell-O molds
and everybody packs the perfect little church for sermons decrying
the wages of lust. When four of the five graduating high-school
seniors announce that they're lighting out for Los Angeles,
skeptical townspeople start taking bets on how many of them will
chicken out and stay put in Dancer. Squirrel (Ethan Embry), after
all, has an alcoholic father to look after, and Keller (Breckin
Meyer) takes care of his grandfather. Terrell Lee (Peter Facinelli)
belongs in the oil business, and John (Eddie Mills) is a born
rancher. Though Tim McCanlies' film has a knowing eye for things
Texan, all gets smothered in ``a tone of saccharine folksiness''
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 95 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan and the Lost City
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Rice Burroughs' durable ape man (Casper Van Dien), a k a
John Clayton or Lord Greystoke, deserts England and impending
marriage to a put-out Jane (Jane March) for a foray back to his
homeland, which is being thoroughly plundered and pillaged by the
evil scholar and explorer Nigel Ravens (Steven Waddington). At
stake finally are the riches of the city of Opar, the cradle of
civilization no less. The old Saturday afternoon chestnut is still
``kid stuff and little more, but the old formula still works''
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $102.96. 84 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Hit
</P>
<P>
   The name of Hong Kong director John Woo is invoked often, but in
this case he's the executive producer of a film put in the hands of
another Hong Kong veteran, Che-Kirk Won. And a preposterous mess it
is, with Mark Wahlberg evoking some sympathy as Mel, a neurotic hit
man tied to treacherous colleagues who leave piles of corpses and
end up kidnapping their boss' goddaughter. Swilling patent medicine
to calm his stomach, Mel swims upstream in a ``high-concept,
low-reward hodgepodge'' (Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 91 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   THE TRIAL. ``Film,'' Orson Welles once told an interviewer,
``should not be a fully illustrated, all-talking, all-moving
version of a book, but should be itself.'' Managing striking
theatrical effects of its own, Welles' film, inspired by (he
rejected ``adapted from'') Franz Kafka's nightmare novel of
bureaucratic menace, stars Anthony Perkins as Joseph K, an
unlikable but innocent man who, over his increasingly desperate
protests, is convicted and finally executed by the state for a
crime that is never identified and he knows nothing about. The cast
includes Welles himself, Jeanne Moreau and Romy Schneider. Found in
a decrepit state, and by accident, the European-made film has been
restored by David Pierce and Milestone Film and Video. 1962. 129
minutes, with the original American trailer. $29.95. Information:
(800) 603-1104.
</P>
<P>
   MAN WITH A PLAN. Fred Tuttle's 94-year-old father needs $28,000
for a hip operation. Fred, a 73-year-old retired Vermont dairy
farmer who plays himself in John O'Brien's film, needs a job with a
six-figure salary and a dental plan. So he runs for Congress and
wins in a screen performance that earned Tuttle so much fame that
he actually won a real-life victory last month as the Republican
nominee for the U.S. Senate. (Never clarified, the Fred plan
apparently rests on being friendly, renewable, extraterrestrial and
dinky, whatever they mean.) 1996. Acorn. $19.95. 90 minutes. No
rating. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   YOU ARE WHAT YOU EAT. Tiny Tim warbles ``Danny Boy,'' ``Be My
Baby'' and ``I Got You Babe'' and other numbers on a tape from the
60's that includes selections by Jefferson Airplane, Frank Zappa,
Paul Butterfield, the Electric Flag and the Family Dog. 1998. Ivy.
$29.95. 75 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
