</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAGIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLOCK AND KIDMAN MAKE A `MAGIC' PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the days of Salem, the sultry Owens women have been called
witches. Feared, reviled, exiled and lusted after, the Owens
matriarchs have survived despite a curse cast over them by an
ancestor. Jilted by her lover, Sarah Owens promised that every man
an Owens woman loves will be doomed to an early death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sally Owens (Sandra Bullock) and her wild sister
Gillian (Nicole Kidman) are still feared by the inhabitants of the
small New England town where they live with their two spell-casting
aunts, Frances (Stockard Channing) and Jet (Dianne Wiest). Gillian
itches to see the world and runs off with the first man who comes
calling. Sally finds happiness at home, starting a business with
her husband and two young daughters. But things come to a boil
after hubby is mowed down by a truck and Gillian returns _ along
with an unwanted visitor _ her abusive, creepy boyfriend, Jimmy
(Goran Visnjic).
</P>
<P>
   After the sisters accidentally kill the woman-bashing punk with
an overdose of witchcraft, they bury him in the garden, but find he
just won't stay dead. It'll take all the strength and magic the
women can muster to break the old curse and rid the house of
Jimmy's hold over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical Magic'' contains strong ideas about female bonding
and a ``sisterhood is powerful'' notion that is sure to alienate
some viewers. But it might be the next candidate for a meeting
ground for women everywhere, much as the film, ``First Wives Club''
and the novel about the ``Ya Ya Sisterhood,'' proved to be.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that ``Practical Magic'' has a spellbinding
charm and that's mostly ensured by the chemistry and star-power of
the cast, as well as the fact that the film maintains a smart, even
wry sense of humor about itself.
</P>
<P>
   Director Griffin Dunne has a quirky eye and a fascination for
the darker side of life. His film, ``Addicted To Love,'' managed to
make black comedy out of stalking and ``Practical Magic'' has much
of the same twisted sense of humor. But he also has a wonderful
flair for the visual storytelling medium (the film was shot in the
San Juan Islands) and the camera work and special effects play a
strong part in the film's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the popular novel by Alice Hoffman, screenwriters Robin
Swicord, Akiva Goldman and Adam Brooks have scripted an engaging,
if not wholeheartedly original, story, though most of the credit
must go to the cast for making movie-star magic with ultimately
contrived material.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman has fun playing a wild card and she and Bullock shine as
sisters who have a bond so intense it's a blessing as well as a
curse. ``Practical Magic'' needs their gung-ho talent and charisma
to draw us in and they throw themselves into this cauldron of dark,
uncomfortable comedy with gusto, conjuring more screen magic than
the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   Practical Magic. Directed by Griffin Dunne. Written by Robin
Swicord, Akiva Goldman, Adam Brooks. Cast: Sandra Bullock, Nicole
Kidman, Aidan Quinn, Stockard Channing, Dianne Wiest. Warner Bros.
109 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual content, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
