<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     10-15 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOUGH TASK OF FILLING THE SHOES OF A LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Freeman might want to give Morris Smith a call.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, you may remember, was the Fidelity Investments money
manager who found out just how painful it could be to follow the
legendary Peter Lynch. Now it is Chuck Freeman's turn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.4l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Freeman spent 27 years as the understudy for superstar manager
John Neff at Vanguard Group's storied Windsor fund before taking
over in 1996 when Neff retired. Things went well at first, and
Windsor was the only big nonindex equity fund to beat the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 over his first seven quarters in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   But the roof has fallen in lately on the 54-year-old Freeman, a
partner at Boston's Wellington Management Co., which has long
managed the fund for Pennsylvania-based Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, a contrarian value investor, has trailed the index the
last four quarters, including a disasterous loss of 19.4 percent
last quarter. Over the last year, Windsor is down 23.2 percent
compared with a loss of 9.03 percent for all growth and income
funds monitored by Lipper Analytical Services. Windsor ranks 424 of
450 among all such funds over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the days before fund managers were followed as closely
as home-run hitters, someone like Neff could have a lousy year and
it was written off as the nature of the business. Neff, in fact,
had awful years in 1989 and 1990, and his numbers were fairly
mediocre his last few years. But that was then.
</P>
<P>
   Now the scrunity is far greater, the choices for investors
endless, and money far more mobile, thanks to the mutual fund
supermarkets, which have made switching funds as easy as a
telephone call. And The Chuck Freeman Watch has begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fund manager skates on thin ice,'' said Business Week this
month. The Wall Street Journal, and an on-line investment
publication, both ran stories suggesting Vanguard could consider
changing managers or going to a multimanager approach. ``When
there's bad performance for an extended period, you don't just
stand there. Sooner or later you've got to do something,'' the
Journal quoted Jack Bogle, Vanguard's founder, as saying after a
board meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard insists there are no such changes are in the cards.
John Brennan, Vanguard's chief executive, says Bogle's comments
were taken out of context and that Windsor is doing exactly what it
is supposed to do _ making gutsy bets against the market. ``The
board of directors is fully supportive of Chuck Freeman and his
team,'' Brennan said yesterday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say things haven't been ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman has found himself in just the wrong place in this
volatile market. Late last year, he badly underestimated the impact
of the Asian crisis and had too much of the fund invested in the
kind of commodity and cyclical stocks that got crushed. He was
light on the ``Nifty Fifty'' big-name stocks that have lead the
market and over-invested in small- and medium-capitalization
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Freeman noted yesterday in an interview, have been
``horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors yanked $1.7 billion from the fund in the first nine
months of the year, says Daniel P. Wiener, editor of the
Independent Advisor for Vanguard Investors, a newsletter in
Potomac, Md. The fund, which had $23 billion in assets in April,
was down to $17.1 billion at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been particularly stark compared with those of
Vanguard's Windsor II, a sister fund, which has been holding up
well in the downturn. That fund ranks 101 of 711 growth and income
funds over the last year and 35 of 450 funds over the last three
years, says Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard maintains the funds were never supposed to be clones of
each other, with Windsor II more diversified than its highly
concentrated older sibling. Still, says Freeman, ``they had just
the right portfolio for an economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman is standing by his contrarian picks. Windsor has three
times the weighting in commodity cyclicals like basic materials and
energy as the S&AMP;P 500. This is about as far away from indexing as
you can get; fully 35 percent of his portfolio isn't even included
in the S&AMP;P index.
</P>
<P>
   What Freeman is betting is that the US and European economies
are going to do a lot better than people think despite the problems
in Asia and Latin America and that a worldwide economic turnaround
is in the cards in the next 12 months. When that happens, Freeman
says, the market should broaden out and his cheap stocks should do
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a classical turning point,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That would suit those patient Vanguard executives just fine.
Wiener, the Vanguard newsletter editor, says Bogle's personal
Windsor holdings are down $450,000 this year; Brennan's holdings
are down $350,000 and five Vanguard executives on the board
together have lost $1.2 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman won't be exact, but says ``far and away the majority of
my worth'' is in his own fund. And he has been adding to his own
Windsor holdings, both in August and September. This is no easy
profit-sharing money either, he notes, but ``real money, cash
purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
