<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PEEPING AT NATURE, MAINE ALMOST HAS IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAR HARBOR, Maine _ Peeping at nature, perhaps the most popular
recreational activity, has its seasons, and except for alligators
in ditches such as off the Tamiami Highway in Florida, Maine has
them all.
</P>
<P>
   In spring, there is no place better to peep at moose than Maine,
better known as the great salad bowl of New England.
</P>
<P>
   The hardwood forests, especially where there's been
clear-cutting, are the perfect habitat for moose, which also like
to wander roadways, making moose-peeping so easy that the animals
are more dangerous than logging trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Maine is not the only Northern state where whale-peeping is a
commonplace summer activity, but it adds a strange-looking seabird
_ the puffin _ that inhabits a few small islands off the coast.
Boat trips from Bar Harbor to peep at whales and puffins are
usually packed as they head out to Petite Manan and Matinikus
Islands well into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the most common of the peeping sports is fall foliage, an
activity that grows by the year and ranges from a cruise in the old
Buick to a strenuous mountain hike or bike trip.
</P>
<P>
   Acadia National Park, with its central town of Bar Harbor, has
it all. It's a microcosm of the Northern outdoors _ ocean and
inland waterways, forest, beach, and mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain in question, Mount Cadillac, is only 1,500 feet,
which is more of a big, rocky hill. But from its summit last
Sunday, a ringingly clear day, the autumn tweed weave of orange,
red, and yellow stretched for miles to the blue distance where the
bulking shapes of Mount Washington and Mount Katahdin were in view.
</P>
<P>
   So if Cadillac is not Everest or K2 _ you won't need to bring
oxygen _ the climb is still exhilarating and right now at the
height of the foliage colors. It is the highest point on the
Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors to Acadia first make the 27-mile Park Loop Road
drive around Cadillac that begins at the visitor center just across
the bridge from the town of Ellsworth.
</P>
<P>
   For coastal hikers, several pathways run along the cliffbound
coast of the island, with walks from a couple of miles to full-day
hikes that take in such features as Sand Beach and the Otter Cliffs
where Thunder Hole performs. This is an amazing natural rock
formation where, at about three-quarter tide, the waves pound into
a long chasm in the cliff and explode with a roar into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The tamest walk is probably the Shore Path in Bar Harbor. Though
it gets crowded in the summer, the mile walk along the coast of
Frenchman Bay is one of Maine's many postcard settings.
</P>
<P>
   Still in operation is the 151-foot, five-masted schooner
Margaret Todd, which, with red sails billowing in a stiff northeast
wind, heels out among the whitecaps, out of sight behind Sheep
Porcupine Island.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the hiking breaks into two categories: easy, along
the 50 miles of carriage roads that crisscross Acadia; and
strenuous, walks up not only Cadillac but Acadia, Huguenaut,
Champlain, and Gorham. Of these, Acadia, about 3 1/2 hours, is the
best. The summit has spectacular views of the region in its flaming
autumnal colors, offshore islands, and a true fjord, Soames Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac also has great views and one's choice of challenge. The
rockface approach is tough, but the road is easier on the opposite
side. For those who don't want to walk, there is an auto road and
facilities at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the summit, there is a half-mile easy walk that swings a
360-degree view of the region from the Atlantic's highest
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   A few other hikes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Jordan Pond Bridges: a 2-mile walk of moderate challenge with
history of Acadia's carriage roads and stone bridges.
</P>
<P>
   -- Forests of Lilliput: 1 1/2 miles, rated moderate, it takes
walkers into a world of unique mosses, ferns, lichens, and fungi _
and also along the ancient shoreline by island's forest.
</P>
<P>
   -- Carriage roads offer any length walk, bike ride, horseback
ride. Some of these are restricted to foot only; others allow
various uses. All are marked and offer extremely easy access. Few
offer any challenge beyond easy walking, but trail maps are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor center or ranger stop at the park entrance is the
place to pick up maps and information about the entire park and its
hundreds of features.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
