<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIRLINES DRAWS THE LINE ON BULKY BAGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines travelers who like to lug lots of bulky stuff
with them on the plane had better think again.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing an industrywide trend of carry-on crackdowns, United
Airlines announced it will fit some airport security X-ray machines
with stainless steel templates to keep out bags that are too big to
be brought on board.
</P>
<P>
   Bags will have to fit through a 9- by 14-inch rectangle, United
spokeswoman Kristina Price said Wednesday. If necessary, bags can
be folded to make them fit.
</P>
<P>
   Bags that can't make it through must be checked. United will
have customer service representatives on hand to help at the
checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of months, United has had templates in Los Angeles.
On Nov. 1, the airline will begin using them at 38 more U.S.
airports, including Bush Intercontinental, where it has 27 daily
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Safety and cutting down on flight delays are among the reasons
for United's actions, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   When people drag oversized items on board and can't find room,
they end up having to get their bags checked. That may delay
takeoff. Also, she said, officials are concerned about items
tumbling out of bins onto people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, we feel this will really be a much smoother,
hassle-free experience for the customer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The templates, Price said, have generally been well-received by
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At the majority of airports where United installs the templates,
its passengers are the only ones to use the security checkpoints,
Price said. At checkpoints United shares with other airlines, the
equipment is going in only if the other carriers agree, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, United shares with US Airways, whose officials
couldn't reached for comment. US Airways has 11 daily departures
from Houston, according to the Houston Airport System.
</P>
<P>
   United is also spending about $10 million to improve its baggage
handling. That will go for more employees and new technology, Price
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a number of carriers began tackling the
carry-on issue by beefing up and more strongly enforcing policies.
Some began counting briefcases and laptop computers in their
carry-on limits.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines is testing a system similar to United's in a few
airports, including New York's La Guardia Airport, said Delta
spokeswoman Jackie Pate. Houston is not among them. Delta has not
made any plans to expand the templates beyond the test sites, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers, including Northwest Airlines, Southwest
Airlines, Trans World Airlines, American Airlines and Houston-based
Continental Airlines, said Wednesday they don't plan to install
such systems.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to carry-ons, Continental is going the other way
from United, said spokeswoman Julie Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting our efforts into accommodating our passengers
and their baggage,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Continental's new planes are coming with larger overhead storage
bins and some older planes are being retrofitted with larger bins,
she said. Continental does not count laptops or briefcases in its
carry-on limits.
</P>
<P>
   At Dallas-based Southwest, which kicked off its ``Don't be a
Bin &UR;  &LR; Hog'' campaign on Groundhog's Day in February, the company
tested a similar system to United's on the West Coast, said
spokeswoman Melanie Jones. But, she said, the carrier decided not
to go with United's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons, Jones said, is that Southwest wants to have
consistency at its airports. In places where it shares checkpoints
with other carriers, she said, they might not agree to install the
templates. Also, she said, the airline wants its employees _ not
security workers _ to deal with the issue of bags.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Worth-based American, spokesman Tim Smith said officials
are watching what United is doing with interest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
