<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ President Clinton, promising his
own intense involvement, threw the authority of the United States
behind a Middle East peace agreement Thursday, urging the Israeli
and Palestinian leaders to ``break the logjam'' and take the risks
required to provide new hope to their peoples. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Belgrade) _ NATO Secretary-General Solana and U.S.
Gen. Clark, supreme allied commander in Europe, travel to Belgrade
to sign agreements on Kosovo with the Milosevic government. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ENCYCLICAL (Rome) _ Denouncing the ``fateful separation''
of faith and reason in modern times, Pope John Paul II on Thursday
set out a Christian alternative to the dominant philosophies of the
20th century _ post-enlightenment rationalism, Marxism and
``postmodern'' nihilism. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The White House and congressional
leaders agreed Thursday on a $500 billion budget package that
completed the legislative record of the 105th Congress and defined
issues lawmakers will take before voters in little more than two
weeks. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ President Clinton only looked
dead. Even under the threat of impeachment, a president still
wields enormous power, as the budget negotiations concluded this
afternoon demonstrated. By John M. Broder.
</P>
