<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     10-15 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: REVISITING OZ 6 DECADES LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The song ``Over the Rainbow'' was almost cut. Judy
Garland was not the studio's choice, with some executives
preferring Shirley Temple or Deanna Durbin. One director after
another _ including King Vidor and George Cukor _ was replaced. The
film itself was highly expensive, for 1939, costing $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its original problems, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's ``Wizard
of Oz,'' directed by Victor Fleming, remains perhaps the most
inspired film musical ever. It is certainly the most enduring, with
a record 23 airings on network television.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of the movie's 60th anniversary, Warner
Brothers, which owns the rights, is re-releasing a restored version
around the nation at nearly 1,900 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The re-release, set for Nov. 6, will have state-of-the-art
technical improvements, including a remastered soundtrack and a
digitally restored picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've re-released any number of films _ `Giant,' `Blade
Runner,' `Wild Bunch,' `Streetcar Named Desire' _ with original
footage,'' said Barry Reardon, the distribution chief at Warner
Brothers. ``I knew the 60th anniversary of `The Wizard of Oz' was
coming up, and I thought: `Oh great, let's bring it back; there's a
whole generation of people under 25 who've never seen it in a
theater.' And a theater is the place to see the film.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, the studio held a test screening of the
restored film in a theater in the San Fernando Valley, and Reardon
called it a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers were actually coming up to thank us for re-releasing
the film,'' he said. ``How often does that happen?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is the quintessential American family film.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence in the lasting popularity of the film, which was
adapted from the classic children's novel by L. Frank Baum, is
underscored by the way Warner Brothers stores are stocking up
before the holidays on ``Wizard of Oz'' toys, trinkets, coffee mugs
and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Recently ``Wizard of Oz'' items sold unexpectedly strongly on
the QVC shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were shocked,'' Reardon said. ``They never dreamed they'd
sell this much merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Feiner, president of the optical effects division at
Pacific Title/Mirage, said the original black-and-white portions of
the film, depicting Dorothy's world in Kansas, had been destroyed
in a fire in the mid-1970s. Working with a copy of the print,
technicians spent more than nine months removing dirt and scratches
and correcting the images on computers, frame by frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aim was to restore the negative to its original condition
as if it just got out of the camera,'' Feiner said. ``We did
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The film stars a 16-year-old Judy Garland (above) as well as
Frank Morgan, Ray Bolger, Bert Lahr, Jack Haley, Billie Burke,
Margaret Hamilton, Charley Grapewin and ``The Munchkins.'' It was
nominated for six Academy Awards and won two _ for its original
score by Herbert Stothart and for best song, ``Over the Rainbow,''
by Harold Arlen and E.Y. Harburg.
</P>
<P>
   Though the song was cut out of several previews, Arthur Freed,
the associate producer, who later became MGM's foremost producer of
musicals, threatened to quit the project unless it remained in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The competition among films in 1939 was extraordinary. The year
is regarded as Hollywood's most glorious, and remains a sad
reminder of the current caliber of films: now it often takes an
effort to come up with five best picture choices for the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other movies released that year were ``Gone With the
Wind,'' ``Gunga Din,'' ``Wuthering Heights,'' ``Dark Victory,'' ``
Smith Goes to Washington,'' ``Of Mice and Men,'' ``The Women,''
``Stagecoach,'' ``Love Affair,'' ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,''
``Young Lincoln,'' ``Beau Geste'' and ``Babes in Arms,'' which also
starred Judy Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King Tale
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the release of the highly praised 1995 suspense
drama ``The Usual Suspects,'' Bryan Singer, the movie's director,
sent a copy to the novelist Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   Singer's aim was simple: He wanted to acquire the rights to a
King novella, ``Apt Pupil,'' about a perfectly normal high school
senior whose fascination with the Holocaust leads him into a
dangerous relationship with a man whom he believes to be a former
SS officer. (There was an aborted attempt to make the film in 1988
with Nicol Williamson and Rick Schroder).
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the novella when I was 19, and I knew, even back then,
that I wanted to make a movie out of it,'' said the 31-year-old
Singer (below left), who obtained the rights and whose film, ``Apt
Pupil,'' opens Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``What intrigued me most,'' he continued, ``was that this
terrible event that happened so many decades ago in Europe, this
evil, had manifested itself in this completely placid, suburban
Southern California world with this seemingly normal boy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It wasn't so much about Nazism or Fascism. It was
how people become infected with the purity of the power and the
horror of the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   King recently saw the film in New York and was pleased with it,
the director said.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Ian McKellen as the Nazi war criminal who has
been quietly living in hiding and Brad Renfro as the 16-year-old
boy at the top of his high school class who becomes fascinated with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those stories that dealt in a very intense way
with adolescent curiosity,'' Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Usual Suspects'' won two Academy Awards, for Kevin Spacey
as best supporting actor and for Christopher McQuarrie for best
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   After its unexpected success with critics, as well as at the box
office, Singer became one of the most sought-after young filmmakers
in town. He was offered huge sums to direct stars in some action
dramas, but decided to turn them down because of the poor quality
of the scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't find any material that was really inspiring,''
Singer said. ``I finally realized I should go with my gut in terms
of what interests me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has hardly turned his back on big-budget studio films. He
is now getting ready to make a high-tech film for 20th Century Fox,
``X-Men,'' which is based on the Marvel comic series. To prepare,
Singer, among other directors, visited the set of ``Titanic,'' also
from Fox, and conferred with its director, James Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   The new film may cost as much as $90 million. ``It's the biggest
Fox film since `Titanic,''' Singer said delightedly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   800-Pound Gorilla
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin was writing the script for ``The American
President'' through the night at the Four Seasons Hotel in Los
Angeles when, during breaks, he began watching ESPN's
``Sportscenter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living alone and I had `Sportscenter' on to keep me
company,'' the 37-year-old writer recalled. ``I actually wasn't an
avid sports fan, but it just seemed like a place that I'd want to
work, and I began creating this fantasy _ what was going on at ESPN
Sportscenter behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was ``Sports Night,'' a television program created by
Sorkin (above) for ABC about a late-night sports show. The show has
received strong reviews, but Sorkin is waiting to see if the
network, which has a 13-episode commitment, will opt for 9 more.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin, who also wrote the Broadway play ``A Few Good Men'' as
well as its film adaptation, has had a surprising journey to
television.
</P>
<P>
   `` `A Few Good Men' took me two years to write, and so did
`American President,''' he said. ``On television, you have a week
to write the script. You have to tell a story in 21 minutes and 15
seconds. The immediacy is wonderful. I finished a script last
night, and I start rehearsing it this morning. In movies and
theater, you write a joke and you don't hear a laugh for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is you're tired all the time and I live every day
in complete fear that I won't be able to write the next episode,''
Sorkin continued. ``It's always on my mind. When you're finished
with a movie, there's a period of basking in what you've done. Here
there's a period of two minutes, and you have to get started on the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin is also working on a film script, ``In the Ocean of
Storms,'' about a former Apollo astronaut whose life has unraveled,
as well as the book for a Broadway musical adaptation of the Paddy
Chayefsky's script for the film ``Marty.'' The show, with a musical
score by Charles Strouse and Lee Adams, is scheduled to star Jason
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Sorkin said, `` `Sports Night' is the 800-pound gorilla
in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I wish I could work more on each script. I'll often
look at a completed show and think, `Now I know how to write it.'
But you can't take it back. You can only learn from that show and
put it back in the next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
