<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN HEARST APPOINTED TO CALIFORNIA REAL ESTATE POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and chief executive
officer of The Hearst Corporation, announced Thursday that Stephen
T. Hearst has been named vice president and general manager of the
company's Sunical Land &AMP; Livestock division and San Francisco
Realties division.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is effective Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Sunical manages The Hearst Corporation's extensive ranching and
timber operations in California, including the historic 80,000-acre
ranch that surrounds the Hearst Castle; the 65,000-acre Jack ranch
and the company's timber holdings in northern California.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Realties division manages Hearst's commercial
real estate interests in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hearst succeeds A.J. ``Jack'' Cooke, who held these
positions for many years prior to his retirement earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 14 years, Stephen Hearst has been an executive with
the San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which operates the business and
printing aspects of the San Francisco Examiner and the San
Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, he has served as vice president of circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, he was vice president/circulation and information
systems and has held a variety of other posts within the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He previously worked for Hearst International Circulation
Distributors and the Los Angeles Herald Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Hearst has proven himself a highly competent executive
in every post he has held within the company's publishing
activities,'' Bennack said. ``His assumption of responsibility for
the ranching and real estate activities, which have been so much a
part of The Hearst Corporation's history, is an exciting step for
both him and the company. He will do a superb job.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hearst is a great-grandson of William Randolph Hearst,
who founded The Hearst Corporation. He is married and has a son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
