<SLUG> BC-NY-CANCER-MAP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO PROVIDE COUNTY-BY-COUNTY `CANCER MAPS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Responding to pressure, the state Health
Department will produce before the end of the year the first
``cancer maps'' showing the rate of the disease in each New York
county.
</P>
<P>
   Despite urging from cancer-awareness and environmental groups,
the maps may not reveal which neighborhoods have the highest cancer
rates, department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the project, the first of its kind in New York, is
to geographically pinpoint every reported cancer case. Because of
concerns about patient confidentiality and the chance of
statistical error, the maps will list cancer rates and types by
county but may not indicate the existence of clusters of cancer
cases, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, we're not looking to show dots on a
street,'' spokesman Robert Hinckley said. The cancer-mapping
project will eventually produce more detailed information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Marie Williams, president of the 400-member Cancer
Awareness Coalition based in New Paltz, disparaged the idea of maps
that don't have the geographic details.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't do it by Zip Code, it doesn't mean a whole
lot,'' Williams said Wednesday. ``When you disperse the numbers
over the area, you're missing the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists contend that knowing where high rates of cancer occur
would help identify potential environmental causes that would
explain the incidence of cancer. The groups suspect landfills,
contaminated drinking water, toxic waste sites and pesticides may
cause cancer in people living nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, lawmakers have supported grassroots efforts to
determine if cancer rates are linked to their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   But because cancer mapping is such an emotional and politically
charged undertaking, the Health Department said it must proceed
carefully to ensure that its information is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The state is drawing on outside experts for help. Three
scientists from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta, and a representative from the North American Association
of Cancer Registries in Sacramento, Calif., will arrive on Oct. 29
to advise on finding the best way to create the maps, said Health
Department spokeswoman Kristin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Health Commissioner Barbara DeBuono also is convening a
15-member advisory committee of scientists, academics and activists
to guide the development of the cancer maps, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that releasing raw cancer data corresponding to
individual Zip Codes would do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so rife with inaccuracies that any conclusions you draw
would be faulty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also holding up the project is its prime source of data. New
York's cancer registry, a list of every reported case of cancer in
the state that currently contains data only through 1995. Before
the maps are created, Smith said, the Health Department wants to
include the 1996 data.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has been frustration with the slow pace of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the department needs to move as quickly as humanly
possible to put all these pieces of the puzzle together,'' said
Martha McNeil, a spokeswoman for the American Cancer Society in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer rates have declined in recent years, but what many
activists say is a paucity of cancer data has given added meaning
to projects like cancer mapping.
</P>
<P>
   According to the cancer registry's 1994 data, the latest
available to the public, the rate of cancer occurring in men and
women in New York was below the national average, but mortality
rates for both sexes was slightly above the U.S. average.
</P>
</TEXT>
