<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE OTHER HALF LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Oct. 22)  
(gm) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am balanced on a stepladder in my son's second-grade
classroom, staple remover in one hand, taking down a back-to-school
bulletin board and putting up a fall-themed collage of pumpkins and
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   My 7-year-old is making a Chinese dragon, busily gluing, cutting
and drawing, and I nearly fall off the ladder trying to see if it's
coming together all right.
</P>
<P>
   School volunteering is a free ticket to spy on the world your
child inhabits daily, and I'm taking full advantage of my rare
bird's-eye view.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the perks of my new gig as a stay-at-home mom.
</P>
<P>
   Since switching to a part-time job a few months ago, I've
experienced how the other half lives: I sometimes go grocery
shopping on Monday afternoons or hit the park with a picnic lunch
on Tuesdays with my toddler.
</P>
<P>
   This is quite a switch for someone who used to rarely be home in
time for dinner during the week, shopped regularly after midnight
and crammed weekends full of all other chores, social commitments
and family activities.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that there isn't a downside.
</P>
<P>
   First, 2-year-olds can be quite cranky, especially when they are
coming down with chicken pox.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I'm expected to cook a lot more (never my strong suit). I
do the emergency vet trips, the waiting for service calls, the ``To
Do'' list by the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Try as I might, I can't justify dividing household chores 50-50
with my spouse anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, for someone who's easily distracted, being home is
not necessarily the best place to get work done. There's one
particular squirrel outside my office window who does kamikaze
dives from tree to tree just to make me look.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, I'm looking forward to setting the alarm,
showering, dressing up and driving in to an office where
Teletubbies, mashed bananas, tantrums and laundry are not on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I have a nagging suspicion I'm not very good at this
stay-at-home mom business yet.
</P>
<P>
   This was underscored by the unfortunate incident at Gymboree,
where Sarah slipped out and managed to pull a piece of equipment
down on her head.
</P>
<P>
   My fears of a skull fracture proved unwarranted, although she
did have a nasty black eye for a week or so. How did she get hurt
at Gymboree? friends asked me. I didn't even think that was
possible. Isn't everything padded?
</P>
<P>
   And today, while I was volunteering, I couldn't help but
straighten Adam's dragon when he brought it past me. (Even though,
I suspect, classroom volunteers are supposed to operate under the
same non-interference premise as Star Trek's Enterprise crew.)
</P>
<P>
   While I envisioned having lunch with Adam at school once a week
as a treat for him, I'm not sure it has worked out that way. I make
him eat his lunch, under threat of loss of Nintendo time.
Apparently, when I am not sitting beside him, he merely stares at
his tray for the entire half-hour, not wanting to disrupt the
symmetry of the food.
</P>
<P>
   During the worst weeks, I crave my full-time job like I used to
crave more time at home.
</P>
<P>
   But, during the best moments, when I can say yes to people who
call for help with the fund-raiser, or take the dog for a walk
before dinner, or decide to make spaghetti sauce from scratch, I
think this is the best of both worlds, and I am content.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus writes for the New York Times Regional
Newspapers. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
