<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-15 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HEIGHTS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HEIGHTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYDREAMS AND NIGHTMARES IN PBS' DARK `WUTHERING HEIGHTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Wyler's 1939 film version of ``Wuthering Heights''
stopped midway through Emily Bronte's novel, and a new, fuller
rendering on ``Masterpiece Theatre'' tends to legitimize the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie problem. The last patch of this latest ``Wuthering
Heights'' (Sunday on PBS) sputters and dwindles as Heathcliff
(Robert Cavanah) completes his torment over the death of Cathy
(Orla Brady). Some of the twists are also apt to confuse viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not to warn anyone away from Sunday's edgy, genuinely
disturbing adaptation of the 1847 classic.
</P>
<P>
   Produced for London Weekend Television, this version takes a
deep breath and rushes at you with a sort of gothic gust until it
eventually stalls. You'll go to bed Sunday night knowing you
haven't spent your evening watching electronic wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said for ``A Will of Their Own'' (Sunday and
Monday on NBC), a multigenerational potboiler that purports to do
for American women what ``Roots'' did for black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Will of Their Own'' is a tedious, didactic and sloppy
miniseries that exposes its star, Lea Thompson (``Caroline in the
City''), as a dramatic incompetent. Did I mention that it's a bad
TV show?
</P>
<P>
   Back to the moors. Introducing the one-parter, Russell Baker
observes that Bronte's novel ``often feels like the work of a
lonely young woman, mingling daydreams with nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have added that ``wuthering'' was a colloquialism
referring to the roar of a storm. Against the backdrop of a windy,
craggy landscape, the movie is a wild ride atop wuthering passions,
with love and hate in dangerous juxtaposition.
</P>
<P>
   You know the story. Liverpool urchin, Heathcliff, is adopted
into a rural family and forms a soul-mate attachment to his
``sister,'' Cathy.
</P>
<P>
   When they mature to adulthood, she confides to a servant that
she loves Heathcliff, but it would be degrading to marry him.
Instead she marries the refined Edgar Linton (Crispin
Bonham-Carter), setting up a whirlwind of obsession, revenge,
madness and death.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanah's Heathcliff is more astringent than Laurence Olivier's
because the new film's continuation of the story gives us
Heathcliff at his darkest. But it's a pungent, no-holds-barred
performance, in which Heathcliff's explosive emotions are sad,
sinister and vibrantly alive.
</P>
<P>
   Working from Neil McKay's script, director David Skynner conveys
a sense of wild animalism in the bond between Heathcliff and Cathy,
from their childhood romps on the moor to his pursuit of her,
literally, into the grave. It's as scary as it is romantic; it's
definitely a workout.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``A Will of Their Own,'' the miniseries has a hurried,
unfinished and cheapening veneer despite its pedigree. It's
produced by David Wolper (``Roots'') with his son Mark, and
scripted by a previous Peabody Award winner, Susan Nanus.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to examine the changing status of women in American
society from the 1890s to the 1980s through six female generations
of one fictional family. The idea is also to counterprogram the
World Series on Fox, because, presumably, male viewers are pounding
beer and watching baseball. It's network-think.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Will of Their Own'' is almost as subtle as a body slam. It
begins shipboard, with an Irish woman on her way to a new life in
America, giving an heirloom mirror to her daughter and saying, ``My
flame belongs to you now, lovey. Here, don't ever lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what happens in the next scene? Right, mom suffers a
serious head boink on the ship, and she's dead. Just as there's no
stray dialogue, there are no small, character-forming scenes. Every
action is portentous, every word is part of a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson comes along quickly as the third generation and the
focus of the program. She's Amanda Steward _ rebel, feminist,
nurse, famous photojournalist, mother, grandmother and, more than
once, selfish tyrant.
</P>
<P>
   It's an awful performance. Thompson might have some knack for
light comedy, but it obviously doesn't extend to heavy lifting.
She's all wide eyes, dimples and contortions. In a role that
demands much, she's got practically nothing to give.
</P>
<P>
   Using its characters like cardboard cutouts, ``A Will of Their
Own'' marches superficially through suffrage and suffering _ rape,
abortion, financial exploitation, legal discrimination, wife
beating and plain male piggishness.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Burstyn is on hand as Amanda's decidedly unliberated
paternal grandmother (``Head up, back straight, a woman glides when
she moves''). Faye Dunaway contributes one overcooked scene as
birth-control advocate Margaret Sanger. Sonia Braga also has one
scene as an actual personage, migrant farmworker organizer Jessie
Lopez de la Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The men stir most of the misery in the miniseries. Thomas Gibson
(``Dharma &AMP; Greg'') leads the way as the love of Amanda's life, who
fails to tell her he's married. Unlike most men in the miniseries,
though, he has a chance _ I'll leave it at that _ to redeem
himself.
</P>
<P>
   There's the germ of a powerful miniseries here. It just seems
there's not enough money, not enough care, not enough time, not
enough something. Certainly not enough raw talent in the lead role.
But it's a botched chance to do something right with a theme that's
a TV natural.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say sloppy? How about a switch in camera shot where Gibson
keeps talking though his mouth is closed? How about a character
whose Army cap is tucked into his epaulet in one camera angle but
not another?
</P>
<P>
   ``A Will of Their Own'' is five hours of wuthering
worthlessness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
