<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES: TONYS OUTLOOK; DESIGN AWARDS; CHRISTIAN SLATER;
`CORPUS CHRISTI' 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JESS McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Questions Get Early Start
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is eight more months until the Tony Awards, but a
few curious questions have already surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   First is how to classify ``Swan Lake,'' Matthew Bourne's
testosterone-driven take on the dance classic: Is it a new musical
or merely a ballet on Broadway? And what about the revamped
``Scarlet Pimpernel''? Will it be eligible for best new musical, or
best revival, which would have a sweet double meaning if the
rewrite boosts ticket sales?
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake'' producers have begun lobbying, this week inviting
some 1,500 Tony voters to the show. Producers are also likely to
ask the American Theater Wing, which administers the awards, to
consider the show for either best musical or a special achievement
award.
</P>
<P>
   At ``Pimpernel,'' producers said they would also pursue Tony
recognition, but probably as a revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were nominated for best musical last year, so that would
probably be out,'' said Tim Hawkins, the executive producer. ``But
this is such an unprecedented situation that I hope that it would
be a dialogue rather than us making requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Fool Moon,'' the Bill Irwin-David Shiner clown
comedy, which is being restaged next month at the Brooks Atkinson
Theater. Its strained relationship with the awards dates from its
original staging in 1993, when the producer James Freydberg asked
Tony administrators to consider the show for a special award,
maintaining that it was neither a play nor a musical.
</P>
<P>
   The administrators declined. But Freydberg says he will try for
a special award again this time. ``You can't get unless you ask,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Somlyo, the president of the American Theater Wing, said
that final decisions on eligibility lay with the awards' 24-member
administrative committee, which will consider the questions by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year there's going to be something that raises some
questions,'' Somlyo said. ``This year, it's just happening
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Awards for Design
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One awards ceremony attracting little controversy _
and little recognition _ are the Maharams.
</P>
<P>
   The what, you ask? The Maharams, the original name for what are
now blandly called the American Theater Wing Design Awards, are in
their 34th year and were named for Joseph Maharam, a supplier of
fabric for shows. The awards, voted on by a panel of critics, honor
work in scenic design, costumes, lighting and ``unusual effects.''
This year's winners were announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the awards unique is that nominees are selected from
Broadway, off-Broadway and off-off-Broadway shows and that each
category can have as many nominees as voters please. (The Tonys
allow a maximum of four nominees.)
</P>
<P>
   The wide-open field makes for some delicious David versus
Goliath races. In lighting design, for example, Andrew Hill, a
designer for ``Symphonie Fantastique,'' competed against Donald
Holder, a Tony winner for ``The Lion King.'' There were 11 other
nominees. The winners were Jules Fisher and Peggy Eisenhauer of
``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Underdogs fared badly. Other winners were Eugene Lee for scenic
design (``Ragtime'') and Julie Taymor for costumes (``Lion King'').
Ms. Taymor and Michael Curry also won for noteworthy effects.
</P>
<P>
   No Chain Saw Now
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's just about matinee time on a Wednesday, and
Christian Slater is standing in a dirty white tuxedo, holding a
chain saw and flashing his trademark smirk at a camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' said Slater later, taking a break from the photo shoot
for an upcoming film. ``You just don't get this type of experience
in theater.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 18 years since Slater last appeared on a Broadway
stage, in the musical ``Copperfield.'' In that time the 29-year-old
actor has appeared in more than 30 films, playing a wide variety of
rebels, outsiders and, yes, chain saw-wielding socialites.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is taking over as Clifford, the narrator of ``Side
Man,'' Warren Leight's drama about a son and his jazz-obsessed
father, which starts on Tuesday at the John Golden Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said he identified with the role. ``My father was an
actor and my mother was in casting, so I kind of have a feel for
this,'' he said. ``Clifford's this young guy who's just trying to
establish his own identity. I can relate.''
</P>
<P>
   Quiet Side of `Christi'
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid the din of protesters and supporters at Tuesday
night's opening of ``Corpus Christi,'' there were a few less
strident moments.
</P>
<P>
   At ``a quiet walk for the First Amendment,'' for example,
chatter was infectious. ``You get a bunch of actors together and
all they're going to do is talk, talk, talk,'' said Gareth Saxe, a
graduate acting student. ``I was studying lines for a while but
felt like I was being antisocial.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the street, where protesters prayed, George
Gordon, a part-time producer, was passing out fliers for ``The
Jeweler's Shop,'' described as ``a love story with family values.''
The play's author is Pope John Paul II, a former actor and
director, who wrote the script in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just offering an alternative,'' Gordon said. ``And this is
a good crowd to give it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ It could be a very Merry Christmas for the Donmar Warehouse.
The London-based theater will have two Broadway openings this
December. The first is ``Electra,'' a co-production with the
McCarter Theater in Princeton, N.J., due to open at the Barrymore
Theater on Dec. 3. Then, on Dec. 13, David Hare's ``Blue Room,''
starring Nicole Kidman, will open at the Cort Theater, fresh off a
sold-out run in London.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 1999 ``Encores!'' season at City Center will offer the
1937 musical ``Babes in Arms,'' by Rodgers and Hart, running Feb.
11 to 14; ``The Ziegfeld Follies of 1936,'' with lyrics by
Gershwin, on March 25 to 28, and ``Do Re Mi'' (1960), with lyrics
by Betty Comden and Adolph Green and music by Jule Styne, from May
6 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the brave few who haven't had enough of the presidential
scandal, New Dramatists is offering a reading of the complete
testimony of Monica Lewinsky on Wednesday. Information: (212)
757-6960.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
