<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITIZENS PAY MORE TO FEDS THAN THEY GET BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: ADDS the words ``released Thursday'' to second graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York is among the top 10 ``loser'' states where
residents pay more in federal taxes than they get back in federal
spending, according to a new Harvard University study.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Thursday, shows New Yorkers paying $785
more per capita in federal taxes in fiscal 1997 then they got back
in federal programs such as Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid and
defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who has for 22 years
released studies of the so-called ``balance of payments'' between
the states and the federal government, said New York is in ``near
desperate'' financial health and that its ``persistent balance of
payments deficit'' may be responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New York has to pay more attention to this than it has
done,'' Moynihan said in an interview after a Capitol Hill news
conference on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan added that New York's credit rating is the worst of any
state except Louisiana and that it has the third highest poverty
rate (20.5 percent) in the country. While it has the ninth highest
per-capita income ($27,119), it has the fourth highest
cost-of-living rate, making it a relatively wealthy state with a
large number of poor people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 states with the largest payments-to-benefits deficits
were mostly in the Northeast and the Great Lakes region, and they
had been on the list for six years, according to Jay H. Walder and
Herman B. Leonard, professors at Harvard University's John F.
Kennedy School of Government, who conducted the study.
</P>
<P>
   Besides New York, the states were Connecticut with a $2,272
deficit, New Jersey with $1,946, Illinois with $1,688, New
Hampshire with $1,419, Nevada with $1,413, Michigan with $1,383,
Minnesota with $1,325, Delaware with $1,030 and Wisconsin with
$965.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dave Camp, R-Mich., said, ``Clearly you don't want to be in
a situation where you're not receiving your fair share of federal
dollars.'' But he added that Michigan has a deficit largely because
three military bases, which had received federal funds, have closed
in the state in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   California had the 16th worst deficit with a per-capita loss in
fiscal 1997 of $366.
</P>
<P>
   Walder and Leonard noted that the movement of money between
Washington and the states generally leads to a redistribution of
funds from wealthier states to lower-income states.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico has consistently led the nation with the greatest per
capita balance of payments surplus. New Mexicans received $3,500
more per capita in federal programs in fiscal 1997 than they paid
in federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Other ``winner'' states receiving considerably more in federal
benefits than they contributed in federal taxes were North Dakota,
getting back $2,788 per capita, Virginia with a $2,648 per capita
surplus, West Virginia with $2,235, Mississippi with $2,234,
Arkansas with $2,019, Montana with $1,925, Hawaii with $1,788,
Maryland with $1,767 and Alaska with $1,603.
</P>
