<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS DAVIS RETAINS SLIM LEAD IN CALIFORNIA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic nominee for
governor in California, maintains a slight lead over Republican
challenger Dan Lungren, according to a poll released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was favored by 48 percent of those surveyed, the same
percentage of voters supporting him in three polls since July.
Lungren, the state attorney general, was backed by 42 percent of
those surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The closeness of the contest means the remaining undecided
voters are crucial to both candidates. In order to win, analysts
said, Davis must avoid controversy and Lungren must swap his
tough-on-crime agenda and start talking about education and other
issues to soften his conservative image.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it stays like this, Davis probably wins,'' said Del Ali,
senior vice president of Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research of
Columbia, Md., which conducted the poll from Oct. 11-13 for the San
Francisco Examiner and San Francisco's KTVU-TV. The survey of 820
likely California voters had a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The poll indicated a continued gender gap between the
candidates, with Davis more favored by women voters and Lungren
more favored by men.
</P>
<P>
   It also showed Davis capturing the liberal San Francisco Bay
area and urban Los Angeles, and Lungren leading in the more
conservative Central Valley and San Diego areas.
</P>
<P>
   And there appears to be a smaller-than-expected undecided group.
Just 10 percent of those surveyed were undecided, indicating that
voters made up their minds early in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The race is shaping up as a traditional fight between two
establishment candidates with the same educational and extended
backgrounds as public servants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the primary, a lot of people looked at the
candidates and made up their minds,'' said Mary Hughes, a
Democratic political consultant in San Francisco. ``I think people
got a sense of what was going on. And because there wasn't a
contested Republican primary, and as we get inside the three-week
window, Republicans are coming home to their candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren was unopposed in the June primary, but Davis faced a
tough fight against two other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Lungren campaign has not shied from its candidate's
conservative credentials, a strategy built on the belief that
integrity and making tough choices are more important to voters
than the actual issue positions.
</P>
<P>
   In one televised ad, Lungren looks into the camera and tells
voters he is opposed to abortion and that Davis is distorting his
record, a politically risky move in a state that is largely
sympathetic to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ali said Lungren must ``stop running stupid ads about his
abortion position when he is trying to attract soccer moms. That
saves some money for Gray, running those ads. And I know crime is
his issue, but he's got to start talking about education.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the Public Policy Institute of California
showed the majority of Californians surveyed listed education as
their priority.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Lungren has a tough task, because voters already may
know what Lungren and Davis feel about key issues such as abortion,
gun control, the environment and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few issues that are not already on the table,'' she
said. ``So it's not like we are all of a sudden going to discuss
their differences on guns, their differences on choice. ... People
have decided. You're fighting over a very small part of the
electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far too early to declare a successor to Republican Gov.
Pete Wilson, who is barred by law from seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you factor in the statistical error, it's really just a
slight lead (for Davis),'' said Barbara O'Connor, a professor at
the Center for California Studies at California State University in
Sacramento. ``You're talking about one or two voters per precinct,
statewide, and that is a very narrow margin. ... I think what's
happening now is the campaign is congealing, which is typical for
three weeks out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
